{"title_page": "Flora and fauna of Greenland", "text_new": "Although the gay of its area is covered by [[ice cap]]s inhospitable to most forms of life, [[Greenland]]'s terrain and waters support a wide variety of [[plant]] and [[animal]] species. The [[Northeast Greenland National Park|northeastern part of the country]] is the world's largest [[national park]]. The flora and fauna of Greenland are strongly susceptible to changes associated with [[climate change]].<ref name=\"times\">{{cite news|author=Sarah Lyall|date=28 October 2007|accessdate=1 May 2012|title=Warming Revives Flora and Fauna in Greenland|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/28/world/europe/28greenland.html?pagewanted=all}}</ref>\n \t\nThe image galleries below link to information related to the [[flora]] and [[fauna]] of [[Greenland]], including [[Latin]] [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomy]], [[Danish language|Danish]] translations, and links to articles in the [[:da:Forside|Danish Wikipedia]], which can be helpful when searching for more information.\n\n==Flora==\n{{further|List of flora of Greenland}}\n310 species of [[vascular plant]]s were said to be found in Greenland in 1911, including 15 [[endemism|endemic]] species. Although individual plants can be profuse in favourable situations, relatively few plant species tend to be represented in a given place. Except for in [[Qinngua Valley]], Greenland has no native forests,<ref name=\"brit1911\"/> although 9 stands of conifers had been cultivated by 2007.<ref name=\"times\"/>\n\nIn northern Greenland, the ground is covered with a carpet of mosses and low-lying shrubs such as [[Salix herbacea|dwarf willows]] and [[crowberry|crowberries]]. Flowering plants in the north include [[Stylophorum diphyllum|yellow poppy]], ''[[Pedicularis]]'', and ''[[Pyrola]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bay|first1=Christian|title=A phytogeographical study of the vascular plants of northern Greenland - north of 74\u00b000 northern latitude|journal=Meddelelser om Gr\u00f8nland|date=1992|volume=36|pages=1\u2013102}}</ref><ref name=\"brit1911\"/> Plant life in southern Greenland is more abundant, and certain plants, such as the [[Betula nana|dwarf birch]] and willow, may grow several feet high.\n\nThe only natural forest in Greenland is found in the [[Qinngua Valley]].  The forest consists of mainly of downy birch (''[[Betula pubescens]]'') and grey-leaf willow (''[[Salix glauca]]''), growing up to {{convert|7|\u2013|8|m|ft}} tall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wondermondo.com/Countries/NA/Greenland/Kujalleq/Qinngua.htm|title=Qinngua Valley|publisher=Wondermondo|date=2013-06-23}}, accessed 20 Jan 2015</ref>\n\nHorticulture shows a certain degree of success. Plants such as [[broccoli]], [[radish]]es, [[spinach]], [[leek]]s, [[lettuce]], [[turnip]]s, [[chervil]], [[potato]]es and [[parsley]] are grown up to considerable latitudes, while the [[Kujalleq|very south]] of the country also rears [[Astereae|asters]], ''[[Nemophila]]'', [[Reseda (plant)|mignonette]], [[rhubarb]], [[sorrel]] and [[carrot]]s.<ref name=\"brit1911\"/> Over the decade to 2007, the growing season lengthened by as much as three weeks.<ref name=\"times\"/>\n\nIn the 13th-century ''[[Konungs skuggsj\u00e1]] (King's mirror)'', it is stated that the old Norsemen tried in vain to raise barley.<ref name=\"brit1911\"/>  \n\nRecent research from archaeological digs on Greenland by the National Museum in Copenhagen discovered barley grains and concluded that that the Vikings were able to grow barley. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sciencenordic.com/agriculture-archaeology-denmark/vikings-grew-barley-in-greenland/1447746|title=Vikings grew barley in Greenland|last=Hildebr|first=Sybille|last2=t|date=2012-02-03|website=sciencenordic.com|language=no|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Vaccinium uliginosum fruit.jpg|[[Bog Bilberry]] (Arctic Blueberry)<br />''Vaccinium uliginosum''<br />Kigutaarnat nagguii / moseb\u00f8lle / bl\u00e5b\u00e6r<br />[[:kl:Kigutaarnat|Kigutaarnat]], [[:da:Bl\u00e5b\u00e6r|Bl\u00e5b\u00e6r]]\n\nImage:Vaccinium vitis-idaea 20060824 003.jpg|[[Vaccinium vitis-idaea|Cowberry]]<br />''Vaccinium vitis-idaea''<br />kimmernat / tytteb\u00e6r<br />[[:kl:Kimmernat|Kimmernat]], [[:da:Tytteb\u00e6r|Tytteb\u00e6r]]\n\nImage:Alpine bearberry in Varrio Nature Reserve, Finland.jpg|[[Alpine bearberry]]<br />''Arctostaphylos alpina''<br />bjerg melb\u00e6rris<br />[[:da:Melb\u00e6rris|Melb\u00e6rris]]\n\nImage:Jun_com_cones.jpg|[[Juniper berry]]<br />''Alpine Juniper''<br />eneb\u00e6r<br />[[:kl:Kakillarnaq|Kakillarnaq; Paarnaqulluk]], [[:da:Eneb\u00e6r (Juniperus)|Eneb\u00e6r]]\n\nImage:Black crowberry.jpg|[[Crowberry]]<br />''Empetrum hermaphroditum''<br />paarnat / sorteb\u00e6r / revling<br />[[:kl:Paarnat|Paarnat]], [[:da:Almindelig Revling|Almindelig Revling]]\n\nImage:Arctic cottongrass, Inuvik, NT.jpg|[[Arctic Cottongrass]]<br />''Eriophorum scheuchzeri''<br />ukaliusaq / polar k\u00e6ruld<br />[[:da:Ukaliusaq|Ukaliusaq]], [[:da:K\u00e6ruld|K\u00e6ruld]]\n\nImage:Gew\u00f6hnlicher L\u00f6wenzahn Taraxacum officinale agg. Wiese.jpg|[[Dandelion]]<br />''Taraxacum lacerum''<br />inneruulaq / asorut / seqiniusaq / m\u00e6lkeb\u00f8tte<br />[[:kl:Inneruulaq|Inneruulaq; Asorut; Seqiniusaq]], [[:da:M\u00e6lkeb\u00f8tte|M\u00e6lkeb\u00f8tte]]\n\nImage:Koehler1887-GardenAngelica.jpg|[[Garden angelica]]<br />''Angelica archangelica''<br />kuanneq / kvan<br />[[:kl:Kuanneq|Kuanneq]], [[:da:Kvan|Kvan]]\n\nImage:Cladonia rangiferina.jpg|[[Cup Lichen]]<br />''[[Cladonia borealis]]'' Stenroos<br />orsuaasat ermusingasut /rensdyrlav<br /> [[:kl:Orsuaasat ermusingasut|Orsuaasat ermusingasut]], [[:da:B\u00e6gerlav-familien|B\u00e6gerlav-familien]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Fauna==\n{{further|List of mammals of Greenland|List of birds of Greenland}}\n===Land mammals===\nAmong the large land mammals are the [[muskox|musk ox]], the [[Reindeer|caribou]]<ref name=Cuyler>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.7557/2.27.4.347| title = West Greenland caribou explosion: What happened? What about the future?| journal = Rangifer| volume = 27| issue = 4| year = 2007| last1 = Cuyler | first1 = C.| page=219| doi-access = free}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n|title=Population genetics of the native caribou (Rangifer tarandus groenlandicus) and the semi-domestic reindeer (Rangifer tarandus tarandus) in Southwestern Greenland: Evidence of introgression\n|journal=Conservation Genetics |volume=3 |issue=4 |pages=401\u2013409 |doi=10.1023/A:1020523303815\n|year = 2002|last1 = Jepsen|first1 = B.I.|last2=Siegismund |first2=H.R. |last3=Fredholm |first3=M. }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n|url=http://agris.fao.org/agris-search/search.do?recordID=XE8420927\n|title=Feeding ecology of the West Greenland caribou (Rangifer tarandus groenlandicus) in the Sisimiut-Kangerlussuaq region [vegetation, food selection, forage quality, rumen samples, chemical analysis, migration]  [1984]\n|journal=Danish Review of Game Biology (Denmark)\n|accessdate=April 27, 2018\n|year=1984\n|last1=Thing\n|first1=H.\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.natur.gl/en/birds-and-mammals/terrestrial-mammals/caribou-reindeer/\n|title=Caribou\n|accessdate=April 27, 2018\n|publisher=[[Greenland Institute of Natural Resources]] }}</ref>, the [[polar bear]] and the white [[Arctic wolf]]. Other familiar mammals in Greenland include the [[Arctic hare]], [[northern collared lemming|collared lemming]], [[stoat|ermine]] and [[Arctic fox]].<ref name=\"brit1911\"/> [[Reindeer hunting in Greenland|Caribou hunting]] is of considerable cultural importance to the people of Greenland.\n\nDomesticated land mammals include [[dog]]s, which were introduced by the [[Inuit]], as well as such European-introduced species as [[goat]]s, [[Greenlandic sheep]], [[ox]]en and [[Domestic pig|pig]]s, which are raised in modest numbers in [[Kujalleq|the south]].<ref name=\"brit1911\"/>  \n\n<gallery>\nFile:Caribou.jpg|[[Barren-ground caribou]]<br />''Rangifer tarandus groenlandicus''<br />[[:da:rensdyr|rensdyr]] / ren\nFile:Muskus.jpg|[[Muskox]]<br />''Ovibos moschatus''<br />[[:da:moskusokse|moskusokse]]\nFile:Polar bear Olsen, Dave.jpg|[[Polar bear]]<br />''Ursus maritimus''<br />[[:da:isbj\u00f8rn|isbj\u00f8rn]]\nFile:Polarwolf004.jpg|[[Greenland wolf]]<br />''Canis lupus orion''<br />[[:da:ulv|gr\u00f8nland ulv]]\nFile:Eisfuchscele4.jpg|Greenland [[Arctic fox]]<br />''Vulpes lagopus foragorapusis''<br />[[:da:polarr\u00e6v|polarr\u00e6v]]\nFile:Polarhase 2 1997-08-04.jpg|Greenland [[Arctic hare]]<br />''Lepus arcticus groenlandicus''<br />[[:da:snehare|snehare]]\nFile:Lemming (1).jpg|[[Northern collared lemming]]<br />''Dicrostonyx groenlandicus''<br />[[:da:lemming|lemming]]\nFile:Kuupik Kleist, Regeringschef, Gronland talar vid Nordiska radet session i Stockholm 2009.jpg|[[Human]]<br />''Homo sapiens''<br />[[:da:menneske|menneske]]\n</gallery>\n\n===Marine mammals===\nAs many as two million seals are estimated to inhabit Greenland's coasts;<ref name=\"guide\"/> species include the [[hooded seal]] (''Cystophora cristata'') as well as the [[grey seal]] (''Halichoerus grypus'').<ref name=\"brit1911\"/> [[Whale]]s frequently pass very close to Greenlandic shores in the late summer and early autumn. Species represented include the [[beluga whale]], [[blue whale]], [[bowhead whale|Greenland whale]], [[fin whale]], [[humpback whale]], [[minke whale]], [[narwhal]], [[pilot whale]], [[sperm whale]].<ref name=\"guide\">{{cite web|url=http://www.greenland-guide.gl/animal_life.htm|title=Animal life in Greenland &ndash; an introduction by the tourist board|website=Greenland Guide|publisher=Narsaq Tourist Office|accessdate=1 May 2012|date=n.d.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427231950/http://www.greenland-guide.gl/animal_life.htm|archive-date=27 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Whaling]] was formerly a major industry in Greenland; by the turn of the 20th century, however, the [[right whale]] population was so depleted that the industry was in deep decline.<ref name=\"brit1911\"/> [[Walrus]]es are to be found primarily in the north and east of the country;<ref name=\"guide\"/> like narwhal, they have at times suffered from overhunting for their tusks.\n<gallery>\nImage:Narwal.jpg|[[Narwhal]]<br />''Monodon monoceros''<br />[[:da:narhval|narhval]]\n\nImage:Humpback_Whale_underwater_shot.jpg|[[Humpback whale]]<br />''Megaptera novaeangliae''<br />[[:da:pukkelhval|pukkelhval]]\n\nImage:Killerwhales_jumping.jpg|[[Orca]]<br />''Orcinus orca''<br />[[:da:sp\u00e6khugger|sp\u00e6khugger]]\n\nImage:Phoca hispida.jpg|[[Ringed seal]]<br />''Phoca hispida''<br />[[:da:rings\u00e6l|rings\u00e6l]]\n\n<!-- Missing image removed: Image:Cystophora cristata.jpg|[[Hooded seal]]<br />''Cystophora cristata''<br />[[:da:klapmyds|klapmyds]] -->\n\nImage:Phoca groenlandica.jpg|[[Harp seal]]<br />''Phoca groenlandica''<br />[[:da:gr\u00f8nlandss\u00e6l|gr\u00f8nlandss\u00e6l]]\n\nImage:Seehund2cele4.jpg|[[Common seal]]<br />''Phoca vitulina''<br />[[:da:sp\u00e6ttet s\u00e6l|sp\u00e6ttet s\u00e6l]]\n</gallery>\n\n===Birds===\nAs of 1911, 61 species of birds were known to breed in Greenland.<ref name=\"brit1911\">\"Greenland\". ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'', Eleventh Edition.</ref> Certain birds such as the [[common eider|eider duck]], [[guillemot]] and [[Lagopus|ptarmigan]] are often hunted for food in the winter.\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Raichou 01.JPG|[[Rock ptarmigan]]<br />''Lagopus muta''<br />rype<br />[[:da:Skovh\u00f8ns|Skovh\u00f8ns]]\n\nImage:Raven croak.jpg|[[Common raven|Raven]]<br />''Corvus corax''<br />[[:da:ravn|ravn]]\n\nImage:Eagle_In_Flight_2004-09-01.jpeg|[[White-tailed eagle|White-tailed sea eagle]]<br />''Haliaeetus albicilla''<br />[[:da:hav\u00f8rn|hav\u00f8rn]]\n\nImage:Falco peregrinus - 01.jpg|[[Peregrine falcon]]<br />''Falco peregrinus''<br />[[:da:vandrefalk|vandrefalk]]\n\nImage:Falco-rusticolus.jpg|[[Gyrfalcon]]<br />''Falco rusticolus''<br />[[:da:jagtfalk|jagtfalk]]\n\nImage:Harfang en vol 2.jpg|[[Snowy owl]]<br />''Bubo scandiacus''<br />[[:da:sneugle|sneugle]]\n\nImage:Oenanthe oenanthe 01 II.jpg|[[Northern wheatear]]<br />''Oenanthe oenanthe''<br />[[:da:stenpikker|stenpikker]]\n\nImage:Somateria mollissima male female.jpg|[[Common eider]]<br />''Somateria mollissima''<br />[[:da:ederfugl|ederfugl]]\n\nImage:AlleAlle_2.jpg|[[Little auk]]<br />''Alle alle''<br />[[:da:s\u00f8konge|s\u00f8konge]]\n\nImage:Plectrophenax_nivalis1.jpg|[[Snow bunting]]<br />''Plectrophenax nivalis''<br />[[:da:snespurv|snespurv]]\n\nImage:Phalacrocorax_carbo02.jpg|[[Great cormorant]]<br />''Phalacrocorax carbo''<br />[[:da:skarv|skarv]]\n\nImage:Larus hyperboreus1.jpg|[[Glaucous gull]]<br />''Larus hyperboreus''<br />[[:da:gr\u00e5m\u00e5ge|gr\u00e5m\u00e5ge]]\n\nImage:Larus-glaucoides-002.jpg|[[Iceland gull]]<br />''Larus glaucoides''<br />[[:da:hvidvinget m\u00e5ge|hvidvinget m\u00e5ge]]\n\nImage:Fulmarus_glacialis_on_cliff.jpg|[[Northern fulmar]]<br />''Fulmarus glacialis''<br />[[:da:mallemuk|mallemuk]]\n\nImage:RedNeckedPhalaropeIceland2006.jpg|[[Red-necked phalarope]]<br />''Phalaropus lobatus''<br />[[:da:odinshane|odinshane]]\n\nImage:Mergus_serrator.jpg|[[Red-breasted merganser]]<br />''Mergus serrator''<br />[[:da:toppet skallesluger|toppet skallesluger]]\n\nImage:RedthroatedLoon23.jpg|[[Red-throated diver]]<br />''Gavia stellata''<br />[[:da:r\u00f8dstrubet lom|r\u00f8dstrubet lom]]\n\nImage:Common Loon.jpg|[[Great northern diver]]<br />''Gavia immer''<br />[[:da:islom|islom]]\n\nImage:Long-tailed-duck.jpg|[[Long-tailed duck]] (male)<br />''Clangula hyemalis''<br />[[:da:havlit|havlit]]\n\nImage:Puffin2.jpg|[[Atlantic puffin]]<br />''Fratercula arctica''<br />[[:da:lunde|lunde]]\n</gallery>\n\n===Fish===\nOf the many species of fish inhabiting Greenland's waters, several have been of economic importance, including [[cod]], [[caplin]], [[halibut]], [[Sebastes|rockfish]], [[Cyclopterus lumpus|''nipisak'']] (''Cycloperteus lumpus'') and [[sea trout]]. The [[Greenland shark]] is used for the oil in its liver, as well as fermented and eaten as [[h\u00e1karl]], a local delicacy.\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Atlantic_cod.jpg|[[Atlantic cod]]<br />''Gadus ogac''<br />[[:da:torsk|torsk]]\n\nImage:Salmo_salar-Atlantic_Salmon-Atlanterhavsparken_Norway.JPG|[[Atlantic salmon]]<br />''Salmo salar''<br />[[:da:laks|laks]]\n\nImage:Salvelinusalpinus.jpg|[[Arctic char]]<br />''Salvelinus alpinus''<br />[[:da:fjeld\u00f8rred|fjeld\u00f8rred]]\n\nImage:Fiorello_LaGuardia_with_halibut.jpg|[[Halibut]]<br />''Hippoglossus hippoglossus''<br />[[:da:helleflynder|helleflynder]]\n\nImage:Reinhardtius_hippoglossoides.jpg|[[Greenland halibut]]<br />''Reinhardtius hippoglossoides''<br />[[:da:hellefisk|hellefisk]]\n\nImage:Rose_fish.jpg|[[Rose fish]]<br />''Sebastes marinus''<br />[[:da:r\u00f8dfisk|r\u00f8dfisk]]\n\nImage:Seewolf.JPG|[[Seawolf (fish)|Seawolf]]<br />''Anarhichas lupus''<br />[[:da:havkat|havkat]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n; Fauna\n* [[List of mammals of Nunavut]]\n* [[List of Nunavut birds]]\n\n; Flora\n* [[List of Canadian plants by family]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Greenland topics}}\n\n[[Category:Fauna of Greenland| 01]]\n[[Category:Flora of Greenland| 01]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Arctic|*Greenland]]\n[[Category:Arctic land animals|*Greenland]]\n[[Category:Birds of Greenland|*]]\n[[Category:Biota of archipelagoes]]\n", "text_old": "Although the bulk of its area is covered by [[ice cap]]s inhospitable to most forms of life, [[Greenland]]'s terrain and waters support a wide variety of [[plant]] and [[animal]] species. The [[Northeast Greenland National Park|northeastern part of the country]] is the world's largest [[national park]]. The flora and fauna of Greenland are strongly susceptible to changes associated with [[climate change]].<ref name=\"times\">{{cite news|author=Sarah Lyall|date=28 October 2007|accessdate=1 May 2012|title=Warming Revives Flora and Fauna in Greenland|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/28/world/europe/28greenland.html?pagewanted=all}}</ref>\n \t\nThe image galleries below link to information related to the [[flora]] and [[fauna]] of [[Greenland]], including [[Latin]] [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomy]], [[Danish language|Danish]] translations, and links to articles in the [[:da:Forside|Danish Wikipedia]], which can be helpful when searching for more information.\n\n==Flora==\n{{further|List of flora of Greenland}}\n310 species of [[vascular plant]]s were said to be found in Greenland in 1911, including 15 [[endemism|endemic]] species. Although individual plants can be profuse in favourable situations, relatively few plant species tend to be represented in a given place. Except for in [[Qinngua Valley]], Greenland has no native forests,<ref name=\"brit1911\"/> although 9 stands of conifers had been cultivated by 2007.<ref name=\"times\"/>\n\nIn northern Greenland, the ground is covered with a carpet of mosses and low-lying shrubs such as [[Salix herbacea|dwarf willows]] and [[crowberry|crowberries]]. Flowering plants in the north include [[Stylophorum diphyllum|yellow poppy]], ''[[Pedicularis]]'', and ''[[Pyrola]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bay|first1=Christian|title=A phytogeographical study of the vascular plants of northern Greenland - north of 74\u00b000 northern latitude|journal=Meddelelser om Gr\u00f8nland|date=1992|volume=36|pages=1\u2013102}}</ref><ref name=\"brit1911\"/> Plant life in southern Greenland is more abundant, and certain plants, such as the [[Betula nana|dwarf birch]] and willow, may grow several feet high.\n\nThe only natural forest in Greenland is found in the [[Qinngua Valley]].  The forest consists of mainly of downy birch (''[[Betula pubescens]]'') and grey-leaf willow (''[[Salix glauca]]''), growing up to {{convert|7|\u2013|8|m|ft}} tall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wondermondo.com/Countries/NA/Greenland/Kujalleq/Qinngua.htm|title=Qinngua Valley|publisher=Wondermondo|date=2013-06-23}}, accessed 20 Jan 2015</ref>\n\nHorticulture shows a certain degree of success. Plants such as [[broccoli]], [[radish]]es, [[spinach]], [[leek]]s, [[lettuce]], [[turnip]]s, [[chervil]], [[potato]]es and [[parsley]] are grown up to considerable latitudes, while the [[Kujalleq|very south]] of the country also rears [[Astereae|asters]], ''[[Nemophila]]'', [[Reseda (plant)|mignonette]], [[rhubarb]], [[sorrel]] and [[carrot]]s.<ref name=\"brit1911\"/> Over the decade to 2007, the growing season lengthened by as much as three weeks.<ref name=\"times\"/>\n\nIn the 13th-century ''[[Konungs skuggsj\u00e1]] (King's mirror)'', it is stated that the old Norsemen tried in vain to raise barley.<ref name=\"brit1911\"/>  \n\nRecent research from archaeological digs on Greenland by the National Museum in Copenhagen discovered barley grains and concluded that that the Vikings were able to grow barley. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sciencenordic.com/agriculture-archaeology-denmark/vikings-grew-barley-in-greenland/1447746|title=Vikings grew barley in Greenland|last=Hildebr|first=Sybille|last2=t|date=2012-02-03|website=sciencenordic.com|language=no|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Vaccinium uliginosum fruit.jpg|[[Bog Bilberry]] (Arctic Blueberry)<br />''Vaccinium uliginosum''<br />Kigutaarnat nagguii / moseb\u00f8lle / bl\u00e5b\u00e6r<br />[[:kl:Kigutaarnat|Kigutaarnat]], [[:da:Bl\u00e5b\u00e6r|Bl\u00e5b\u00e6r]]\n\nImage:Vaccinium vitis-idaea 20060824 003.jpg|[[Vaccinium vitis-idaea|Cowberry]]<br />''Vaccinium vitis-idaea''<br />kimmernat / tytteb\u00e6r<br />[[:kl:Kimmernat|Kimmernat]], [[:da:Tytteb\u00e6r|Tytteb\u00e6r]]\n\nImage:Alpine bearberry in Varrio Nature Reserve, Finland.jpg|[[Alpine bearberry]]<br />''Arctostaphylos alpina''<br />bjerg melb\u00e6rris<br />[[:da:Melb\u00e6rris|Melb\u00e6rris]]\n\nImage:Jun_com_cones.jpg|[[Juniper berry]]<br />''Alpine Juniper''<br />eneb\u00e6r<br />[[:kl:Kakillarnaq|Kakillarnaq; Paarnaqulluk]], [[:da:Eneb\u00e6r (Juniperus)|Eneb\u00e6r]]\n\nImage:Black crowberry.jpg|[[Crowberry]]<br />''Empetrum hermaphroditum''<br />paarnat / sorteb\u00e6r / revling<br />[[:kl:Paarnat|Paarnat]], [[:da:Almindelig Revling|Almindelig Revling]]\n\nImage:Arctic cottongrass, Inuvik, NT.jpg|[[Arctic Cottongrass]]<br />''Eriophorum scheuchzeri''<br />ukaliusaq / polar k\u00e6ruld<br />[[:da:Ukaliusaq|Ukaliusaq]], [[:da:K\u00e6ruld|K\u00e6ruld]]\n\nImage:Gew\u00f6hnlicher L\u00f6wenzahn Taraxacum officinale agg. Wiese.jpg|[[Dandelion]]<br />''Taraxacum lacerum''<br />inneruulaq / asorut / seqiniusaq / m\u00e6lkeb\u00f8tte<br />[[:kl:Inneruulaq|Inneruulaq; Asorut; Seqiniusaq]], [[:da:M\u00e6lkeb\u00f8tte|M\u00e6lkeb\u00f8tte]]\n\nImage:Koehler1887-GardenAngelica.jpg|[[Garden angelica]]<br />''Angelica archangelica''<br />kuanneq / kvan<br />[[:kl:Kuanneq|Kuanneq]], [[:da:Kvan|Kvan]]\n\nImage:Cladonia rangiferina.jpg|[[Cup Lichen]]<br />''[[Cladonia borealis]]'' Stenroos<br />orsuaasat ermusingasut /rensdyrlav<br /> [[:kl:Orsuaasat ermusingasut|Orsuaasat ermusingasut]], [[:da:B\u00e6gerlav-familien|B\u00e6gerlav-familien]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Fauna==\n{{further|List of mammals of Greenland|List of birds of Greenland}}\n===Land mammals===\nAmong the large land mammals are the [[muskox|musk ox]], the [[Reindeer|caribou]]<ref name=Cuyler>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.7557/2.27.4.347| title = West Greenland caribou explosion: What happened? What about the future?| journal = Rangifer| volume = 27| issue = 4| year = 2007| last1 = Cuyler | first1 = C.| page=219| doi-access = free}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n|title=Population genetics of the native caribou (Rangifer tarandus groenlandicus) and the semi-domestic reindeer (Rangifer tarandus tarandus) in Southwestern Greenland: Evidence of introgression\n|journal=Conservation Genetics |volume=3 |issue=4 |pages=401\u2013409 |doi=10.1023/A:1020523303815\n|year = 2002|last1 = Jepsen|first1 = B.I.|last2=Siegismund |first2=H.R. |last3=Fredholm |first3=M. }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n|url=http://agris.fao.org/agris-search/search.do?recordID=XE8420927\n|title=Feeding ecology of the West Greenland caribou (Rangifer tarandus groenlandicus) in the Sisimiut-Kangerlussuaq region [vegetation, food selection, forage quality, rumen samples, chemical analysis, migration]  [1984]\n|journal=Danish Review of Game Biology (Denmark)\n|accessdate=April 27, 2018\n|year=1984\n|last1=Thing\n|first1=H.\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.natur.gl/en/birds-and-mammals/terrestrial-mammals/caribou-reindeer/\n|title=Caribou\n|accessdate=April 27, 2018\n|publisher=[[Greenland Institute of Natural Resources]] }}</ref>, the [[polar bear]] and the white [[Arctic wolf]]. Other familiar mammals in Greenland include the [[Arctic hare]], [[northern collared lemming|collared lemming]], [[stoat|ermine]] and [[Arctic fox]].<ref name=\"brit1911\"/> [[Reindeer hunting in Greenland|Caribou hunting]] is of considerable cultural importance to the people of Greenland.\n\nDomesticated land mammals include [[dog]]s, which were introduced by the [[Inuit]], as well as such European-introduced species as [[goat]]s, [[Greenlandic sheep]], [[ox]]en and [[Domestic pig|pig]]s, which are raised in modest numbers in [[Kujalleq|the south]].<ref name=\"brit1911\"/>  \n\n<gallery>\nFile:Caribou.jpg|[[Barren-ground caribou]]<br />''Rangifer tarandus groenlandicus''<br />[[:da:rensdyr|rensdyr]] / ren\nFile:Muskus.jpg|[[Muskox]]<br />''Ovibos moschatus''<br />[[:da:moskusokse|moskusokse]]\nFile:Polar bear Olsen, Dave.jpg|[[Polar bear]]<br />''Ursus maritimus''<br />[[:da:isbj\u00f8rn|isbj\u00f8rn]]\nFile:Polarwolf004.jpg|[[Greenland wolf]]<br />''Canis lupus orion''<br />[[:da:ulv|gr\u00f8nland ulv]]\nFile:Eisfuchscele4.jpg|Greenland [[Arctic fox]]<br />''Vulpes lagopus foragorapusis''<br />[[:da:polarr\u00e6v|polarr\u00e6v]]\nFile:Polarhase 2 1997-08-04.jpg|Greenland [[Arctic hare]]<br />''Lepus arcticus groenlandicus''<br />[[:da:snehare|snehare]]\nFile:Lemming (1).jpg|[[Northern collared lemming]]<br />''Dicrostonyx groenlandicus''<br />[[:da:lemming|lemming]]\nFile:Kuupik Kleist, Regeringschef, Gronland talar vid Nordiska radet session i Stockholm 2009.jpg|[[Human]]<br />''Homo sapiens''<br />[[:da:menneske|menneske]]\n</gallery>\n\n===Marine mammals===\nAs many as two million seals are estimated to inhabit Greenland's coasts;<ref name=\"guide\"/> species include the [[hooded seal]] (''Cystophora cristata'') as well as the [[grey seal]] (''Halichoerus grypus'').<ref name=\"brit1911\"/> [[Whale]]s frequently pass very close to Greenlandic shores in the late summer and early autumn. Species represented include the [[beluga whale]], [[blue whale]], [[bowhead whale|Greenland whale]], [[fin whale]], [[humpback whale]], [[minke whale]], [[narwhal]], [[pilot whale]], [[sperm whale]].<ref name=\"guide\">{{cite web|url=http://www.greenland-guide.gl/animal_life.htm|title=Animal life in Greenland &ndash; an introduction by the tourist board|website=Greenland Guide|publisher=Narsaq Tourist Office|accessdate=1 May 2012|date=n.d.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427231950/http://www.greenland-guide.gl/animal_life.htm|archive-date=27 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Whaling]] was formerly a major industry in Greenland; by the turn of the 20th century, however, the [[right whale]] population was so depleted that the industry was in deep decline.<ref name=\"brit1911\"/> [[Walrus]]es are to be found primarily in the north and east of the country;<ref name=\"guide\"/> like narwhal, they have at times suffered from overhunting for their tusks.\n<gallery>\nImage:Narwal.jpg|[[Narwhal]]<br />''Monodon monoceros''<br />[[:da:narhval|narhval]]\n\nImage:Humpback_Whale_underwater_shot.jpg|[[Humpback whale]]<br />''Megaptera novaeangliae''<br />[[:da:pukkelhval|pukkelhval]]\n\nImage:Killerwhales_jumping.jpg|[[Orca]]<br />''Orcinus orca''<br />[[:da:sp\u00e6khugger|sp\u00e6khugger]]\n\nImage:Phoca hispida.jpg|[[Ringed seal]]<br />''Phoca hispida''<br />[[:da:rings\u00e6l|rings\u00e6l]]\n\n<!-- Missing image removed: Image:Cystophora cristata.jpg|[[Hooded seal]]<br />''Cystophora cristata''<br />[[:da:klapmyds|klapmyds]] -->\n\nImage:Phoca groenlandica.jpg|[[Harp seal]]<br />''Phoca groenlandica''<br />[[:da:gr\u00f8nlandss\u00e6l|gr\u00f8nlandss\u00e6l]]\n\nImage:Seehund2cele4.jpg|[[Common seal]]<br />''Phoca vitulina''<br />[[:da:sp\u00e6ttet s\u00e6l|sp\u00e6ttet s\u00e6l]]\n</gallery>\n\n===Birds===\nAs of 1911, 61 species of birds were known to breed in Greenland.<ref name=\"brit1911\">\"Greenland\". ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'', Eleventh Edition.</ref> Certain birds such as the [[common eider|eider duck]], [[guillemot]] and [[Lagopus|ptarmigan]] are often hunted for food in the winter.\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Raichou 01.JPG|[[Rock ptarmigan]]<br />''Lagopus muta''<br />rype<br />[[:da:Skovh\u00f8ns|Skovh\u00f8ns]]\n\nImage:Raven croak.jpg|[[Common raven|Raven]]<br />''Corvus corax''<br />[[:da:ravn|ravn]]\n\nImage:Eagle_In_Flight_2004-09-01.jpeg|[[White-tailed eagle|White-tailed sea eagle]]<br />''Haliaeetus albicilla''<br />[[:da:hav\u00f8rn|hav\u00f8rn]]\n\nImage:Falco peregrinus - 01.jpg|[[Peregrine falcon]]<br />''Falco peregrinus''<br />[[:da:vandrefalk|vandrefalk]]\n\nImage:Falco-rusticolus.jpg|[[Gyrfalcon]]<br />''Falco rusticolus''<br />[[:da:jagtfalk|jagtfalk]]\n\nImage:Harfang en vol 2.jpg|[[Snowy owl]]<br />''Bubo scandiacus''<br />[[:da:sneugle|sneugle]]\n\nImage:Oenanthe oenanthe 01 II.jpg|[[Northern wheatear]]<br />''Oenanthe oenanthe''<br />[[:da:stenpikker|stenpikker]]\n\nImage:Somateria mollissima male female.jpg|[[Common eider]]<br />''Somateria mollissima''<br />[[:da:ederfugl|ederfugl]]\n\nImage:AlleAlle_2.jpg|[[Little auk]]<br />''Alle alle''<br />[[:da:s\u00f8konge|s\u00f8konge]]\n\nImage:Plectrophenax_nivalis1.jpg|[[Snow bunting]]<br />''Plectrophenax nivalis''<br />[[:da:snespurv|snespurv]]\n\nImage:Phalacrocorax_carbo02.jpg|[[Great cormorant]]<br />''Phalacrocorax carbo''<br />[[:da:skarv|skarv]]\n\nImage:Larus hyperboreus1.jpg|[[Glaucous gull]]<br />''Larus hyperboreus''<br />[[:da:gr\u00e5m\u00e5ge|gr\u00e5m\u00e5ge]]\n\nImage:Larus-glaucoides-002.jpg|[[Iceland gull]]<br />''Larus glaucoides''<br />[[:da:hvidvinget m\u00e5ge|hvidvinget m\u00e5ge]]\n\nImage:Fulmarus_glacialis_on_cliff.jpg|[[Northern fulmar]]<br />''Fulmarus glacialis''<br />[[:da:mallemuk|mallemuk]]\n\nImage:RedNeckedPhalaropeIceland2006.jpg|[[Red-necked phalarope]]<br />''Phalaropus lobatus''<br />[[:da:odinshane|odinshane]]\n\nImage:Mergus_serrator.jpg|[[Red-breasted merganser]]<br />''Mergus serrator''<br />[[:da:toppet skallesluger|toppet skallesluger]]\n\nImage:RedthroatedLoon23.jpg|[[Red-throated diver]]<br />''Gavia stellata''<br />[[:da:r\u00f8dstrubet lom|r\u00f8dstrubet lom]]\n\nImage:Common Loon.jpg|[[Great northern diver]]<br />''Gavia immer''<br />[[:da:islom|islom]]\n\nImage:Long-tailed-duck.jpg|[[Long-tailed duck]] (male)<br />''Clangula hyemalis''<br />[[:da:havlit|havlit]]\n\nImage:Puffin2.jpg|[[Atlantic puffin]]<br />''Fratercula arctica''<br />[[:da:lunde|lunde]]\n</gallery>\n\n===Fish===\nOf the many species of fish inhabiting Greenland's waters, several have been of economic importance, including [[cod]], [[caplin]], [[halibut]], [[Sebastes|rockfish]], [[Cyclopterus lumpus|''nipisak'']] (''Cycloperteus lumpus'') and [[sea trout]]. The [[Greenland shark]] is used for the oil in its liver, as well as fermented and eaten as [[h\u00e1karl]], a local delicacy.\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Atlantic_cod.jpg|[[Atlantic cod]]<br />''Gadus ogac''<br />[[:da:torsk|torsk]]\n\nImage:Salmo_salar-Atlantic_Salmon-Atlanterhavsparken_Norway.JPG|[[Atlantic salmon]]<br />''Salmo salar''<br />[[:da:laks|laks]]\n\nImage:Salvelinusalpinus.jpg|[[Arctic char]]<br />''Salvelinus alpinus''<br />[[:da:fjeld\u00f8rred|fjeld\u00f8rred]]\n\nImage:Fiorello_LaGuardia_with_halibut.jpg|[[Halibut]]<br />''Hippoglossus hippoglossus''<br />[[:da:helleflynder|helleflynder]]\n\nImage:Reinhardtius_hippoglossoides.jpg|[[Greenland halibut]]<br />''Reinhardtius hippoglossoides''<br />[[:da:hellefisk|hellefisk]]\n\nImage:Rose_fish.jpg|[[Rose fish]]<br />''Sebastes marinus''<br />[[:da:r\u00f8dfisk|r\u00f8dfisk]]\n\nImage:Seewolf.JPG|[[Seawolf (fish)|Seawolf]]<br />''Anarhichas lupus''<br />[[:da:havkat|havkat]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n; Fauna\n* [[List of mammals of Nunavut]]\n* [[List of Nunavut birds]]\n\n; Flora\n* [[List of Canadian plants by family]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Greenland topics}}\n\n[[Category:Fauna of Greenland| 01]]\n[[Category:Flora of Greenland| 01]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Arctic|*Greenland]]\n[[Category:Arctic land animals|*Greenland]]\n[[Category:Birds of Greenland|*]]\n[[Category:Biota of archipelagoes]]\n", "name_user": "92.29.105.30", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flora_and_fauna_of_Greenland"}
{"title_page": "Bais Yaakov", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=May 2011}}\n:''For the neighborhood in Jerusalem, see [[Beit Ya'akov, Jerusalem|Beit Ya'akov]].''\n[[Image:Beit yaaaak.JPG|thumb|300px|Beit Yaacov students praying at the Western Wall.]]\n'''Bais Yaakov''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea \u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1}} also Beis Yaakov, Beit Yaakov or Beth Jacob; lit. House [of] Jacob) is a [[genericized]] name for full-time [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox Jewish]] elementary and secondary schools for Jewish girls throughout the world. \n\nBais Yaakov, started by [[Sarah Schenirer]] in post-World War I\n[[Krak\u00f3w]], was at the time a revolutionary approach to Jewish women's education. It has since achieved mainstream status within Orthodox Judaism, with branches located worldwide in every Jewish community with a significant population. \n\nWhile many of these schools carry the Bais Yaakov name, they are not necessarily affiliated, though they may be for other reasons.\n\n== History ==\n[[Image:Bais-Yaakov-1.jpg|thumb|300px|The second graduating class of the Bais Ya'akov in Lodz, Poland, in 1934.]]\nThe Bais Yaakov movement was started by seamstress [[Sarah Schenirer]] in 1917 in [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Poland]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = Carry Me In Your Heart|last = Benisch|first = Pearl|publisher = Feldheim|year = 2003|isbn = |location = |pages = }}</ref> The first school building survives as apartments, and is marked with a bronze plaque.\n\nWhile boys attended [[cheder]] and [[Talmud Torah]] schools (and in some cases [[yeshiva]]s), at that time there was no formalized system of Jewish education for girls and young Jewish women.\n\nSchenirer saw that there was a high rate of assimilation among girls due to the vast secular influences of the non-Jewish schools that the girls were then attending. Sarah Schenirer concluded that only providing young Jewish women with a thorough, school-based Jewish education would effectively combat this phenomenon. She started a school of her own, trained other women to teach, and set up similar schools in other cities throughout [[Europe]].\n\nShe obtained the approval of [[Yisrael Meir Kagan]] (author of ''[[Chofetz Chaim]]''), who issued a [[responsum]] holding that contemporary conditions required departing from traditional prohibitions on teaching women Torah and accepting the view that it was permitted. Following the Chofetz Chaim's approbation, the Bais Yaakov Movement in Poland was taken under the wing of [[World Agudath Israel|Agudath Israel]]. Additionally, she sought and received approbation from [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic]] rabbis as well, most notably the [[Yissachar Dov Rokeach (third Belzer rebbe)|Belzer Rebbe]] and the [[Avraham Mordechai Alter|Gerrer Rebbe]].<ref>\"From Sarah to Sarah\" by S. Feldbrand1976</ref> The original Bais Yaakov was a seminary of sorts, intended to train girls to themselves become teachers and spread the Bais Yaakov movement.\n\nGirls who were taught in the Bais Yaakov movement used their education as psychological support to survive World War II and [[the Holocaust]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=To Vanquish the Dragon|last=Benisch|first=Pearl|publisher=Feldheim|year=1991|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[World War II]], Jews who came to [[North America]], [[Israel]], and other places established girls' schools of the same name, although some{{who|date=July 2019}} claim that the educational philosophy differs slightly from that of the original Bais Yaakov schools.\n\nBesides elementary and high schools, there are also post-secondary schools in the Bais Yaakov system, usually referred to as seminaries. These run various courses generally lasting between one and three years. There are also post-secondary schools that combine Torah education with practical workforce skills, such as computer programming, education, and graphic arts.\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe name Bais Yaakov comes from a verse in the [[Book of Exodus]] in which the term \"House of Jacob\" is understood by [[Jewish commentaries on the Bible]] to refer to the female segment of the Jewish nation.<ref>{{bibleverse|Exodus|19:3}}</ref>\n\n== Current ==\n=== Educational approach ===\nThe educational policies of most Bais Yaakov schools worldwide is generally that of [[Haredi Judaism]] and the [[Agudath Israel movement]]. In accordance with the differences between the Israeli and Diaspora Haredi communities, there are slight variations in outlook and philosophy between Israeli, American and European Bais Yaakov schools. Israeli Bais Yaakov schools tend to de-emphasize the secular content of the [[curriculum]], whereas in North America and Europe the girls frequently receive a more diverse secular education. Large cities may have several Bais Yaakov schools, each with small variations in philosophy, typically over the importance placed on secular studies and/or accommodations made to secular values.\n\nStudents are required to uphold a dress code or wear uniforms which conform to the rules of ''[[tzniut|tznius]]'' (modesty). Uniforms differ from school to school but typically consist of a long pleated skirt, [[oxford shirt]], and sweater or sweatshirt.\n\nThe schools' primary purpose is to prepare students to be contributors to family and community, as good [[Jew]]s, wives, professionals, and mothers. \n\nSecular studies sometimes reflect government proficiency requirements in such subjects as math, science, literature and history in their respective countries.\n\n=== Curriculum ===\n:''See also [[Midrasha #Curriculum]].''\nMost non-Hasidic Bais Yaakov schools in America teach Judaic studies in the mornings and a college preparatory program of secular studies in the afternoons. Judaic studies usually include study of [[Chumash (Judaism)|Chumash]] ([[Pentateuch]]), [[Nevi'im]] (Prophets), and other parts of the [[Hebrew Bible]]; and instruction in [[Hebrew language]], [[Jewish history]] and the study of practical ''[[halakha]]'' (Jewish law), sometimes directly from the text, and other times as a summary of classic ''halakha'' sources.\n\nOne of the tenets of [[Orthodox Judaism]] is that it is impossible to fully understand the written Torah without the Jewish commentaries, so Bais Yaakov girls are taught the [[Tanakh]] through this approach. A major focus is on [[Rashi]], considered the foremost Torah commentator.\n\nThe curriculum of Bais Yaakov differs from that of male-only [[yeshiva]]s, where the core component of study is the [[Talmud]]. Girls in Bais Yaakov schools do not learn law from the text of the Talmud itself, but may study its non-legal portions of ''[[aggadah]]'' (homiletics). This contrasts with the approach of many [[Modern Orthodox Judaism|Modern Orthodox]] [[Jewish day school]]s, which increasingly teach Talmud to women.\n\n=== Locations ===\n[[Image:\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea \u05e1\u05e4\u05e8 \"\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea \u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1\" \u05d4\u05e8\u05d0\u05e9\u05d5\u05df, \u05e7\u05e8\u05e7\u05d5\u05d1 (1).jpg|thumb|250px|Beit Yaakov teachers' Seminary, [[Krak\u00f3w]], Poland.]]\nBranches exist in most North American cities with large [[:Category:Orthodox Jewish communities|populations of Orthodox Jews]] such as New York City, Montreal, Miami, Chicago, Detroit, Los Angeles, Baltimore, Denver, [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]], Toronto, [[Lakewood Township, New Jersey|Lakewood]], [[Passaic, New Jersey|Passaic]], [[Monsey, New York|Monsey]], and in most Israeli cities. Bais Yaakov-type schools are also found in major Jewish centers in Europe, such as London, [[Manchester]], [[Antwerp]] and Moscow, and in other Jewish centers around the world, Including [[Johannesburg, South Africa|Johannesburg]].\n\nPre-war locations included over 260 towns and cities in Poland, with its central teachers' seminary in [[Krak\u00f3w]].\n\n== Hasidic schools ==\nSchools for girls within the Hasidic world share the same values, outlook, methodology, and aims of the non-Hasidic Haredi schools. However, they may place a greater emphasis on the teachings of their individual Hasidic [[Rebbe]]s and much of the instruction may be conducted in [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]], which is still the home language for most Hasidic families in the world today. Also, in many Hasidic Beis Yaakov schools in Israel, English is often not taught, which is not the case in other Bais Yaakov schools.\n\nSchools for young Hasidic girls which are not part of the Bais Yaakov movement take names such as:\n\n* [[Beth Rivkah|Bais Rivkah]], Bnos Menachem, Bnos Rabbeinu, Bais [[Chaya Mushka Schneerson|Chaya Mushka]], or [[Bais Chana Women International|Bais Chana]] for the [[Chabad Lubavitch]] girls' schools.\n*  Bnos Zion for the [[Bobov (Hasidic dynasty)|Bobov]] girls' schools.\n*  Bnos Belz or Beis Malka for [[Belz (Hasidic dynasty)|Belz]] girls' schools.\n*  Bnos Vizhnitz for [[Vizhnitz (Hasidic dynasty)|Vizhnitz]] girls' schools.\n*  Beis Rochel schools for girls of the [[Satmar (Hasidic dynasty)|Satmar]] community, as well as some girls' schools of related Hasidic groups (often of Hungarian background). \n\nThese schools follow a different curriculum of Judaic studies, which is less text-based and more focused on practical knowledge than the curriculum in other schools. Within their communities, these schools are usually referred to as offering education ''al pi taharas kodesh'', roughly translating as \"holy, pure education\".\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Mesivta]]\n* [[Ulpana]]\n* [[Women in Judaism]]\n* [[Midrasha]]\n* [[Jewish_education #Girls' education]]\n* [[Hashkafa #Gender roles]]\n* [[Yeshiva #Types of yeshivot]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jwa.org/encyclopedia/article/schenirer-sarah/ Jewish Women's Archive: Sarah Schenirer]\n*[https://thebaisyaakovproject.com/ The Bais Yaakov Project]\n\n{{OrthodoxJudaism}}\n{{Jewish education}}\n\n[[Category:Orthodox Jewish schools for women]]\n[[Category:Jewish organizations established in 1917]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=May 2011}}\n:''For the neighborhood in Jerusalem, see [[Beit Ya'akov, Jerusalem|Beit Ya'akov]].''\n[[Image:Beit yaaaak.JPG|thumb|300px|Beit Yaacov students praying at the Western Wall.]]\n'''Bais Yaakov''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea \u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1}} also Beis Yaakov, Beit Yaakov or Beth Jacob; lit. House [of] Jacob) is a [[genericized]] name for full-time [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox Jewish]] elementary and secondary schools for Jewish girls throughout the world. \n\nBais Yaakov, started by [[Sarah Schenirer]] in post-World War I\n[[Krak\u00f3w]], was at the time a revolutionary approach to Jewish women's education. It has since achieved mainstream status within Orthodox Judaism, with branches located worldwide in every Jewish community with a significant population. \n\nWhile many of these schools carry the Bais Yaakov name, they are not necessarily affiliated, though they may be for other reasons.\n\n== History ==\n[[Image:Bais-Yaakov-1.jpg|thumb|300px|The second graduating class of the Bais Ya'akov in Lodz, Poland, in 1934.]]\nThe Bais Yaakov movement was started by seamstress [[Sarah Schenirer]] in 1917 in [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Poland]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = Carry Me In Your Heart|last = Benisch|first = Pearl|publisher = Feldheim|year = 2003|isbn = |location = |pages = }}</ref> The first school building survives as apartments, and is marked with a bronze plaque.\n\nWhile boys attended [[cheder]] and [[Talmud Torah]] schools (and in some cases [[yeshiva]]s), at that time there was no formalized system of Jewish education for girls and young Jewish women.\n\nSchenirer saw that there was a high rate of assimilation among girls due to the vast secular influences of the non-Jewish schools that the girls were then attending. Sarah Schenirer concluded that only providing young Jewish women with a thorough, school-based Jewish education would effectively combat this phenomenon. She started a school of her own, trained other women to teach, and set up similar schools in other cities throughout [[Europe]].\n\nShe obtained the approval of [[Yisrael Meir Kagan]] (author of ''[[Chofetz Chaim]]''), who issued a [[responsum]] holding that contemporary conditions required departing from traditional prohibitions on teaching women Torah and accepting the view that it was permitted. Following the Chofetz Chaim's approbation, the Bais Yaakov Movement in Poland was taken under the wing of [[World Agudath Israel|Agudath Israel]]. Additionally, she sought and received approbation from [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic]] rabbis as well, most notably the [[Yissachar Dov Rokeach (third Belzer rebbe)|Belzer Rebbe]] and the [[Avraham Mordechai Alter|Gerrer Rebbe]].<ref>\"From Sarah to Sarah\" by S. Feldbrand1976</ref> The original Bais Yaakov was a seminary of sorts, intended to train girls to themselves become teachers and spread the Bais Yaakov movement.\n\nGirls who were taught in the Bais Yaakov movement used their education as psychological support to survive World War II and [[the Holocaust]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=To Vanquish the Dragon|last=Benisch|first=Pearl|publisher=Feldheim|year=1991|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[World War II]], Jews who came to [[North America]], [[Israel]], and other places established girls' schools of the same name, although some{{who|date=July 2019}} claim that the educational philosophy differs slightly from that of the original Bais Yaakov schools.\n\nBesides elementary and high schools, there are also post-secondary schools in the Bais Yaakov system, usually referred to as seminaries. These run various courses generally lasting between one and three years. There are also post-secondary schools that combine Torah education with practical workforce skills, such as computer programming, education, and graphic arts.\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe name Bais Yaakov comes from a verse in the [[Book of Exodus]] in which the term \"House of Jacob\" is understood by [[Jewish commentaries on the Bible]] to refer to the female segment of the Jewish nation.<ref>{{bibleverse|Exodus|19:3}}</ref>\n\n== Current ==\n=== Educational approach ===\nThe educational policies of most Bais Yaakov schools worldwide is generally that of [[Haredi Judaism]] and the [[Agudath Israel movement]]. In accordance with the differences between the Israeli and Diaspora Haredi communities, there are slight variations in outlook and philosophy between Israeli, American and European Bais Yaakov schools. Israeli Bais Yaakov schools tend to de-emphasize the secular content of the [[curriculum]], whereas in North America and Europe the girls frequently receive a more diverse secular education. Large cities may have several Bais Yaakov schools, each with small variations in philosophy, typically over the importance placed on secular studies and/or accommodations made to secular values.\n\nStudents are required to uphold a dress code or wear uniforms which conform to the rules of ''[[tzniut|tznius]]'' (modesty). Uniforms differ from school to school but typically consist of a long pleated skirt, [[oxford shirt]], and sweater or sweatshirt.\n\nThe schools' primary purpose is to prepare students to be contributors to family and community, as good [[Jew]]s, wives, professionals, and mothers. \n\nSecular studies sometimes reflect government proficiency requirements in such subjects as math, science, literature and history in their respective countries.\n\n=== Curriculum ===\nMost non-Hasidic Bais Yaakov schools in America teach Judaic studies in the mornings and a college preparatory program of secular studies in the afternoons. Judaic studies usually include study of [[Chumash (Judaism)|Chumash]] ([[Pentateuch]]), [[Nevi'im]] (Prophets), and other parts of the [[Hebrew Bible]]; and instruction in [[Hebrew language]], [[Jewish history]] and the study of practical ''[[halakha]]'' (Jewish law), sometimes directly from the text, and other times as a summary of classic ''halakha'' sources.\n\nOne of the tenets of [[Orthodox Judaism]] is that it is impossible to fully understand the written Torah without the Jewish commentaries, so Bais Yaakov girls are taught the [[Tanakh]] through this approach. A major focus is on [[Rashi]], considered the foremost Torah commentator.\n\nThe curriculum of Bais Yaakov differs from that of male-only [[yeshiva]]s, where the core component of study is the [[Talmud]]. Girls in Bais Yaakov schools do not learn law from the text of the Talmud itself, but may study its non-legal portions of ''[[aggadah]]'' (homiletics). This contrasts with the approach of many [[Modern Orthodox Judaism|Modern Orthodox]] [[Jewish day school]]s, which increasingly teach Talmud to women.\n\n=== Locations ===\n[[Image:\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea \u05e1\u05e4\u05e8 \"\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea \u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1\" \u05d4\u05e8\u05d0\u05e9\u05d5\u05df, \u05e7\u05e8\u05e7\u05d5\u05d1 (1).jpg|thumb|250px|Beit Yaakov teachers' Seminary, [[Krak\u00f3w]], Poland.]]\nBranches exist in most North American cities with large [[:Category:Orthodox Jewish communities|populations of Orthodox Jews]] such as New York City, Montreal, Miami, Chicago, Detroit, Los Angeles, Baltimore, Denver, [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]], Toronto, [[Lakewood Township, New Jersey|Lakewood]], [[Passaic, New Jersey|Passaic]], [[Monsey, New York|Monsey]], and in most Israeli cities. Bais Yaakov-type schools are also found in major Jewish centers in Europe, such as London, [[Manchester]], [[Antwerp]] and Moscow, and in other Jewish centers around the world, Including [[Johannesburg, South Africa|Johannesburg]].\n\nPre-war locations included over 260 towns and cities in Poland, with its central teachers' seminary in [[Krak\u00f3w]].\n\n== Hasidic schools ==\nSchools for girls within the Hasidic world share the same values, outlook, methodology, and aims of the non-Hasidic Haredi schools. However, they may place a greater emphasis on the teachings of their individual Hasidic [[Rebbe]]s and much of the instruction may be conducted in [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]], which is still the home language for most Hasidic families in the world today. Also, in many Hasidic Beis Yaakov schools in Israel, English is often not taught, which is not the case in other Bais Yaakov schools.\n\nSchools for young Hasidic girls which are not part of the Bais Yaakov movement take names such as:\n\n* [[Beth Rivkah|Bais Rivkah]], Bnos Menachem, Bnos Rabbeinu, Bais [[Chaya Mushka Schneerson|Chaya Mushka]], or [[Bais Chana Women International|Bais Chana]] for the [[Chabad Lubavitch]] girls' schools.\n*  Bnos Zion for the [[Bobov (Hasidic dynasty)|Bobov]] girls' schools.\n*  Bnos Belz or Beis Malka for [[Belz (Hasidic dynasty)|Belz]] girls' schools.\n*  Bnos Vizhnitz for [[Vizhnitz (Hasidic dynasty)|Vizhnitz]] girls' schools.\n*  Beis Rochel schools for girls of the [[Satmar (Hasidic dynasty)|Satmar]] community, as well as some girls' schools of related Hasidic groups (often of Hungarian background). \n\nThese schools follow a different curriculum of Judaic studies, which is less text-based and more focused on practical knowledge than the curriculum in other schools. Within their communities, these schools are usually referred to as offering education ''al pi taharas kodesh'', roughly translating as \"holy, pure education\".\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Mesivta]]\n* [[Ulpana]]\n* [[Women in Judaism]]\n* [[Midrasha]]\n* [[Jewish_education #Girls' education]]\n* [[Hashkafa #Gender roles]]\n* [[Yeshiva #Types of yeshivot]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jwa.org/encyclopedia/article/schenirer-sarah/ Jewish Women's Archive: Sarah Schenirer]\n*[https://thebaisyaakovproject.com/ The Bais Yaakov Project]\n\n{{OrthodoxJudaism}}\n{{Jewish education}}\n\n[[Category:Orthodox Jewish schools for women]]\n[[Category:Jewish organizations established in 1917]]\n", "name_user": "Fintor", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCurriculum", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bais_Yaakov"}
{"title_page": "List of best-selling books", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{dynamic list}}\n<!--\n\nBE AWARE: many popular published sources from the early 21 century take their facts from this article, or previous versions of it, directly or indirectly. They are therefore not suitable as references, since that would be circular referencing. See the talk page and archives for more information.\n\n-->\nThis page provides '''lists of best-selling individual books and book series''' to date and in any language. ''\"Best selling\"'' refers to the estimated number of copies sold of each book, rather than the number of books printed or currently owned. [[Comic book|Comics]] and [[textbook]]s are not included in this list. The books are listed according to the highest sales estimate as reported in reliable, independent sources. This list is incomplete because there are many books, such as ''[[The Count of Monte Cristo]]'' by [[Alexandre Dumas]], or ''[[A Christmas Carol]]'' by [[Charles Dickens]], that are commonly cited as \"best-selling books\" yet have no reliable sales figures. Similarly, many notable book series that sold very widely are poorly documented ([[Land of Oz]]) or consist of multiple sub-series ([[Tom Swift]]).\n\nAccording to ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' as of 1995, the [[Bible]] is the best-selling book of all time, with an estimated 5{{nbsp}}billion copies sold and distributed.<ref name=\"guinnessworldrecords\">{{cite web|title=Best selling book of non-fiction|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/best-selling-book-of-non-fiction|publisher=Guinness World Records|accessdate=15 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315025558/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/best-selling-book-of-non-fiction|archivedate=15 March 2015}}</ref>  The ''[[Quotations from Chairman Mao Tse-tung]]'', also known as the ''Little Red Book'', has produced a wide array of sales and distribution figures \u2014 with estimates ranging from 800{{nbsp}}million<ref name=\"guinnessworldrecords\"/> to over 6.5 billion printed volumes,<ref>Zhengyuan Fu, ''Autocratic Tradition and Chinese Politics'', Cambridge University Press 1994, p. 186. [https://books.google.com/books?id=uGZIziWmlmsC&printsec=frontcover&dq=autocratic+tradition+and+chinese+politics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CBwQ6AEwAGoVChMI56TJyKv6yAIViXE-Ch0DEQvm#v=onepage&q=autocratic%20tradition%20and%20chinese%20politics&f=false Autocratic Tradition and Chinese Politics] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112153604/https://books.google.com/books?id=uGZIziWmlmsC&printsec=frontcover&dq=autocratic+tradition+and+chinese+politics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CBwQ6AEwAGoVChMI56TJyKv6yAIViXE-Ch0DEQvm |date=2016-01-12 }}</ref> with some claiming the distribution ran into the \"billions\"<ref>[[Allen Kent]], Harold Lancour, Jay E. Daily, ''Encyclopedia of Library and Information Science, Volume 22'', CRC Press 1977, p.31. [https://www.google.com/search?tbm=bks&hl=en&q=Encyclopedia+of+Library+and+Information+Science%3A+Volume+22 Encyclopedia of Library and Information Science]</ref> and some citing \"over a billion\" official volumes between 1966 and 1969 alone as well as \"untold numbers of unofficial local reprints and unofficial translations.\"<ref>Alexander C. Cook, ''Mao's Little Red Book: A Global History'', Cambridge University Press 2014, p. xiii [https://books.google.com/books?id=ttjSAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=mao%27s+little+red+book:+a+global+history&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAGoVChMIwsfq57T6yAIVSfI-Ch0XggzB#v=onepage&q=mao's%20little%20red%20book%3A%20a%20global%20history&f=false Mao's Little Red Book: A Global History] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112153604/https://books.google.com/books?id=ttjSAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=mao%27s+little+red+book:+a+global+history&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAGoVChMIwsfq57T6yAIVSfI-Ch0XggzB |date=2016-01-12 }}</ref><ref>Daniel Leese, ''Mao Cult: Rhetoric and Ritual in China's Cultural Revolution'', Cambridge University Press 2013, p. 108 [https://books.google.com/books?id=iqjviY6aFloC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Mao+Cult:+Rhetoric+and+Ritual+in+China%27s+Cultural+Revolution&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAGoVChMIzqqJwq_6yAIVgTI-Ch3k6wSv#v=onepage&q=Mao%20Cult%3A%20Rhetoric%20and%20Ritual%20in%20China's%20Cultural%20Revolution&f=false Mao Cult: Rhetoric and Ritual in China's Cultural Revolution] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112153604/https://books.google.com/books?id=iqjviY6aFloC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Mao+Cult:+Rhetoric+and+Ritual+in+China%27s+Cultural+Revolution&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAGoVChMIzqqJwq_6yAIVgTI-Ch3k6wSv |date=2016-01-12 }}</ref> Exact print figures for these and other books may also be missing or unreliable since these kinds of books may be produced by many different and unrelated publishers, in some cases over many centuries. All books of a religious, ideological, philosophical or political nature have thus been excluded from the below lists of best-selling books for these reasons.\n\nHaving sold more than 500 million copies worldwide,<ref name=\"Forbes\">[https://www.forbes.com/pictures/lml45effkg/j-k-rowling-founder-of-the-harry-potter-empire/ Forbes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825195304/https://www.forbes.com/pictures/lml45effkg/j-k-rowling-founder-of-the-harry-potter-empire/ |date=2017-08-25 }} on ''Harry Potter'': \"It and the six subsequent books have now sold 500 million copies worldwide.\" (22 May 2013)</ref><ref>[https://www.hypable.com/harry-potter/book-history/ Hybable] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906134322/https://www.hypable.com/harry-potter/book-history/ |date=2017-09-06 }} on ''Harry Potter'': \"Collectively, the seven Harry Potter books have sold nearly 500 million copies since the publication of Harry Potter and the Philosopher\u2019s Stone in 1997, making Harry Potter the bestselling book series of all time.\" (29 April 2012)</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/books/news/data-show-uk-loves-harry-potter/ The Telegraph] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171004015807/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/books/news/data-show-uk-loves-harry-potter/ |date=2017-10-04 }} on ''Harry Potter'': \"More than 500 million copies of the books have been sold worldwide and the series has been translated into 79 languages.\" (26 June 2017)</ref> ''[[Harry Potter]]'' by [[J. K. Rowling]] is the best-selling book series in history. The first [[novel]] in the series, ''[[Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone]]'', has sold in excess of 120 million copies,<ref name=\"Chalton 2017 129\">{{cite book|last=Chalton|first=Nicola|author2=MacArdle, Meredith|title=20th Century in Bite-Sized Chunks|publisher=Chartwell Books|year=2017|page=129|isbn=978-0-7858-3510-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eF8HDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA129&lpg=PA129&dq=philosopher%27s+stone+120+million&source=bl&ots=xcuvqK2qLp&sig=GFDBLllrb6LEkISCOroWndKwemc&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj69Nu5z-3VAhUyS5oKHftkBawQ6AEITDAL#v=onepage&q=philosopher's%20stone%20120%20million&f=false|accessdate=23 August 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180114001005/https://books.google.com/books?id=eF8HDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA129&lpg=PA129&dq=philosopher%27s+stone+120+million&source=bl&ots=xcuvqK2qLp&sig=GFDBLllrb6LEkISCOroWndKwemc&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj69Nu5z-3VAhUyS5oKHftkBawQ6AEITDAL#v=onepage&q=philosopher's%20stone%20120%20million&f=false|archivedate=14 January 2018}}</ref> making it one of the best-selling books of all time. As of June 2017, the series has been translated into 80 languages,<ref>[https://www.jkrowling.com/harry-potter-translated-scots/ J.K. Rowling] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731000042/https://www.jkrowling.com/harry-potter-translated-scots/ |date=2017-07-31 }} on ''Harry Potter'': \"20 years after it was first published in the UK in 1997, Harry Potter and the Philosopher\u2019s Stone is to be translated into its 80th language \u2013 Scots!\" (28 June 2017)</ref> placing Harry Potter among history's [[List of literary works by number of translations|most translated literary works]]. The last four books in the series consecutively set records as the fastest-selling books of all time, where the final installment, ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows]]'', sold roughly fifteen million copies worldwide within twenty-four hours of its release.<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/lists/2008/53/celebrities08_JK-Rowling_CRTT.html Forbes] on ''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows'': \"The final one, Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows, has sold 44 million since it was published last July, including 15 million in the first 24 hours.\" (19 December 2008)</ref><ref>[https://www.worldrecordacademy.com/business/fastest_selling_book_world_record_set_by_harry_potter_new_book_70663.htm World Record Academy] on ''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows'': \"Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 the seventh and last novel in the series \u2013 sold around 15 million copies worldwide in its first day and set the new world record for the fastest selling book.\" (23 July 2007)</ref> With twelve million books printed in the first U.S. run, it also holds the record for the highest initial print run for any book in history.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6912529.stm BBC] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081128201059/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6912529.stm |date=2008-11-28 }} on ''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows'': \"The book had a print run of 12 million in the US, compared with 10.8 million for the last book, according to Lisa Holton of the book's US publisher Scholastic.\" (23 July 2007)</ref><ref>[https://www.inshorts.com/news/deathly-hallows-sold-15-mn-copies-in-24-hours-1467645762711 Inshorts] on ''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows'': \"The final instalment of the Harry Potter series, 'The Deathly Hallows' is recognised by Guinness World Records as 'the fastest selling book of fiction in 24 hours' with a total of 15 million books sold. With 12 million books printed in the first run, it also holds a record for the 'highest initial print run for a fiction book'.\" (4 July 2016)</ref>\n\n==Key==\nFigures are inexact, and methods vary by source; the list is incomplete, since sources are unavailable for many books.\n\n{{legend2|#f9f9f9|Fiction|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n\n{{legend2|lavender|Nonfiction|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n\n== List of best-selling individual books ==\n=== More than 100 million copies ===\n<!--\n        Do not add   Don Quixote    or    Tale of Two Cities   without discussing on the talk page, please (see also talk page archives).\n-->\n<!--Fifty Shades of Grey does not qualify as a single volume book. Please see talk page for more details.-->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- \"\n!Book !! Author(s) !! Original language !! First published !! Approximate sales !! Genre\n|-\n|''[[The Lord of the Rings]]''||[[J. R. R. Tolkien]]|| English || 1954 || 150 million<ref>{{cite news |last1=Levine |first1=Mort |title=\u2018Lord of the Rings\u2019 as you\u2019ve never experienced it |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2015/04/10/lord-of-the-rings-as-youve-never-experienced-it/ |accessdate=November 21, 2018 |work=The Mercury News |date=April 10, 2015|quote=The three films, based on the Tolkien novels that were written between 1937 and 1949 and sold more than 150 million copies, were filmed in New Zealand\u2019s astonishing forests by director Peter Jackson at a cost of more than $300 million.}}</ref><ref name=\"Chalton 2017 129\" /><ref>*\n| ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'' is considered by many to be a single book{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}, because it was written and planned by the author to be such. It is written in the preface to many editions that the book is sometimes 'erroneously' referred to as a trilogy, and goes on to state that it is one book in three volumes. Some people consider it to instead be a trilogy or series of three books, because it was originally published as a series of three volumes: ''[[The Fellowship of the Ring]]'', ''[[The Two Towers]]'', and ''[[The Return of the King]]''. [http://www.waterstones.com/waterstonesweb/displayProductDetails.do?sku=5007234 ''Waterstone's'']  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928071938/http://www.waterstones.com/waterstonesweb/displayProductDetails.do?sku=5007234 |date=2007-09-28 }}, Waterstones.com: This move by the publishing house was due largely to post-war paper shortages as well as to minimize the price of the first volume to aid sales.{{failed verification|date=November 2018}}\n*Wagner, Vit. [https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/article/203389 \"Tolkien proves he's still the king\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110309035210/http://www.thestar.com/entertainment/article/203389 |date=2011-03-09 }}, ''[[The Toronto Star]]'', 16 April 2007: In subsequent printings the book has sometimes appeared as a single volume, and in at least one case was split into seven. The figure of 150 million is a 2007 estimate of copies of the full story sold, whether published as one volume, three, or some other configuration.{{failed verification|date=November 2018}} \"Fully one-third of the 150 million copies of The Lord of the Rings sold to date were purchased after the release of the first film in the series.\"</ref>\n| [[fantasy]]\n|-\n| ''[[The Alchemist (novel)|The Alchemist]]'' (''O Alquimista'') || [[Paulo Coelho]] || Portuguese || 1988 || 150 million<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/2009/08/31/alchemist-geneva-brazil-opinions-high-five-paulo-coelho.html Forbes] {{webarchive|url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.ca/532/nine-books-sold-more-100-million-copies-and-how-they-compare-my-book |date=2019-10-05 }} on \"High Five With Paulo Coelho\"</ref>||[[fantasy]]\n|-\n|''[[The Little Prince]]'' (''Le Petit Prince'') ||[[Antoine de Saint-Exup\u00e9ry]] || French || 1943 || 140 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2013/03/the-little-prince-anniversary/317005/ http://thetimes-tribune.com/news/little-prince-discovery-offers-new-insight-into-classic-book-1.1310195|title='Little Prince' discovery offers new insight into classic book|author=Thomas Adamson (Associated Press)|work=thetimes-tribune.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202095913/http://thetimes-tribune.com/news/little-prince-discovery-offers-new-insight-into-classic-book-1.1310195|archivedate=2017-02-02}}</ref>|| [[fantasy]] (picture book)\n|-\n|''[[Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone]]'' ||[[J. K. Rowling]] || English || 1997 || 120 million<ref name=\"Chalton 2017 129\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Livingston |first1=Michael |title=Burbank Public Library offering digital copies of first \u2018Harry Potter\u2019 novel to recognize the book\u2019s 20th anniversary |url=https://latimes.com/socal/burbank-leader/news/tn-blr-me-burbank-library-harry-potter-20180831-story.html |accessdate=October 27, 2018 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=September 4, 2018|quote=No matter the name, the first Harry Potter book is the best seller of the seven-part series. \u201cSorcerer\u2019s Stone\u201d has sold more than 120 million copies worldwide.}}</ref>|| [[fantasy]], [[Mystery fiction|mystery]]\n|-\n|''[[The Master and Margarita]]'' (''\u041c\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440 \u0438 \u041c\u0430\u0440\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0430'')||[[Mikhail Bulgakov]] || Russian || 1967 || 100 million<ref>https://deadline.com/2019/12/baz-luhrmann-the-master-and-margarita-mikhail-bulgakov-elvis-presley-1202806494/</ref>|| [[fantasy]], [[farce]], [[supernatural fiction|supernatural]], [[Romance novel|romance]], [[satirical novel]]\n|-\n|''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]'' || [[Lewis Carroll]] || English  || 1865 || 100 million<ref>https://www.thevintagenews.com/2016/06/12/alice-lidell-the-girl-that-inspired-alice-in-wonderland-2/</ref>|| [[fantasy novel]]\n|-\n|''[[The Hobbit]]'' ||[[J. R. R. Tolkien]]|| English || 1937 || 100 million<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/booknews/9555838/The-Hobbit-What-has-made-the-book-such-an-enduring-success.html \"The Hobbit: What has made the book such an enduring success?\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161113111720/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/booknews/9555838/The-Hobbit-What-has-made-the-book-such-an-enduring-success.html |date=2016-11-13 }}, The Telegraph, 20 September 2012.</ref>|| [[fantasy]]\n|-\n|''[[And Then There Were None]]''||[[Agatha Christie]]|| English || 1939 || 100 million<ref>{{cite news |last1=Flood |first1=Alison |title=And Then There Were None declared world's favourite Agatha Christie novel |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/sep/01/and-then-there-were-none-declared-worlds-favourite-agatha-christie-novel |accessdate=October 27, 2018 |work=The Guardian |date=September 1, 2015}}</ref>|| [[Mystery fiction|mystery]]\n|-\n|''[[Dream of the Red Chamber]]'' ({{zh||c=\u7d05\u6a13\u5922|labels=no}})||[[Cao Xueqin]]|| Chinese || 1791 || 100 million<ref>{{cite news | title=The five biggest-selling books of all time: in pictures | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/8526939/The-five-biggest-selling-books-of-all-time-in-pictures.html?image=4 | work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | publisher=[[Telegraph.co.uk]] | quote=Approximate sales more than 100m}}</ref>|| [[family saga]]\n\n|}\n\n=== Between 50 million and 100 million copies ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- \"\n!Book !! Author(s) !! Original language !! First published !! Approximate sales !! Genre\n|-\n|''[[The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe]]'' || [[C. S. Lewis]] || English || 1950 || 85 million<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/books-life/7545438/The-20-greatest-childrens-books-ever.html The Telegraph] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100406033817/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/books-life/7545438/The-20-greatest-childrens-books-ever.html |date=2010-04-06 }} on ''The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe'': \"This classic story has sold more than 85 million copies in 29 different languages since its publication in 1950.\" (3 April 2010)</ref>||[[fantasy]]\n|-\n|''[[She: A History of Adventure]]'' || [[H. Rider Haggard]] || English || 1887 || 83 million<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/invisible-ink-no-309-henry-rider-haggard-a6802696.html The Independent] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129221558/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/invisible-ink-no-309-henry-rider-haggard-a6802696.html |date=2016-01-29 }} on ''She'': \"His next novel, She, about a beautiful ageless sorceress, was a smashing success, and by 1965 had sold 83 million copies.\" (3 April 2010)</ref>||[[adventure fiction|adventure]]\n|-\n|''[[The Adventures of Pinocchio]]'' (''Le avventure di Pinocchio'') || [[Carlo Collodi]] || Italian || 1881 || data-sort-value=\"80.1 million\" | >80 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artspecialday.com/9art/2017/10/26/carlo-collodi/|title=Carlo Collodi, il pap\u00e0 del burattino pi\u00f9 conformista della letteratura|language=Italian|publisher=artspecialday.com|date=April 3, 2018|access-date=April 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403234914/http://www.artspecialday.com/9art/2017/10/26/carlo-collodi/|archive-date=April 3, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>[http://www.repubblicaletteraria.it/Collodi_Pinocchio.htm Repubblica Italiana] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090428194705/http://www.repubblicaletteraria.it/Collodi_Pinocchio.htm |date=2009-04-28 }} on ''Le Avventure di pinocchio'': \"\u201cThe Adventures of Pinocchio\u201d translated in more of 260 languages.\" (1 July 2001)</ref> || [[fantasy]]\n|-\n|''[[Vardi Wala Gunda]]'' || [[Ved Prakash Sharma]] || Hindi || 1992 || data-sort-value=\"80.1 million\" | >80 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/forensic-science-in-hindi-pulp-fiction-blockbusters-a7645341.html|title=Forensic science in Hindi pulp fiction blockbusters|quote=[Ved Prakash Sharma's] 1992 novel ''Vardi Wala Gunda'' (''The Uniformed Goon'') sold an unprecedented 1.5 million copies on publication day and went on to sell more than 80 million. |last1=Mandhwani|first1=Aakriti|last2=Tripathi|first2=Kartikeya|date=23 March 2017|access-date=28 April 2018|work=[[The Independent#Online presence|The Independent]]}}</ref>{{Better source |reason=The Independednt article does not quote any source. The figure looks dubious. |date=November 2019}} || [[detective fiction|detective]]\n|-\n|''[[The Da Vinci Code]]'' || [[Dan Brown]] || English || 2003 || 80 million<ref>[http://www.mercurynews.com/celebrities/ci_12530761 San Jos\u00e9 Mercury News] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113003131/http://www.mercurynews.com/celebrities/ci_12530761 |date=2012-01-13 }} on ''The Da Vinci Code'': \"That earlier book has sold more than 80 million copies worldwide, was adapted into a movie and made hits out of Brown's previous novels, including \"Angels & Demons,\" whose film version is now in theaters.\" (5 June 2009)</ref>||[[Mystery (fiction)|mystery]] [[Thriller (genre)|thriller]]\n|-\n|''[[Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets]]'' || [[J. K. Rowling]] || English || 1998 || 77 million<ref>[https://www.hypable.com/harry-potter/book-history Hypable] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906134322/https://www.hypable.com/harry-potter/book-history/ |date=2017-09-06 }} on ''Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'': \"As of 2012, the book has sold 77 million copies worldwide and been translated into 72 languages.\" (April 2012)</ref>||[[fantasy]]\n|-\n|''[[Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban]]'' || [[J. K. Rowling]] || English || 1999 || 65 million<ref name=\"fansided.com\">[https://fansided.com/fandom250/harry-potter-jk-rowling FanSided] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824012648/https://fansided.com/fandom250/harry-potter-jk-rowling/ |date=2017-08-24 }} on ''Harry Potter'': \"The success of the books \u2014 every one of which has sold over 65 million copies \u2014 and the films \u2014 which have done billions of dollars worth of box office sales worldwide \u2014 is perhaps the easiest way to demonstrate the sheer size of the Harry Potter fandom.\" (November 2016)</ref>||[[fantasy]]\n|-\n|''[[Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire]]'' || [[J. K. Rowling]] || English || 2000 || 65 million<ref name=\"fansided.com\"/>||[[fantasy]]\n|-\n|''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix]]'' || [[J. K. Rowling]] || English || 2003 || 65 million<ref name=\"fansided.com\"/>||[[fantasy]]\n|-\n|''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]'' || [[J. K. Rowling]] || English || 2005 || 65 million<ref name=\"fansided.com\"/>||[[fantasy]]\n|-\n|''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows]]'' || [[J. K. Rowling]] || English || 2007 || 65 million<ref name=\"fansided.com\"/>||[[fantasy]]\n|-\n|''[[The Catcher in the Rye]]'' || [[J. D. Salinger]] || English || 1951 || 65 million||[[Coming-of-age story|coming-of-age]]\n|-style=\"background-color:lavender;\"\n|-\n|''[[The Bridges of Madison County]]'' || [[Robert James Waller]] || English || 1992 || 60 million<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://triblive.com/aande/theaterarts/9886121-74/county-bridges-stanley|title='The Bridges of Madison County' novel springs to life as a musical|last=Carter|first=Alice T.|website=TribLIVE.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-13|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414082053/http://triblive.com/aande/theaterarts/9886121-74/county-bridges-stanley|archivedate=2017-04-14}}</ref>|| [[romance novel|romance]]\n|-\n|''[[Black Beauty]]'' || [[Anna Sewell]] || English || 1877 || 50 million<ref>[http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/books/children/article3459873.ece The Times] {{