glish\n| (Up to 1965)\n| 11,000,000<ref>{{Cite book|title=70 Years of Best Sellers|page=12,40,79|date=1967|author=Alice Payne Hackett|location=New York, London|publisher=R. R. Bowker}}</ref>\n|-\n|\u4e09\u7701\u5802\u56fd\u8a9e\u8f9e\u5178 (''[[Sanseido Kokugo Jiten]]'') \"Sanseido Dictionary of the Japanese Language\" || [[Kenb\u014d Hidetoshi]] || Japanese || 1960 || 10 million<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sanseido-publ.co.jp/publ/dicts/fuku_meikoku.html |title=Sanseido |publisher=Sanseido-publ.co.jp |accessdate=2009-08-31 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091026233852/http://www.sanseido-publ.co.jp/publ/dicts/fuku_meikoku.html |archivedate=2009-10-26 }}</ref>\n|-\n|\u5bb6\u5ead\u306b\u65bc\u3051\u308b\u5be6\u969b\u7684\u770b\u8b77\u306e\u79d8\u8a23 (''Katei Ni Okeru Jissaiteki Kango No Hiketsu'') \"Key to Practical Personal Care at Home\" || [[Takichi Tsukuda]] || Japanese || 1925 || 10 million<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ne.jp/asahi/matsukinpapa/ucd/tukudaT1.html |title=Tsukuda Takichi Akahon No Page |publisher=Ne.jp |accessdate=2009-08-31 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090110064707/http://www.ne.jp/asahi/matsukinpapa/ucd/tukudaT1.html |archivedate=2009-01-10 }}</ref>\n|-\n|''C\u7a0b\u5e8f\u8bbe\u8ba1'' (''C Program Design'') || [[Tan, Haoqiang]] || Chinese || 1991 || 10 million<ref>[http://paper.people.com.cn/rmrbhwb/html/2009-06/29/content_284606.htm Paper.people.com.cn] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721182044/http://paper.people.com.cn/rmrbhwb/html/2009-06/29/content_284606.htm |date=2011-07-21 }} (June 29, 2009)</ref>\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Books}}\n* [[List of best-selling manga]]\n* [[List of best-selling fiction authors]]\n* [[List of bestselling novels in the United States]]\n* [[List of literary works by number of languages translated into]]\n* [[Lists of books]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100224080326/http://www.ipl.org/div/farq/bestsellerFARQ.html The Internet Public Library]\n* [http://mulibraries.missouri.edu/specialcollections/mott.htm Frank Luther Mott Collection of American Best Sellers, 1662\u20131945] at the [[University of Missouri]]\n\n{{Books}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Best-Selling Books}}\n[[Category:Top book lists|Best-selling]]\n[[Category:Lists of bestsellers|Books]]\n[[Category:Literature records]]\n", "name_user": "Lauchlanmack", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBetween 50 million and 100 million copies", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_best-selling_books"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Dillon, 4th Viscount Dillon", "text_new": "{{Short description|17th-century Irish viscount}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Thomas Dillon, 4th Viscount Dillon\n| image         =\n| alt           =\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = March 1615\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = 1673\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Irish\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Landowner, soldier\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = Loser in the [[Battle of Dungan's Hill]]\n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Thomas Dillon, 4th Viscount Dillon''' [[Privy Council of Ireland|PC (Ire)]] (1615\u20131673) held his title for 42 years that saw the [[Irish Rebellion 1641|Irish Rebellion of 1641]], the [[Irish Confederate Wars]] and the [[Cromwellian Conquest of Ireland]]. He sided with the Confederates but was a moderate who opposed [[Giovanni Battista Rinuccini|Rinuccini]], the papal nuncio. Dillon was an administrator and army officer, who fled the field of the [[Battle of Dungan's Hill]] and did not rescue [[James Butler, 1st Duke of Ormond|Ormond]] at the [[Battle of Rathmines]]. However, he defended [[Athlone]] successfully against [[Henry Ireton|Ireton]] in 1650.\n\n==Birth and origins==\nThomas was born in March 1615{{sfn|Burke|1949|p=[https://archive.org/details/burkesgenealogic1949unse/page/603/ 603]|ps=: \"... [the 4th Viscount] b. March 1615 ...\"}}{{sfn|Webb|1878b|p=[https://archive.org/details/acompendiumiris00webbgoog/page/n156/ 149, line 42]|ps=: \"... was born about 1614 ...\"}}{{sfn|Cokayne|1916|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo04coka/page/358/ 358, line 9]|ps=: \"THOMAS ... uncle and h., being next br. to the 2nd Viscount and then aged 15.\"}} in Ireland. He was the second son of Christopher Dillon and his wife Jane Dillon. His father was the eldest son and [[heir apparent]] of [[Theobald Dillon, 1st Viscount Dillon]]. Christopher predeceased his father and therefore never succeeded as viscount. He was a member of the landed gentry and known as Christopher Dillon of Ballylaghan in [[County Mayo]]. Thomas's mother was the eldest daughter of [[James Dillon, 1st Earl of Roscommon]]. His father's and his mother's family were branches of the same widespread [[Normans in Ireland|Old English]] family, established in Ireland in 1185 when Sir Henry Dillon accompanied [[John, King of England|Prince John]] to Ireland.{{sfn|Webb|1878a|p=[https://archive.org/details/acompendiumiris00webbgoog/page/n157/ 149, line 7]|ps=: \"... [Sir Henry Dillon] came to Ireland in 1185 as secretary to Prince John ...\"}} His parents married in 1604 and had seven sons and five daughters.{{sfn|Burke|1832|p=[https://archive.org/details/ageneralandhera01burkgoog/page/n421/ 367]|ps=: \"CHRISTOPHER (Sir), of Bealalahin, in the county of Mayo, who m. in 1604, Lady Jane Dillon, eldest daughter of James, first Earl of Roscommon, and dying before his father, left seven sons and five daughters.\"}}\n\n[[File:DillonArms.jpg|left|thumb|200px|Arms of Dillon: ''Argent, a lion passant between three crescents gules'']]\n\n<div style=\"float: right; margin: 0 0 0 1em\">\n{{chart top|width=auto|collapsed=no|Family tree}}\n{{chart/start|style=clear: both; font-size: 80%; width: 40em;}}\n{{chart|Txt|Txt=Thomas Dillon with wife, parents, and other selected relatives.|boxstyle_Txt=border: 0 solid white; padding-bottom 1em; text-align: left;}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart/start|style=font-size: 70%;}}\n{{chart| | | | | | |ThbD1|y|Elnor|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |ThbD1=[[Theobald Dillon, 1st Viscount Dillon|Theobald<br>'''1st<br>Viscount''']]<br>{{midsize|d. 1624}}|boxstyle_ThbD1=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: beige;\n |Elnor='''Eleanor<br>Tuite'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1638}}}}\n{{chart| | | | |,|-|-|-|-|^|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v| }}\n{{chart| | | |Chrst|y|Janet| | |Lucas| |JmsDl|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |Chrst='''Christopher<br>Dillon of<br>Ballylaghan'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1624}}\n |Janet='''Janet<br>Dillon'''<br>{{midsize|m. 1604}}\n |Lucas='''Lucas<br>Dillon of<br>Loughglynn'''\n |JmsDl=[[James Dillon (officer)|'''James<br>Dillon''']]<br>{{midsize|c. 1600 \u2013<br>aft. 1669}}}}\n{{chart| |,|-|-|-|v|^|-|-|-|-|-|.|`|-|-|-|.}}\n{{chart|LcsD2| |ThsD4|y|Frncs| |ThbDl| |RbtDl|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |LcsD2=Lucas<br>'''2nd<br>Viscount'''<br>{{midsize|1610\u20131629}}|boxstyle_LcsD2=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: beige;\n |ThsD4=Thomas<br>'''4th<br>Viscount'''<br>{{midsize|1615\u20131673}}|boxstyle_ThsD4=border: 2px solid red; border-radius: 0.5em; background: beige;\n |Frncs='''Frances<br>White'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1664}}\n |ThbDl='''Theobald<br>Dillon'''\n |RbtDl='''Robert<br>Dillon of<br>Loughglynn'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1691}}}}\n{{chart| |!| | | | | |!| | | | |!| | | | |!}}\n{{chart|ThbD3| | | |ThsD5| | |LcsD6| | |ThbD7|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |ThbD3=Theobald<br>'''3rd<br>Viscount'''<br>{{midsize|1629\u20131630}}|boxstyle_ThbD3=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: beige;\n |ThsD5=Thomas<br>'''5th<br>Viscount'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1674}}|boxstyle_ThsD5=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: beige;\n |LcsD6=[[Lucas Dillon, 6th Viscount Dillon|Lucas<br>'''6th<br>Viscount''']]<br>{{midsize|d. 1682}}|boxstyle_LcsD6=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: beige;\n |ThbD7=[[Theobald Dillon, 7th Viscount Dillon|Theobald<br>'''7th<br>Viscount''']]<br>{{midsize|d. 1691<br>Jacobite}}|boxstyle_ThbD7=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: beige;}}\n{{chart| | | | |,|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|-|'}}\n{{chart| | | |HryD8|y| Frn | |Arthr|y|CathS|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |HryD8=[[Henry Dillon, 8th Viscount Dillon|Henry<br>'''8th<br>Viscount''']]<br>{{midsize|d. 1714}}|boxstyle_HryD8=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: beige;\n |Frn='''Frances<br>Hamilton'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1751}}\n |Arthr=[[Arthur Dillon, Count Dillon|'''Arthur''']]<br>{{midsize|1670\u20131733<br>French<br>General}}\n |CathS='''Christina<br>Sheldon'''<br>{{midsize|1684\u20131757}}}}\n{{chart| | | | | |,|'| | |,|-|-|-|v|'}}\n{{chart| | | | |RchD9| |ChD10| |HrD11|y|Chltt|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |RchD9=Richard<br>'''9th<br>Viscount'''<br>{{midsize|1688\u20131737}}|boxstyle_RchD9=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: beige;\n |ChD10=[[Charles Dillon, 10th Viscount Dillon|Charles<br>'''10th<br>Viscount''']]<br>{{midsize|1701\u20131741}}|boxstyle_ChD10=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: beige;\n |HrD11=[[Henry Dillon, 11th Viscount Dillon|Henry<br>'''11th<br>Viscount''']]<br>{{midsize|1705\u20131787}}|boxstyle_HrD11=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: beige;\n |Chltt='''Charlotte<br>Lee'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1794}}}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart/start|style=clear: both;}}\n{{chart|Leg|Leg='''Legend'''|boxstyle_Leg=border: 0 solid white;}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart/start|style=clear: both; font-size: 70%;}}\n{{chart|SbjBx|SbjTx| |Bk1Bx|Bk1Tx|\n |SbjBx=XXX|boxstyle_SbjBx=border: 2px solid red; border-radius: 0.5em; color: white;\n |SbjTx=Thomas<br>Dillon|boxstyle_SbjTx=border: 0 solid white; text-align: left;\n |Bk1Bx=XXX|boxstyle_Bk1Bx=background: beige; border-radius: 0.5em; border-width: 1px; color: beige;\n |Bk1Tx=[[Viscount Dillon|Viscounts<br>Dillon]]|boxstyle_Bk1Tx=border: 0 solid white; text-align: left;}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart/start|style=clear: both; font-size: 80%; width: 40em;}}\n{{chart|Txt|Txt=This family tree is partly derived from the Dillon family tree pictured in La Tour du Pin.{{sfn|La Tour du Pin|1913|pp=[https://archive.org/details/journaldunefemme01lato/page/14/ 14\u201315]|ps=: \"Note g\u00e9n\u00e9alogique sur la Maison des Lords Dillon\"}} Also see the lists of siblings and children in the text.|boxstyle_Txt=border: 0 solid white; text-align: left;}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart_bottom}}\n</div>\n\nHe appears below among his brothers as the second son:\n#Lucas (1610\u20131629), who was the 2nd Viscount Dillon;{{sfn|Lodge|1789b|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/185/ 185, line 19]|ps=: \"Lucas, the eldest son, and second Viscount Dillon, was 14 years and 6 months old when he succeeded his grandfather ...\"}}\n#'''Thomas''' (1615\u20131673), the subject of this article;\n#Theobald, the father of the 6th Viscount.{{sfn|Lodge|1789b|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/185/ 185, line 11]|ps=: \"Theobald, the father of Lucas, the 6th Viscount;\"}}\n#James, never married;{{sfn|Lodge|1789b|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/185/ 185, line 12a]|ps=: \"James, who died without issue;\"}}\n#John, married Bingham's widow;{{sfn|Lodge|1789b|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/185/ 185, line 12b]|ps=: \"... as did John, who married the widow of ___ Bingham, esq.;\"}}\n#Christopher, died young;{{sfn|Lodge|1789b|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/185/ 185, line 14a]|ps=: \"... Christopher, and Francis, died young;\"}} and\n#Francis, who died young.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTELodge1789b[httpsarchiveorgdetailspeerageofireland04lodgpage185 185, line 14a]\"/>\n\nHe also had sisters including:\n#Joan, married John O'Madden, chief of his sept in the barony of Longford, Count Galway;{{sfn|Lodge|1789b|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/185/ 185, line 14b]|ps=: \"... daughter Joan, married to John O'Madden, chief of his sept in the barony of Longford, in county of Galway&nbsp;...\"}} \n#Elizabeth, became a nun in the Order of St. Clare;{{sfn|Lodge|1789b|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/185/ 185, line 17]|ps=: \"... Elizabeth, and Mary, nuns of the order of St. Clare; \"}}\n#Mary, became a nun in the order of St. Clare;<ref name=\"FOOTNOTELodge1789b[httpsarchiveorgdetailspeerageofireland04lodgpage185 185, line 17]\"/>\n#Eleanora, died young;{{sfn|Lodge|1789b|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/185/ 185, line 18]|ps=: \"... Eleanora, and Mary, both died young.\"}} and\n#Mary, died young.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTELodge1789b[httpsarchiveorgdetailspeerageofireland04lodgpage185 185, line 18]\"/>\n\n==Viscount==\nOn 28 February 1624 his father died{{sfn|Cokayne|1916|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo04coka/page/357/ 357, line 33]|ps=: \"Christopher was s. and h. ap. of the last Viscount but d. v.p., 28 Feb 1623/4.\"}} and his grandfather followed him into the grave two weeks later on 15 March 1624.{{sfn|Debrett|1828|p=[https://archive.org/details/debrettspeerage01debrgoog/page/n326/ 748, line 9]|ps=: \"... and [the 1st Viscount] d. 15 March 1624 ...\"}} His elder brother Lucas succeeded his grandfather as the 2nd Viscount Dillon. Lucas was viscount for about five years and died in 1629,{{sfn|Cokayne|1916|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo04coka/page/358/ 358, line 2]|ps=: \"He [the 2nd Viscount] d. at Killenfagny, co. Westmeath, 13 Apr. and was bur. 14 Sept. 1629 in the Friary of Athlone.\"}} leaving a three months old child, Theobald,{{sfn|Lodge|1789b|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/185/ 185, line 30]|ps=: \"Theobald, the third Viscount, at the death of his father ...\"}} who became the 3rd Viscount and a [[Ward (law)|ward]] of the King but lasted only about a year dying on 13 May 1630 in his infancy.{{sfn|Cokayne|1916|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo04coka/page/358/ 358, line 8]|ps=: \"He [the 3rd Viscount] d. an infant, 13 May 1630.\"}} Thomas, his uncle, succeeded as the 4th Viscount. As he was 15 at the time, he entered immediately into the possession of the estate.{{sfn|Lodge|1789b|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/185/ 185, line 33]|ps=: \"Thomas, the 4th Viscount, who being within age, viz. 15 years old at the accession to the honour ; K. Charles I by indenture, bearing date of 8 December same year [1630] demised and to farm set, the estates then very considerable ...\"}} Lord Dillon, as he was now, in that same year converted to [[Protestantism]], was received into the [[Church of Ireland]],{{sfn|Henderson|1888|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati15stepuoft/page/86/ 86, right column]|ps=: \"... he [the 4th Viscount] declared himself a protestant.\"}} and on 16 March 1640 took his seat in the [[House of Lords]] of the [[Parliament of Ireland|Irish Parliament]],{{sfn|Cokayne|1916|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo04coka/page/358/ 358, line 12]|ps=: \"... having declared himself a Protestant, took his seat in the House of Lords [I.] 16 March 1639/40.\"}} which Catholic peers usually refused to do because of the [[oath of supremacy]]. He even became a member of thye Privy council.{{sfn|Lodge|1789b|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/183/ 183, last line]|ps=: \"... and 23 October 1640 we find him a Lord of the Privy Council&nbsp;...\"}}\n\n==Marriage and children==\nIn 1635 Lord Dillon married Frances White, daughter of Nicholas White, esquire, of [[Leixlip]],{{sfn|Cokayne|1916|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo04coka/page/358/ 358, line 21]|ps=: \"He m., before 1636, Frances da. of Sir Nicholas WHITE of Leixlip, by Ursula, 1st da. of Garrett (MOORE) 1st VISCOUNT MOORE OF DROGHEDA.}}{{sfn|Burke1949|p=[https://archive.org/details/burkesgenealogic1949unse/page/603/ 603, left column, line 42]|ps=: \"... m. 1635, Frances, dau. of Nicholas White of Leixlip ...\"}} and granddaughter of [[Garret Moore, 1st Viscount Moore]] by her mother Ursula Moore.{{sfn|Lodge|1789a|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland02lodg/page/100/ 100, line 10]|ps=: \"Daughter Ursula was married to Sir Nicholas White of Leixlip, in the county of Kildare ...\"}} She brought him a dowry of \u00a33000. Her sister Mary White married [[Theobald Taaffe, 1st Earl of Carlingford|Theobald Taaffe, the 2nd Viscount Taaffe]] (later 1st Earl of Carlingford), who thus became his brother-in-law.{{sfn|Cokayne|1913|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo03coka/page/28/ 28, line 19]|ps=: \"He [Taaffe] m., 1stly, Mary, 1st da. of Sir Nicholas WHITE of Leixlip, co. Kildare, by Ursula, 1st da. of Garrett, 1st VISCOUNT MOORE OF DROGHEDA.\"}}\n\nThe couple had six sons and an unknown number of daughters. The sons were:\n#Charles (born 1636 or before), who was a general in French and Spanish service;{{sfn|Burke|1949|p=[https://archive.org/details/burkesgenealogic1949unse/page/603/ 603, left column, line 44]|ps=: \"Charles, Gen in the French and Spanish services, Gov. of Tournay, b. 1636, d.s.p., before his father.\"}}\n#Christopher (died 1663), who never married;{{sfn|Lodge|1789b|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/189/ 189, line 26]|ps=: \"Christopher who died in Winetavern-Street unmarried and was buried by his mother 20 June 1663.\"}}\n#Rupert, who died while being a page to Charles II, during his exile;{{sfn|Burke|1949|p=[https://archive.org/details/burkesgenealogic1949unse/page/603/ 603, left column, line 46]|ps=: \"Rupert, page to CHARLES II, k. on service.\"}}\n#Thomas (died 1674), who became the 5th Viscount;{{sfn|Lodge|1789b|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/189/ 189, line 36]|ps=: \"Thomas, the 5th Viscount Dillon married Elizabeth, eldest daughter of Sir John Bourke of Derymaclagtny in the county of Galway ... and his Lordship deceasing 1674, the honour devolved on Lucas Dillon, eldest son of Theobald, third son of Sir Christopher Dillon, eldest son of Theobald, the first Viscount.\"}}{{sfn|Burke|1949|p=[https://archive.org/details/burkesgenealogic1949unse/page/603/ 603, left column, line 47]|ps=: \"THOMAS, 5th Viscount. His only surviving son.\"}}\n#Ormond, who died young;{{sfn|Lodge|1789b|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/189/ 189, line 34]|ps=: \"Ormond, and Nicholas, died young.\"}}\n#Nicholas, who died young.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTELodge1789b[httpsarchiveorgdetailspeerageofireland04lodgpage189 189, line 34]\"/>\n\n==Irish wars==\nIn October 1641 the [[Irish Rebellion of 1641|Irish Rebellion]] broke out. In February 1642, the Irish Parliament sent Lord Dillon and his brother-in-law Lord Taaffe to England to submit grievances to [[Charles I of England]]. However, they were intercepted at [[Ware, Hertfordshire|Ware]] by order of the [[English House of Commons]].{{sfn|Warner|1768a|p=[https://archive.org/details/historyrebellio00warngoog/page/n150/ 130]|ps=: \"What the private instructions were that Lord DILLON was entrusted with are not particularly known; because ... when he and Lord TAAFE who accompanied him were got to Ware, their persons and papers were seized by order of the English House of Commons;\"}} They escaped a few months later and met the King at York.{{sfn|Webb|1878b|p=[https://archive.org/details/acompendiumiris00webbgoog/page/n156/ 149, line 48]|ps=: \"Being on a mission to King Charles in February 1641-'2, he was, with Lord Taaffe, seized at Ware by order of the House of Commons. After some months' imprisonment, they escaped and joined the King at York.\"}} Upon Dillon's return to Ireland, he was made Lieutenant-General, and was appointed [[President of Connaught]], a position he was to hold jointly with [[Henry Wilmot, 2nd Viscount Wilmot]]. He was briefly one of the [[Lord Justices (Ireland)|Lords Justices for Ireland]].\n\nThe rebel nobility established a [[Confederate Ireland#Members of the Supreme Council of the Confederation of Kilkenny.2C November 1642|Supreme Council]] of 25 men in November 1642. Dillon was one of the 6 members from [[Connacht]]. With the arrival of the papal nuncio, [[Giovanni Battista Rinuccini]], in Ireland on 21 October 1645{{sfn|Coffey|1914|p=[https://archive.org/details/oneillormondchap00coffuoft/page/152/ 152, line 16]|ps=: \"... landed at Kenmare October, 21st [1645].\"}} Dillon's Protestant religion caused him problems. He decided to convert back to Catholicism and on 6 December 1646 Dillon was received back into the [[Roman Catholic Church]] by the Nuncio at St Mary's Church,{{efn|This is the old parish church in the centre of the town, not [[St Mary's Cathedral, Kilkenny|St Mary's Cathedral]], built in the 19th century.}} Kilkenny.{{sfn|Lodge|1789b|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/187/ 187, line 12]|ps=: \"... where 6 December 1646, he was reconciled by the nuncio to the Church of Rome, according to the Roman Pontifical in St. Mary's Church before a vast concourse of people;\"}} He had left Athlone under the command of Captain MacGawly, who betrayed him and handed the town over to [[Eoghan Ruadh \u00d3 N\u00e9ill|Owen Roe O'Neill]]. After his conversion the Confederate Council ordered O'Neill to give the town back to Dillon, but O'Neill refused.{{sfn|Coffey|1914|p=[https://archive.org/details/oneillormondchap00coffuoft/page/191/ 191]|ps=: \"O'Neill still held Athlone, though ordered to give it back to Lord Costello by the Council\"}}\n\nIn August 1647, the Confederate Leinster army under [[Thomas Preston, 1st Viscount Tara|Thomas Preston]] was severely beaten in the [[Battle of Dungan's Hill]] by Parliamentarian troops under [[Michael Jones (soldier)|Michael Jones]]. At this occasion Dillon commanded the Confederate cavalry, which fled in the early stages of the battle.{{sfn|Lenihan|2004|p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613660/page/226/ 226, left column, line 10]|ps=: \"Dillon joined the Leinster confederate Catholic army and led the cavalry contingent at the catastrophic defeat at Dungan's Hill in August 1647.\"}}\n\nDillon is mentioned several times in the Peace Treaty of 17 January 1648/9 between the [[Confederate Ireland|Irish Confederates]] and [[James Butler, 1st Duke of Ormonde|Ormonde]], acting for [[Charles I of England]], as \"Thomas lord viscount Dillon of Costologh\" (i.e. Costello-Gallen)\". [[John Milton]] called him an \"archrebel\".{{sfn|Milton|1649|p=[https://archive.org/details/proseworksofjohn00milt/page/263/ 263]|ps=: \"... a standing army of papists at the beck and command of Dillon, Muskerry, and other archrebels ...\"}}\n\nIn 1649 Dillon took part in Ormonde's unsuccessful [[Siege of Dublin (1649)|Siege of Dublin]]. He blockaded the [[Northside, Dublin|Northside]] of the town with 2500 men{{sfn|Hayes-McCoy|1990|p=[https://archive.org/details/irishbattlesmili0000haye/page/206/ 206, line 30]|ps=: \"He left 2,500 men under Lord Dillon on the north side of the river Liffey ...\"}} and did not intervene, when General [[Michael Jones (soldier)|Michael Jones]] sallied in the south-east and defeated Ormond in the [[Battle of Rathmines]] on 2 August 1649.{{sfn|Lenihan|2004|p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613660/page/226/ 226, left column, line 26]|ps=: \"On 2 August a surprise attack overran Ormond's camp; at some point in the battle Ormond sent a message ordering Dillon to march south and attack the rear of the parliamentary army. Dillon refused, probably because it seemed to him to be too late to prevent a rout.\"}} After the battle Dillon retreated northwards to [[Trim, County Meath|Trim]]. Some of his troops went to reinforce the garrison of [[Drogheda]] but he himself had no part in the ensuing [[Siege of Drogheda]] by [[Oliver Cromwell|Cromwell]], 3\u201311 September 1649.\n\nIn 1650 Dillon successfully defended [[Athlone]] against a Parliamentarian army under [[Henry Ireton]], skilfully holding him off by protracted parleys until Ireton decided to leave and rather reinforce [[Hardress Waller]] at the [[Siege of Limerick (1650\u20131651)|siege of Limerick]]. However too much time had been lost and the parliamentarians took neither of these towns in the campaign of 1650.{{sfn|Warner|1768b|p=[https://archive.org/details/historyrebellio01warngoog/page/n233/ 228, line 8]|ps=: \"... IRETON, joining his army to SR C. COOTE's, advanced to Athlone in order to take in that garrison, but finding the bridge broken and the town on that side burned, COOTE was left to block it up and IRETON ...  joined his army before Limerick.\"}} [[Charles Coote, 1st Earl of Mountrath|Coote]] later took Athlone in 1651.\n\nDillon's estates were confiscated by the [[Act for the Settlement of Ireland 1652|Cromwellian Settlement]] of 1652, and he and his family lived in exile on the continent until the [[English Restoration|Restoration]].\n\n==Restoration, later life and death==\nIn 1663 most of his extensive lands were restored by the [[Act of Settlement 1662]], and several high offices in the state were conferred upon him, including that of [[Custos Rotulorum of Westmeath]]. However Dudley Costello, who was from a family of Gaelic freeholders that had been cheated out of their land by the 1st Viscount, resisted by organising rapparee actions. He was eventually shot in a skirmish in eastern [[County Mayo]] in 1667.{{sfn|Carte|1851|p=[https://archive.org/details/lifeofjamesdukeo04cart/page/256/ 256]|ps=: \"Costellogh ventured in the night to attack one of them, commanded by Captain Theobald Dillon, supposing them to be raw men, and easily frighted; but met with so warm a reception, that he was shot dead on the spot ...\"}}\n\nAfter 1669 Dillon inherited an estate of {{convert|2500|acre|km2}} in [[County Mayo]] and [[County Roscommon]] from his uncle, Sir [[James Dillon (officer)|James Dillon]], youngest son of the 1st Viscount.\n\nDillon died about 1673{{sfn|Cokayne|1916|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo04coka/page/358/ 358, line 25]|ps=: \"He d. in 1673 or 1674.}}{{sfn|Burke1949|p=[https://archive.org/details/burkesgenealogic1949unse/page/603/ 603, left column, line 43]|ps=: \"... and d. 1672-3 ...\"}} and was succeeded by Thomas, his only surviving son, as the 5th Viscount.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEBurke1949[httpsarchiveorgdetailsburkesgenealogic1949unsepage603 603, left column, line 47]\"/> When the 5th Viscount's died childless, the title passed to his first cousin Lucas, the 6th Viscount, and thereafter to the [[Loughglynn]] branch of the family, which descended from the 1st Viscount through his second son, Lucas Dillon of Loughglynn.\n\nMost likely, Frances, his wife, outlived him and died in 1674, being buried in St. Mary's Chapel in [[Christ Church Cathedral, Dublin|Christ Church Cathedral]].{{sfn|Cokayne|1916|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo04coka/page/358/ 358, line 23]|ps=: \"She [Frances], who brought him \u00a33000 fortune, d. 20 and was bur. 23 Dec 1674, in St. Mary's Chapel in Christchurch.}} However, [[John Lodge (archivist)|John Lodge]] thought that Frances was the Lady Dillon who has been recorded as dying in 1664 in Dillon's house in Winetavern Street, Dublin, and was buried at [[St James' Church, Dublin (Church of Ireland)|St James's]].{{sfn|Lodge|1789b|p=[https://archive.org/details/peerageofireland04lodg/page/189/ 189, line 16]|ps=: \"... who died in Winetavern-street and was buried in St. James's, 9 January 1664.\"}}\n\n{| {{Table|hide}}\n!colspan=3|Timeline\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Age!!align=\"left\"|Date!!align=\"left\"|Event\n|-\n|0||1615, Mar||Born.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEBurke1949[httpsarchiveorgdetailsburkesgenealogic1949unsepage603 603]\"/>\n|-\n|{{age|1615|3|1624|2}}10||1624, 28 Feb||His father, Christopher Dillon, died.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTECokayne1916[httpsarchiveorgdetailscompletepeerageo04cokapage357 357, line 33]\"/>\n|-\n|10||1624, 15 Mar||His grandfather, [[Theobald Dillon, 1st Viscount Dillon|Theobald Dillon, the 1st Viscount]], died<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEDebrett1828[httpsarchiveorgdetailsdebrettspeerage01debrgoogpagen326 748, line 9]\"/> and was succeeded by his eldest son Lucas Dillon.\n|-\n|14||1629, 13 Apr||His elder brother, Lucas, the 2nd Viscount, died and was succeeded by his posthumous infant son Theobald.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTECokayne1916[httpsarchiveorgdetailscompletepeerageo04cokapage358 358, line 2]\"/>\n|-\n|15||1630, 13 May||His nephew, Theobald, the 3rd Viscount, died and Thomas, the subject of this article, succeeded as the 4th Viscount.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTECokayne1916[httpsarchiveorgdetailscompletepeerageo04cokapage358 358, line 8]\"/>\n|-\n|15||1630||He made himself a Protestant.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEHenderson1888[httpsarchiveorgdetailsdictionaryofnati15stepuoftpage86 86, right column]\"/>\n|-\n|21||1635||Married Frances White.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTECokayne1916[httpsarchiveorgdetailscompletepeerageo04cokapage358 358, line 21]\"/><ref name=\"FOOTNOTEBurke1949[httpsarchiveorgdetailsburkesgenealogic1949unsepage603 603, left column, line 42]\"/>\n|-\n|21||1636||Charles, his eldest son, born.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEBurke1949[httpsarchiveorgdetailsburkesgenealogic1949unsepage603 603, left column, line 44]\"/>\n|-\n|24||1640, 16 Mar||He took his seat in the [[Irish House of Lords|House of Lords]] of the [[Parliament of Ireland|Irish Parliament]].<ref name=\"FOOTNOTECokayne1916[httpsarchiveorgdetailscompletepeerageo04cokapage358 358, line 12]\"/>\n|-\n|27||1642, Feb||He and [[Theobald Taaffe, 1st Earl of Carlingford|Taaffe]] were sent by the Irish Parliament to England to submit grievances to [[Charles I of England|Charles I]].<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEWebb1878b[httpsarchiveorgdetailsacompendiumiris00webbgoogpagen156 149, line 48]\"/>\n|-\n|31||1646, 6 Dec||Converted back to Catholicism.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTELodge1789b[httpsarchiveorgdetailspeerageofireland04lodgpage187 187, line 12]\"/>\n|-\n|32||1647, Aug||Commanded the Confederate cavalry at the [[Battle of Dungan's Hill]].<ref name=\"FOOTNOTELenihan2004[httpsarchiveorgdetailsisbn_0198613660page226 226, left column, line 10]\"/>\n|-\n|34||1649||Blockaded the northern side of the [[River Liffey|Liffey]] during [[James Butler, 1st Duke of Ormond|Ormond's]] [[Siege of Dublin (1649)|Siege of Dublin]].<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEHayes-McCoy1990[httpsarchiveorgdetailsirishbattlesmili0000hayepage206 206, line 30]\"/>\n|-\n|35||1650||Defended [[Athlone]] successfully against a parliamentarian army under [[Henry Ireton]].\n|-\n|37||1652||His estates confiscated by the [[Act for the Settlement of Ireland 1652|Cromwellian Settlement Act]].\n|-\n|48||1663||Most of his land restored to him by the [[Act of Settlement 1662|Act of Settlement]].\n|-\n|52||1667, 3 May||The [[rapparee]] [[Dubhaltach Caoch Mac Coisdealbhaigh|Dudley Costello]] is shot dead in [[Coolcarney]].<ref name=\"FOOTNOTECarte1851[httpsarchiveorgdetailslifeofjamesdukeo04cartpage256 256]\"/>\n|-\n|58||1673||Died<ref name=\"FOOTNOTECokayne1916[httpsarchiveorgdetailscompletepeerageo04cokapage358 358, line 25]\"/><ref name=\"FOOTNOTEBurke1949[httpsarchiveorgdetailsburkesgenealogic1949unsepage603 603, left column, line 43]\"/> and was succeeded by his son, also called Thomas Dillon, as the 5th Viscount.\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Viscount Dillon]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Notelist}}\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{citation|last=Burke |first=John |author-link=John Burke (genealogist) |date=1832 |title=A General and Heraldic Dictionary of the Peerage and Baronetage of the British Empire |edition=4th |volume=1 |publisher=Henry Colburn and Richard Bentley |publication-place=London |url=https://archive.org/details/ageneralandhera01burkgoog/}} \u2013 Abdy to Hutchinson\n*{{citation|last=Burke |first=Bernard |author-link=Bernard Burke |date=1949 |title=A Genealogical and Heraldic Dictionary of the Peerage and Baronetage of the British Empire |edition=99th |publisher=Burke's Peerage Ltd. |publication-place=London |url=https://archive.org/details/burkesgenealogic1949unse/}} (for Dillon)\n*{{citation|last=Carte |first=Thomas |author-link=Thomas Carte |date=1851 |title=The Life of James Duke of Ormond |edition=new |volume=4 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |publication-place=Oxford |url=https://archive.org/details/lifeofjamesdukeo04cart/}} - 1660\u20131688 (for Dudley Costellogh)\n*{{citation|last=Coffey |first=Diarmid |da