hive.org/details/proseworksofjohn00milt/page/247/ |ref=CITEREFMilton1649}}\n*{{citation|last=Warner |first=Ferdinand |date=1768a |title=History of the Rebellion and Civil-War in Ireland |volume=1 |publisher=James William |publication-place=Dublin |url=https://archive.org/details/historyrebellio00warngoog/}} \u2013 from the Rebellion to the Cessation\n*{{citation|last=Warner |first=Ferdinand |date=1768b |title=History of the Rebellion and Civil-War in Ireland |volume=2 |publisher=James William |publication-place=Dublin |url=https://archive.org/details/historyrebellio01warngoog/}}\n*{{citation|last=Webb |first=Alfred |date=1878a |title=Dillon, Theobald, Viscount |dictionary=Compendium of Irish Biography |publisher=M. H. Gill & Son |publication-place=Dublin |page=[https://archive.org/details/acompendiumiris00webbgoog/page/n157/ 149] |url=https://archive.org/details/acompendiumiris00webbgoog/}}\n*{{citation|last=Webb |first=Alfred |date=1878b |title=Dillon, Thomas, 4th Viscount |dictionary=Compendium of Irish Biography |publisher=M. H. Gill & Son |publication-place=Dublin |pages=[https://archive.org/details/acompendiumiris00webbgoog/page/n157/ 149\u2013150] |url=https://archive.org/details/acompendiumiris00webbgoog/}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thepeerage.com/p37097.htm#i370965 Genealogy of Thomas Dillon, 4th Viscount Dillon of Costello-Gallin on The Peerage website]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-reg|ie}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Viscount Dillon]] | years=1630&ndash;-1673 | before=Theobald Dillon| after=Thomas Dillon}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dillon, Thomas Dillon, 4th Viscount Dillon}}\n\n[[Category:1615 births]]\n[[Category:1673 deaths]]\n[[Category:17th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:Irish expatriates]]\n[[Category:Irish soldiers in the Irish Confederate Wars]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of Ireland]]\n[[Category:People from County Mayo]]\n[[Category:Viscounts Dillon]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: an skirmish \u2192 a skirmish (2), to late \u2192 too late - per source, though this isn't quite an exact quote.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Dillon,_4th_Viscount_Dillon"}
{"title_page": "Rana dynasty", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{short description|Nepali Kshetri dynasty of rulers}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2011}}\n{{Royal house|\n| surname        = Rana dynasty\n| native_name    = \u0930\u093e\u0923\u093e \u0935\u0902\u0936\n| native_name_lang = ne\n| other_name     = Ranas of Nepal\n| type           = [[Royal House]]\n| estates        = [[Rana palaces of Nepal]]\n| coat of arms   = Coat of Arms of Rana dynasty.jpg\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Kingdom of Nepal]]\n* Kingdom of [[Kaski District|Kaski]] & [[Lamjung district|Lamjung]] (under [[Nepal]])}}\n| titles         = {{Plainlist|\n* Titular King of [[Kaski District|Kaski]] & [[Lamjung district|Lamjung]]\n* [[Sri|Shree Tin]] [[Maharaja]]\n* [[Rana (title)|Ranajyu/Ranaji]] [[Saheb]]}}\n| founder        = [[Jung Bahadur Rana]]\n|parent house =  [[Kunwar family of Gorkha]]\n| final ruler    = [[Mohan Shumsher]]\n| current head   = presently as [[pretender]]\n|motto           = ''[[Janani Janmabhumishcha Swargadapi Gariyasi]]''<ref>https://www.hubert-herald.nl/Nepal.htm#_ednref6</ref>\n|motto_lang      = sa\n|motto_trans     = Mother and Motherland are superior to heaven.\n| founding year  = 1846 A.D.\n| deposition     = 1951 A.D.\n| religion       = Hinduism\n|cadet_branches = \n| notes = The family were [[Kunwar family|Kunwars]] which was historically a [[Chhetri]] clan.{{sfn|Regmi|1975|p=90}}\n}}\n{{History of Nepal}}\n{{Ranas of Nepal}}\n'''Rana dynasty''' ({{lang-ne|\u0930\u093e\u0923\u093e \u0935\u0902\u0936}}; [[IAST]]: ''R\u0101\u1e47\u0101 va\u1e43\u015ba'') is [[Chhetri]]{{refn|group=note|Founder of this dynasty, [[Jang Bahadur Rana]], was a noble of [[Khas people|Khas community]].<ref>{{Cite book |author=Dor Bahadur Bista |author-link=Dor Bahadur Bista |title=Fatalism and Development: Nepal's Struggle for Modernization |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JzFROpFVYRAC&pg=PA48 |year=1991 |publisher=Orient Blackswan |isbn=978-81-250-0188-1 |ref=harv}}</ref> He belonged to [[Kunwar family]] which was historically a [[Chhetri]] clan.{{sfn|Regmi|1975|p=90}} They also had marital relations with other Chhetri families as [[Thapa dynasty]] of Mukhtiyar [[Bhimsen Thapa]] and [[Pande dynasty]] of [[Ranajit Pande]].<ref name=\"PurushottamShamsher1990\" />}} dynasty from the [[Indian subcontinent]]<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book |title=Greater Game |author=Van PraaghD |date=2003 |publisher=MQUP |isbn=978-0-7735-7130-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KVDIvLQDGckC&pg=PA319 |page=319 |accessdate=11 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911115456/https://books.google.com/books?id=KVDIvLQDGckC&pg=PA319 |archive-date=11 September 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> that ruled the [[Kingdom of Nepal]] from 1846 A.D until 1951 A.D, reducing the [[Shah dynasty|Shah monarch]] to a figurehead and making [[List of Prime Ministers of Nepal|Prime Minister]] and other government positions held by the Ranas hereditary. They claimed [[Kshatriya]] status themselves.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dietrich |first=Angela |title=Buddhist Monks and Rana Rulers: A History of Persecution |url=http://ccbs.ntu.edu.tw/FULLTEXT/JR-BH/bh117536.htm |accessdate=17 September 2013 |newspaper=Buddhist Himalaya: A Journal of Nagarjuna Institute of Exact Methods |year=1996 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001124156/http://ccbs.ntu.edu.tw/FULLTEXT/JR-BH/bh117536.htm |archive-date=1 October 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lal |first=C. K. |title=The Rana resonance |url=http://nepalitimes.com/news.php?id=8741 |accessdate=17 September 2013 |newspaper=[[Nepali Times]] |date=16 February 2001 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928013152/http://nepalitimes.com/news.php?id=8741 |archive-date=28 September 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> Rana dynasty is historically known for the ''[[Totalitarianism|iron-fisted rule]]''.<ref>http://archive.nepalitimes.com/article/Nepali-Times-Buzz/the-rana-reign-a-recap-of-history,3751</ref> This changed after the [[Revolution of 1951]] with the promulgation of a new constitution, when power shifted back to the monarchy of [[King Tribhuvan]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Kraemer |first=Karl-Heinz |title=Democratization and political parties in Nepal |url=http://nepalresearch.org/publications/harvard_9903.htm |publisher=Harvard University |accessdate=25 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524165715/http://nepalresearch.org/publications/harvard_9903.htm |archive-date=24 May 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Rana dynasty descended from the [[Kunwar family]], a nobility of the [[Gorkha Kingdom]].{{sfn|Joshi|Rose|1966|p=30}} Due to the marital lineages with the politically reigning [[Thapa dynasty]] (of ''[[Mukhtiyar]]'' [[Bhimsen Thapa]]) from early 19th century, Ranas gained entry to central [[Durbar (court)|Darbar]] politics.{{sfn|Acharya|2012|p=11-12}}<ref name=\"PurushottamShamsher1990\" /> Ranas were also linked to the minor faction of another politically acclaimed [[Pande dynasty]] of Gorkha through Thapa dynasty.<ref name=\"PurushottamShamsher1990\" />\n\n== Genealogy ==\nChronicler Daniel Wright has published the genealogy of [[Jang Bahadur Kunwar Rana]]. The genealogy begins with Tatt\u0101 R\u0101\u1e47\u0101 as [[Raja]] (King) of [[Chittaurgarh]].{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=285}} His nephew Fakht Si\u1e43ha R\u0101\u1e47\u0101 had a son named R\u0101ma Si\u1e43ha R\u0101\u1e47\u0101, who came to hills after the siege of Chittaur.{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=285}} He was employed by a hill Raja for ten or twelve months who wanted to retain R\u0101ma Si\u1e43ha in his country. The hill Raja asked for the daughter of [[Raja]] of B\u012bn\u0101t\u012b, a Bag\u0101le [[Kshetri|K\u1e63etr\u012b]] and married her to R\u0101ma Si\u1e43ha.{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=285}} They had six sons over 10-12 years, one of whom was recognized by the title of ''[[Kunwar|Kum\u0310vara]] [[Khadka|Kha\u1e0dk\u0101]]'' for bravery displayed in the battle against Raja of Sat\u0101n Ko\u1e6d.{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=285}} The title was used by his descendants. R\u0101ma Si\u1e43ha was suddenly met by his younger brother who requested him to return Chittaur for once and R\u0101ma Si\u1e43ha died reaching there.{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=286}} The hill Raja made R\u0101ma Si\u1e43ha's son R\u0101ut Kunwar a nobleman (Sard\u0101r) and commandant of the army.{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=286}} Ahir\u0101ma Kunwar, a son of R\u0101ut Kunwar, was invited by King of Kaski and was made nobleman with a birta or jagir of Dhuage Saghu village.{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=286}} King of Kaski asked the hand of Ahir\u0101ma's daughter, who was a great beauty through only Kalas Puja to which Ahir\u0101ma replied to give his daughter only through lawful marriage.{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=286}} King brought his troops and tried to take on the village by force.{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=286}} Ahir\u0101ma was supported by the villagers belonging to Par\u0101jul\u012b Th\u0101p\u0101 caste and a war was initiated.{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=286}} On the same day, Ahir\u0101ma took his immediate family including two sons namely; [[Ram Krishna Kunwar]] and Jaya Krishna Kunwar, to King of Gorkha, [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]] where lands of Kunwar-Khola was given to them as ''birta''.{{sfn|Wright|1877|pp=286-87}}\n\n[[John Whelpton]] opines that Kunwar origin legend which states that first of their ancestors to enter hill married a daughter of Bagale Kshetri might have directed their family links to [[Bagale Thapa]], the clan of Mukhtiyar [[Bhimsen Thapa]].{{sfn|Whelpton|1991|p=36}}\n\nRana dynasts; Prabhakar, Gautam and [[Pashupati Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]] claim the descent of Ranas of Nepal from ''Kunwar'' Kumbhakaran Singh, younger brother of [[Guhila_dynasty|Guhila]] King of [[Mewar]], Rawal [[Ratnasimha]]. During the [[Siege of Chittorgarh (1303)|first siege of Chittorgarh]] in 1303 A.D., Kumbhakaran Singh's descendants left [[Mewar]] to north towards Himalayan foothills according to the book \" Rana's Of Nepal\" where the preface is written by [[Arvind Singh Mewar]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://books.google.com/?id=GE1uAAAAMAAJ&q=ranas+of+nepal&dq=ranas+of+nepal |title=THE RANAS OF NEPAL |last1=Rana |first1=Prabhakar S. J. B. |last2=Rana |first2=Pashupati Shumshere Jung Bahadur |last3=Rana |first3=Gautam S. J. B. |year=2003}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.np/books?redir_esc=y&id=GE1uAAAAMAAJ&dq=ranas+of+nepal&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Arvind+Singh+mewar|title=Ranas Of Nepal|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n== Historical background ==\n{{See|Kunwar family}}\n[[File:Ram Krishna Kunwar.jpg|thumb|left|''[[Sardar]]'' [[Ram Krishna Kunwar]], prominent male ancestor of Ranas of Nepal]]\nThe founder of this dynasty was [[Jang Bahadur Rana]], who belonged to [[Kunwar family]] which was then considered a minor noble family of [[Kshatriya]] status.{{sfn|Joshi|Rose|1966|p=30}} Jang Bahadur was a son of Gorkhali governor [[Bal Narsingh Kunwar]] and nephew of [[Mathabarsingh Thapa]]{{sfn|Acharya|2012|p=11-12}}, the reigning [[Prime Minister of Nepal]] (1843\u20131845) from the [[Thapa dynasty]].{{sfn|Acharya|2012|p=177-178}} Bal Narsingh Kunwar was the son of Kaji [[Ranajit Kunwar]] and grandson of ''[[Sardar]]'' [[Ram Krishna Kunwar]]{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=193}}, who was prominent military general of King [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]].{{sfn|Adhikari|1984|p=27}}{{sfn|Hamal|1995|pp=180-181}} Ram Krishna Kunwar was born to Ahiram Kunwar.{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=193}} There were ample of rewards and recognitions received by ''Sardar'' Ram Krishna Kunwar from the Gorkhali monarch Prithvi Narayan.{{sfn|Hamal|1995|p=181}} His grandson Bal Narsingh was initially a follower of the renounced King [[Rana Bahadur Shah]] and Kaji [[Bhimsen Thapa]], and followed the King in his exile to [[Banaras]] on 1 May 1800.{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=13}} On the night of 25 April 1806, King Rana Bahadur was killed by step-brother Sher Bahadur in desperation after which Bal Narsingh immediately killed the King's assassin.{{sfn|Acharya|2012|p=67}}{{sfn|Nepal|2007|pp=62\u201363}}{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|pp=27-28}} He was a close ally of the influential minister Bhimsen Thapa{{sfn|Acharya|2012|p=67}}, who initiated a great massacre at Bhandarkhal garden following the chaos from the King's murder.{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=28}}{{sfn|Acharya|2012|pp=68\u201371}}{{sfn|Nepal|2007|pp=63\u201364}} Following closeness to Mukhtiyar Bhimsen, he became the son-in-law of Bhimsen's brother ''Kaji '' [[Nain Singh Thapa]] of [[Thapa dynasty]].<ref name=\"PurushottamShamsher1990\">{{cite book |last=JBR |first=PurushottamShamsher |date=1990 |title=Shree Teen Haruko Tathya Britanta |trans-title= |url= |language=Nepali |location=Bhotahity, Kathmandu |publisher=Vidarthi Pustak Bhandar |isbn=978-99933-39-91-5 |accessdate=}}</ref> The close relatives and supporters of Thapa faction replaced the old courtiers and administrators.{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=28}} The Kunwar family came to power being relatives of powerful Mukhtiyar Bhimsen Thapa. Similarly, Kunwars were related to [[Pande dynasty]] by their maternal grandmother Rana Kumari Pande who was daughter of ''[[Mulkaji]]'' [[Ranajit Pande]].<ref name=\"PurushottamShamsher1990\" />\n\n=== Rise of Jang Bahadur ===\n[[File:Jang Bahadur Ranaji.jpg|thumb|[[Jang Bahadur Rana|Jang Bahadur Kunwar Ranaji]], founder of Rana dynasty]]\nBal Narsingh's son ''Kaji'' [[Jang Bahadur Rana|Jang Bahadur Kunwar]] became a significant person in the central politics of Nepal during the prime ministership of his uncle [[Mathabar Singh Thapa]].{{sfn|Adhikari|1984|p=27}} On 17 May 1845 around 11&nbsp;pm, Mathabar Singh was summoned to the royal palace and was assassinated in a cold blood by Jang Bahadur on the royal orders.{{sfn|Adhikari|1984|p=27}} He was considered to have been merciless, ruthless and fatal due to his association with Mathabar Singh.{{sfn|Adhikari|1984|p=27}} Jang Bahadur was made a [[Kaji (Nepal)|Kaji]] (equivalent to minister) after following the order of assassination of Mathabar.{{sfn|Joshi|Rose|1966|p=30}} On the night of 14 September 1846, Queen [[Rajya Lakshmi Devi]] summoned the courtiers on the mysterious murderer of her aide ''General Kaji'' [[Gagan Singh Bhandari]], to which courtiers hurried to the Kot quickly.{{sfn|Acharya|2013|pp=137}} Many of the courtiers were unarmed except for a sword, as they had responded immediately to the royal summons. The armies allocated by [[Jung Bahadur Rana]] also had taken most of the arms of courtiers who had managed to bring them. Queen Rajya Lakshmi Devi and King [[Rajendra Bikram Shah]] were also present in the Kot.{{sfn|Acharya|2013|pp=137\u2013145}} Queen Rajya Lakshmi demanded the execution of Kaji Bir Keshar (Kishor) Pande on alleged suspicion to which General [[Abhiman Singh Rana Magar]] looked towards King for confirmation. Jang misinformed Queen that Abhiman Singh's troops were arriving for overpowering the Queen's faction and demanded an immediate arrest.{{sfn|Joshi|Rose|1966|p=30}} Abhiman tried to force his way out and was killed by Jang's soldier. In the chaos followed, Jang and his brothers began bloodshed and many rival nobles and courtiers were eliminated by them.{{sfn|Joshi|Rose|1966|pp=30-31}} The letter to British Resident [[Henry Montgomery Lawrence]] stated that there were 32 Bharadars (courtiers) killed in the massacre.{{sfn|Stiller|1981|pp=304-306}}\n\n===Bhandarkhal massacre episode===\nWhen Jang Bahadur refused the Junior Queen's request to place Prince Ranendra in the place of Crown Prince [[Surendra of Nepal]], the Queen secretly contacted the victims of Kot and conspired to assassinate Jung Bahadur in the royal Bhandarkhal garden. After receiving a command from the Queen to come to Bhandarkhal, Jang Bahadur took his fully armed troops and headed towards the garden. The troops killed the chief conspirator, Birdhwaj Basnyat on the way, and marched towards Bhandarkhal where seeing Jang Bahadur approach fully armed with his troops, the other conspirators started to flee. 23 people were killed in the massacre while 15 escaped.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Life of Maharaja Sir Jung Bahadur Rana|last=Jung|first=Padma|publisher=|year=1909|isbn=|location=Allahabad|pages=88}}</ref> In the 23rd of September 1846, all officers of military and bureaucracy were called upon to their respective offices within 10 days. Then, Jung Bahadur appointed his brothers and nephews to the highest ranks of the government.<ref name=\"Britanta\">{{Cite book|title=Ranashasanko Britanta|last=Rana|first=Pramod Shumsher|publisher=Pairavi Book House|year=2009|isbn=9789994630721|location=Kathmandu|pages=31,32,44}}</ref> He consolidated the position of premiership after conducting [[Kot massacre]] (Kot Parva) and Bhandarkhal Parva<ref>{{cite book |last=Rana |first=Purushottam S.J.B. |title=Jung Bahadur Rana: the story of his rise and glory |location= |year=1998 |edition= |pages=150 |publisher=Book Faith India |url= |isbn=978-81-7303-087-1}}</ref> on the basic templates provided by his maternal [[grand-uncle]] ''Mukhtiyar'' [[Bhimsen Thapa]].{{sfn|Acharya|2012|p=11-12}}\n\n==Rana Regime; Rule of Jang==\nAfter the massacres of Kot and Bhandarkhal, the [[Thapa dynasty|Thapas]], [[Pande dynasty|Pandes]], [[Basnyat family|Basnyats]] and other citizens had settled in [[Banaras]]. Similarly, some citizens had gone to settle in [[Nautanwa]] and [[Bettiah]]. ''Chautariya'' Guru Prasad Shah too had gone to live with the King of Bettiah. After knowing about the presence of the King and the Queen in Benaras, Guru Prasad went there and started to congregate an army and a plan to execute Jung Bahadur started to be formed.<ref name=\"Britanta\"/>\n===Battle of Alau===\nIn May 12, 1847, Jung Bahadur gave a speech in [[Tundikhel]]. There he accused the King of the attempted assassination of the Prince and the Prime Minister. The Council then decided to dethrone King Rajendra deeming him mentally ill, and on the same day [[Surendra of Nepal|Surendra]] was crowned as the new king of Nepal. Hearing the news of the coronation of Surendra, Rajendra decided to take the responsibility of removing Jung Bahadur upon himself and declaring himself as the leader of the army, he left Benaras. Rajendra then appointed Guru Prasad Shah as the Chief of the Army for the operation of removal of Jung Bahadur Rana from Nepal and started to accumulate weapons and training the troops. Antagonism from the [[Company rule in India|British-India Company]] forced Rajendra and his troops to enter Nepal. On the 23rd of July, the troops reached a village called [[Alau, Nepal|Alau]] in Bara and set a camp there. One spy group of the Government of Nepal was keeping close eyes on the event of the rebel groups at [[Bettiah]]. They sent the news to Jung Bahadur, immediately after which he sent a troop in the leadership of Sanak Singh Tandon to Alau. They were told to suppress the rebellions, arrest Rajendra and bring him to Kathmandu. On the 27th of July, the ''Gorakhnath Paltan'' (Gorakhnath Battalion) reached and rested in a village called [[Simraungadh]], not too far from Alau. The battle of Alau was a decisive one between the forces of King Rajendra and Jang Bahadur. The King lost significantly in the battle. If the massacre of Kot had established Jung Bahadur as a dictator, the battle of Alau had helped him strengthen his dictatorship. Rajendra was imprisoned in an old palace in Bhaktapur.<ref name=\"Britanta\"/>\n=== Rise to royalty ===\nOn 15 May 1848, a Lal Mohar (Red sealed document) was issued claiming descent from [[Sisodia|Ranas of Mewar]] and authorizing the Kunwar family of Jang Bahadur to style themselves as '''Kunwar Ranaji'''.{{sfn|Whelpton|1991|p=253}} On 6 August 1856, Jang Bahadur Kunwar (now Ranaji) was conferred the title of [[Maharaja]] ('''Great King''') of Kaski and Lamjung, two former hill principalities, by King of Nepal, [[Surendra Bikram Shah]].{{sfn|Whelpton|1991|p=192}}\n\n==Rana Regime; Rule of the Shamshers==\n[[File:Bir_Shamsher JBR.jpg|thumb|[[Bir Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]], the first Shamsher Rana ruler]]\nIn 1885, the Shumsher family, the nephews of [[Jang Bahadur]], murdered many of the sons of [[Jung Bahadur]] and took over Nepal in a military [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] thus bringing in the rule of the Shamsher Rana family also known as the Satra Bhai (17 brothers) Rana family. They murdered [[Renaudip Singh Bahadur|Sri Teen Maharaja Ranodip Singh]] and occupied the hereditary throne of Prime Minister. After this they added [[Jang Bahadur]] to their name, although they were descended from Jang's younger brother Dhir Shamsher<ref name=\"PurushottamShamsher1990\" />\n\n== Kunwar family tree ==\n{{tree chart/start |summary= Ram Krishna Kunwar was born to Ahiram Kunwar.{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=193}}{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=286}} He had only a son named [[Ranjit Kunwar]] and three grandsons; [[Bal Narsingh Kunwar]], Balram Kunwar and Rewant Kunwar.{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=193}} Bal Narsingh had nine sons in the birth order; Bhakta Bir Kunwar, [[Jang Bahadur Kunwar]], [[Bam Bahadur Kunwar]], Badri Narsingh Kunwar, Jaya Bahadur Kunwar, Krishna Bahadur Kunwar, [[Ranodip Singh Kunwar|Ranauddip Singh Kunwar]], Jagat Shamsher Kunwar and Dhir Shamsher Kunwar.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royalark.net/Nepal/lamb2.htm |title=Lamb2 |accessdate=2 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180203210425/http://www.royalark.net/Nepal/lamb2.htm |archive-date=3 February 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n{{tree chart| | | | | | | | | | | | | RKK | | RKK='''[[Ram Krishna Kunwar]]'''}}\n{{tree chart| | | | | | | | | | | | | |!| |}}\n{{tree chart| | | | | | | | | | | | |RJK| | RJK=[[Ranajit Kunwar]]|}}\n{{tree chart| |,|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|v|-|^|-|-|-|-|-|.|}}\n{{tree chart| BNK| | | | | | | | BRK | | | | | | RwK|BNK='''[[Bal Narsingh Kunwar]]'''|BRK=Balaram Kunwar|RwK=Rewant Kunwar}}\n{{tree chart| |)|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|.|}}\n{{tree chart| BBK| | JBK| | BBaK| | BNK | | JBaK | | KBK | |RSK | | JSK | | DSK | BBK= Bhakta Bir Kunwar|JBK='''[[Jang Bahadur Kunwar]]'''|BBaK= [[Bam Bahadur Kunwar]] | BNK= Badri Narsingh Kunwar |JBaK=Jaya Bahadur Kunwar|KBK= Krishna Bahadur Kunwar |RSK='''[[Ranodip Singh Kunwar|Ranauddip Singh Kunwar]]'''|JSK=Jagat Shamsher Kunwar|DSK=[[Dhir Shamsher Rana|Dhir Shamsher Kunwar]]}}\n{{tree chart/end}}\n\n== Rana Prime Ministers ==\nNine Rana rulers took the hereditary office(s) of Prime Minister, Supreme Commander-in-Chief and Grand Master of the Royal Orders. All were crowned as the Maharaja of [[Lamjung District|Lamjung]] and [[Kaski District|Kaski]].\n\n{{Tree list}}\n* [[Ranajit Kunwar]] Rana (1723\u20131815)\n** {{Tree list/final branch}} [[Bal Narsingh Kunwar]] Rana (1783\u20131841)\n*** [[File:Simple silver crown.svg|15px]] '''I. Shr\u012b T\u012bn [[Jung Bahadur Rana]]''' [[Order of the Bath|GCB]], [[Order of the Star of India|GCSI]] (18 June 1816 \u2013 25 February 1877). Prime Minister and C-in-C 15 September 1846 to 1 August 1856 and from 28 June 1857 until his death. Granted the hereditary title of ''Rana'' on 5 May 1848, as a suffix to the male members of his family. Granted the hereditary title of ''Maharaja of Lamjung and Kaski'' (to be enjoyed \u2018offspring to offspring\u2019, and the hereditary offices of Prime Minister and C-in-C (to be enjoyed in succession by his surviving brothers, his sons, then his nephews), 6 August 1856. Received a [[salute]] of 19 guns from the [[United Kingdom|British]].\n*** [[Bam Bahadur Kunwar]] Rana (1818 \u2013 25 May 1857; Prime Minister: 1 August 1856 \u2013 25 May 1857)\n*** [[File:Simple silver crown.svg|15px]] '''II. Shr\u012b T\u012bn [[Ranodip Singh Kunwar]] (aka Ranodip Singh Rana)''' [[Order of the Star of India|KCSI]] (3 April 1825 \u2013 assassinated 22 November 1885). Ruled 25 February 1877 to 22 November 1885.\n*** {{Tree list/final branch}} General Sri [[Dhir Shumsher Kunwar Rana]] (1828\u20131884)\n**** [[File:Simple silver crown.svg|15px]] '''III. Shr\u012b T\u012bn [[Bir Shumsher Jung Bahadur Rana]]''' [[Order of the Star of India|GCSI]] (10 December 1852 \u2013 5 March 1901). Ruled 22 November 1885 to 5 March 1901.\n**** [[File:Simple silver crown.svg|15px]] '''IV. Shr\u012b T\u012bn [[Dev Shumsher Jung Bahadur Rana]]''' (17 July 1862 \u2013 20 February 1914). Ruled 5 March to 27 June 1901, when as a result of his progressive nature, he was deposed by his relatives and [[exile]]d to India.\n**** [[File:Simple silver crown.svg|15px]] '''V. Shr\u012b T\u012bn [[Chandra Shumsher Jung Bahadur Rana]]''' [[Order of the Bath|GCB]], [[Order of the Star of India|GCSI]], [[Order of St Michael and St George|GCMG]], [[Royal Victorian Order|GCVO]] (8 July 1863 \u2013 26 November 1929). Ruled 27 June 1901 to 26 November 1929.\n***** {{Tree list/final branch}} [[File:Simple silver crown.svg|15px]] '''IX. Shr\u012b T\u012bn [[Mohan Shumsher JBR|Mohan Shumsher Jung Bahadur Rana]]''' [[Order of the Bath|GCB]], [[Order of the Star of India|GCIE]], [[Order of the British Empire|GBE]] (23 December 1885 \u2013 6 January 1967). Ruled 30 April 1948 to 18 February 1951, at which date he was divested of his titles and later went to [[India]].\n**** [[File:Simple silver crown.svg|15px]] '''VI. Shr\u012b T\u012bn [[Bhim Shumsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]''' [[Order of the Star of India|GCSI]], [[Order of St Michael and St George|GCMG]], [[Royal Victorian Order|KCVO]] (16 April 1865 \u2013 1 September 1932). Ruled 26 November 1929 to 1 September 1932.\n***** {{Tree list/final branch}} [[File:Simple silver crown.svg|15px]] '''VIII. Shr\u012b T\u012bn [[Padma Shumsher Jung Bahadur Rana]]''' [[Order of the Star of India|GCSI]], [[Order of the Indian Empire|GCIE]], [[Order of the British Empire|GBE]], (5 December 1882 \u2013 11 April 1961). Ruled 29 November 1945 to 30 April 1948, whereupon he [[abdicated]] in favor of his cousin.\n**** {{Tree list/final branch}} [[File:Simple silver crown.svg|15px]] '''VII. Shr\u012b T\u012bn [[Juddha Shumsher Jung Bahadur Rana]]''' [[Order of the Bath|GCB]], [[Order of the Star of India|GCSI]], [[Order of the Indian Empire|GCIE]] (19 April 1875 \u2013 20 November 1952). Ruled 1 September 1932 to 29 November 1945, whereupon he [[Abdication|abdicated]] in favor of his nephew.\n{{Tree list/end}}\n\n=== Succession ===\nSuccession to the role of the Prime Ministers and the title of ''Maharaja of Lamjung and Kaski'' was by [[agnatic seniority]], by which the oldest male heir among the sons of equal (a-class) marriages in a generation would succeed. The order of succession was determined by seniority, with each eligible male heir holding a military command, as follows:\n\n# Prime Minister and Commander-in-Chief (Mukhtiyar the Heir Apparent, with the rank of Field Marshal).\n# Western Commanding-General.\n# Eastern Commanding-General.\n# Southern Commanding-General.\n# Northern Commanding-General.\n\n==Notable Rana members==\n*[[Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Bam Bahadur Kunwar]]\n*[[Ranodip Singh Kunwar]]\n*[[Bir Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Dev Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Chandra Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Bhim Shumsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Juddha Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Rudra Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Padma Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Mohan Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Baber Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Kaiser Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Kiran Shamsher Rana]]\n*[[Nir Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Toran Shumsher J.B.R.]]\n*[[Nara Shumsher J.B.R.]]\n*[[Ratna Shumsher J.B.R.]]\n*[[Pradip Shumsher J.B.R.]]\n*[[Satchit Rana|Satchit Shamsher Jung Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Pashupati Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Madhukar Shamsher Rana]]\n*[[Om Bikram Rana]]\n*[[Gaurav Shumsher JB Rana]]\n*[[Udaya Shumsher Rana]], great-grandson of Baber\n\n===Other notable connected members===\n*[[Ranajit Pande]], maternal grandfather of Ganesh Kumari, mother of [[Jung Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Nain Singh Thapa]] was father-in-law of [[Bal Narsingh Kunwar]].\n*[[George Jivaji Rao Scindia]], father-in-law of [[Pashupati Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]].\n*[[Surya Bahadur Thapa]], brother-in-law of Himalaya Shamsher JBR\n*[[Prithvi Bahadur Pande]], son-in-law of Himalaya Shamsher JBR\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Rana couple.jpg|Major-General Vishnu Shamsher Rana and wife\nFile:Rana family 1915.jpg|Commanding General Babar Shumsher Rana and family\nFile:Dhir Shamsher Rana and sons bw.jpg|Dhir Shamsher Rana and sons make up Shamsher Rana dynasty\nFile:Chandra Shamsher and sons.jpg|Chandra Shamsher and sons\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Daudaha system]]\n* [[Pajani System]]\n* [[Rolls of Succession in Rana (Nepal)]]\n* [[History of Nepal]]\n* [[Rana palaces of Nepal]]\n* [[Thapa dynasty]]\n\n== References ==\n=== Footnotes ===\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{Cite book |title=The Bloodstained Throne: Struggles for Power in Nepal (1775\u20131914) |last=Acharya |first=Baburam |publisher=Penguin Books Ltd |year=2013 |isbn=978-0-14-341637-1 |location=New Delhi |url=https://books.google.com/?id=UWQtAAAAQBAJ&dq=bloodstained+acharya}}\n* {{citation |last=Acharya |first=Baburam |editor-last=Acharya |editor-first=Shri Krishna |title=Janaral Bhimsen Thapa : Yinko Utthan Tatha Pattan |location=Kathmandu |year=2012 |pages=228 |language=Nepali |publisher=Education Book House |isbn=9789937241748}}\n* {{citation |last=Adhikari |first=Krishna Kant |title=Nepal Under Jang Bahadur, 1846\u20131877 |volume=1 |publisher=Buku |year=1984 |location=Nepal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7PP1yElRzIUC|isbn=9788180698132}}\n* {{cite book |last=Hamal |first=Lakshman B. |year=1995 |title=Military history of Nepal |publisher=Sharda Pustak Mandir |page=125 |oclc=32779233}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Democratic Innovations in Nepal: Case Study of Political Acculturation |last=Joshi |first=Bhuwan Lal |last2=Rose |first2=Leo E. |publisher=University of California Press |year=1966 |isbn=978-0-520-00622-5 |location=Berkeley |url=https://books.google.com/?id=MX22o4PJ3Q0C&printsec=frontcover&dq=joshi+rose#v=onepage&q=joshi%20rose&f=false}}\n* {{citation |last=Nepal |first=Gyanmani |title=Nepal ko Mahabharat |publisher=Sajha |language=Nepali |year=2007 |edition=3rd |pages=314 |location=Kathmandu |isbn=9789993325857}}\n* {{citation |last=Pradhan |first=Kumar L. |title=Thapa Politics in Nepal: With Special Reference to Bhim Sen Thapa, 1806\u20131839 |publisher=Concept Publishing Company |year=2012 |isbn=9788180698132 |location=New Delhi |pages=278 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7PP1yElRzIUC}}\n*{{citation | last = Regmi | first = Mahesh Chandra | title = Preliminary Notes on the Nature of Rana Law and Government | journal = Regmi Research Series | volume = 7 | issue = 5 | pages = 88\u201397 | date = May 1, 1975 | origyear = | url = http://himalaya.socanth.cam.ac.uk/collections/journals/regmi/pdf/Regmi_07.pdf |accessdate=}}\n* {{citation |last=Stiller |first=Ludwig F. |title=Letters from Kathmandu: The Kot Massacre |year=1981 |publisher=Research Centre for Nepal and Asian Studies, Tribhuvan University, Kirtipur |url=https://books.google.com/?id=NFBfAQAACAAJ&dq=stiller+the+kot+massacre}}\n* {{citation |last=Vaidya |first=Tulsi Ram |title=Prithvinaryan Shah, the founder of Nepal |year=1993 |publisher=Anmol Publications |isbn=9788170417019 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Prithvinarayan_Shah_the_founder_of_moder.html?id=jSVwAAAAMAAJ}}\n* {{cite book |last=Whelpton |first=John |year=1991 |title=Kings, soldiers, and priests: Nepalese politics and the rise of Jang Bahadur Rana, 1830\u20131857 |publisher=Manohar Publications |page=254 |isbn=9788185425641}}\n* {{citation |last=Wright |first=Daniel |title=History of Nepal |year=1877 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/History_of_Nep%C4%81l.html?id=mHE5hkHc7kcC}}\n\n== External links ==\n* Friend in need:1857, Friendship forgotten:1887 William Digby-Friend in need:1857, Friendship forgotten:1887\n* [http://www.4dw.net/royalark/Nepal/lambjang.htm Lambjang and Kaski \u2013 Brief History] at Royalark.\n* [http://www.thecosmosphere.com/history-flashback-rana-dynasty/ Old pictures of Nepal from Rana Dynasty]\n\n{{Nepal topics}}\n\n[[Category:Nepalese monarchy]]\n[[Category:Rana regime]]\n[[Category:Rajput rulers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{short description|Nepali Kshetri dynasty of rulers}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2011}}\n{{Royal house|\n| surname        = Rana dynasty\n| native_name    = \u0930\u093e\u0923\u093e \u0935\u0902\u0936\n| native_name_lang = ne\n| other_name     = Ranas of Nepal\n| type           = [[Royal House]]\n| estates        = [[Rana palaces of Nepal]]\n| coat of arms   = Coat of Arms of Rana dynasty.jpg\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Kingdom of Nepal]]\n* Kingdom of [[Kaski District|Kaski]] & [[Lamjung district|Lamjung]] (under [[Nepal]])}}\n| titles         = {{Plainlist|\n* Titular King of [[Kaski District|Kaski]] & [[Lamjung district|Lamjung]]\n* [[Sri|Shree Tin]] [[Maharaja]]\n* [[Rana (title)|Ranajyu/Ranaji]] [[Saheb]]}}\n| founder        = [[Jung Bahadur Rana]]\n|parent house =  [[Kunwar family of Gorkha]]\n| final ruler    = [[Mohan Shumsher]]\n| current head   = presently as [[pretender]]\n|motto           = ''[[Janani Janmabhumishcha Swargadapi Gariyasi]]''<ref>https://www.hubert-herald.nl/Nepal.htm#_ednref6</ref>\n|motto_lang      = sa\n|motto_trans     = Mother and Motherland are superior to heaven.\n| founding year  = 1846 A.D.\n| deposition     = 1951 A.D.\n| religion       = Hinduism\n|cadet_branches = \n| notes = The family were [[Kunwar family|Kunwars]] which was historically a [[Chhetri]] clan.{{sfn|Regmi|1975|p=90}}\n}}\n{{History of Nepal}}\n{{Ranas of Nepal}}\n'''Rana dynasty''' ({{lang-ne|\u0930\u093e\u0923\u093e \u0935\u0902\u0936}}; [[IAST]]: ''R\u0101\u1e47\u0101 va\u1e43\u015ba'') is a [[Kshatriya]] ([[Rajput]]-[[Chhetri]]){{refn|group=note|Founder of this dynasty, [[Jang Bahadur Rana]], was a noble of [[Khas people|Khas community]].<ref>{{Cite book |author=Dor Bahadur Bista |author-link=Dor Bahadur Bista |title=Fatalism and Development: Nepal's Struggle for Modernization |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JzFROpFVYRAC&pg=PA48 |year=1991 |publisher=Orient Blackswan |isbn=978-81-250-0188-1 |ref=harv}}</ref> He belonged to [[Kunwar family]] which was historically a [[Chhetri]] clan.{{sfn|Regmi|1975|p=90}} They also had marital relations with other Chhetri families as [[Thapa dynasty]] of Mukhtiyar [[Bhimsen Thapa]] and [[Pande dynasty]] of [[Ranajit Pande]].<ref name=\"PurushottamShamsher1990\" />}} dynasty from the [[Indian subcontinent]]<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book |title=Greater Game |author=Van PraaghD |date=2003 |publisher=MQUP |isbn=978-0-7735-7130-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KVDIvLQDGckC&pg=PA319 |page=319 |accessdate=11 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911115456/https://books.google.com/books?id=KVDIvLQDGckC&pg=PA319 |archive-date=11 September 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> that ruled the [[Kingdom of Nepal]] from 1846 A.D until 1951 A.D, reducing the [[Shah dynasty|Shah monarch]] to a figurehead and making [[List of Prime Ministers of Nepal|Prime Minister]] and other government positions held by the Ranas hereditary.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dietrich |first=Angela |title=Buddhist Monks and Rana Rulers: A History of Persecution |url=http://ccbs.ntu.edu.tw/FULLTEXT/JR-BH/bh117536.htm |accessdate=17 September 2013 |newspaper=Buddhist Himalaya: A Journal of Nagarjuna Institute of Exact Methods |year=1996 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001124156/http://ccbs.ntu.edu.tw/FULLTEXT/JR-BH/bh117536.htm |archive-date=1 October 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lal |first=C. K. |title=The Rana resonance |url=http://nepalitimes.com/news.php?id=8741 |accessdate=17 September 2013 |newspaper=[[Nepali Times]] |date=16 February 2001 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928013152/http://nepalitimes.com/news.php?id=8741 |archive-date=28 September 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> Rana dynasty is historically known for the ''[[Totalitarianism|iron-fisted rule]]''.<ref>http://archive.nepalitimes.com/article/Nepali-Times-Buzz/the-rana-reign-a-recap-of-history,3751</ref> This changed after the [[Revolution of 1951]] with the promulgation of a new constitution, when power shifted back to the monarchy of [[King Tribhuvan]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Kraemer |first=Karl-Heinz |title=Democratization and political parties in Nepal |url=http://nepalresearch.org/publications/harvard_9903.htm |publisher=Harvard University |accessdate=25 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524165715/http://nepalresearch.org/publications/harvard_9903.htm |archive-date=24 May 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Rana dynasty descended from the [[Kunwar family]], a nobility of the [[Gorkha Kingdom]].{{sfn|Joshi|Rose|1966|p=30}} Due to the marital lineages with the politically reigning [[Thapa dynasty]] (of ''[[Mukhtiyar]]'' [[Bhimsen Thapa]]) from early 19th century, Ranas gained entry to central [[Durbar (court)|Darbar]] politics.{{sfn|Acharya|2012|p=11-12}}<ref name=\"PurushottamShamsher1990\" /> Ranas were also linked to the minor faction of another politically acclaimed [[Pande dynasty]] of Gorkha through Thapa dynasty.<ref name=\"PurushottamShamsher1990\" />\n\n== Genealogy ==\nChronicler Daniel Wright has published the genealogy of [[Jang Bahadur Kunwar Rana]]. The genealogy begins with Tatt\u0101 R\u0101\u1e47\u0101 as [[Raja]] (King) of [[Chittaurgarh]].{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=285}} His nephew Fakht Si\u1e43ha R\u0101\u1e47\u0101 had a son named R\u0101ma Si\u1e43ha R\u0101\u1e47\u0101, who came to hills after the siege of Chittaur.{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=285}} He was employed by a hill Raja for ten or twelve months who wanted to retain R\u0101ma Si\u1e43ha in his country. The hill Raja asked for the daughter of [[Raja]] of B\u012bn\u0101t\u012b, a Bag\u0101le [[Kshetri|K\u1e63etr\u012b]] and married her to R\u0101ma Si\u1e43ha.{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=285}} They had six sons over 10-12 years, one of whom was recognized by the title of ''[[Kunwar|Kum\u0310vara]] [[Khadka|Kha\u1e0dk\u0101]]'' for bravery displayed in the battle against Raja of Sat\u0101n Ko\u1e6d.{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=285}} The title was used by his descendants. R\u0101ma Si\u1e43ha was suddenly met by his younger brother who requested him to return Chittaur for once and R\u0101ma Si\u1e43ha died reaching there.{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=286}} The hill Raja made R\u0101ma Si\u1e43ha's son R\u0101ut Kunwar a nobleman (Sard\u0101r) and commandant of the army.{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=286}} Ahir\u0101ma Kunwar, a son of R\u0101ut Kunwar, was invited by King of Kaski and was made nobleman with a birta or jagir of Dhuage Saghu village.{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=286}} King of Kaski asked the hand of Ahir\u0101ma's daughter, who was a great beauty through only Kalas Puja to which Ahir\u0101ma replied to give his daughter only through lawful marriage.{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=286}} King brought his troops and tried to take on the village by force.{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=286}} Ahir\u0101ma was supported by the villagers belonging to Par\u0101jul\u012b Th\u0101p\u0101 caste and a war was initiated.{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=286}} On the same day, Ahir\u0101ma took his immediate family including two sons namely; [[Ram Krishna Kunwar]] and Jaya Krishna Kunwar, to King of Gorkha, [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]] where lands of Kunwar-Khola was given to them as ''birta''.{{sfn|Wright|1877|pp=286-87}}\n\n[[John Whelpton]] opines that Kunwar origin legend which states that first of their ancestors to enter hill married a daughter of Bagale Kshetri might have directed their family links to [[Bagale Thapa]], the clan of Mukhtiyar [[Bhimsen Thapa]].{{sfn|Whelpton|1991|p=36}}\n\nRana dynasts; Prabhakar, Gautam and [[Pashupati Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]] claim the descent of Ranas of Nepal from ''Kunwar'' Kumbhakaran Singh, younger brother of [[Guhila_dynasty|Guhila]] King of [[Mewar]], Rawal [[Ratnasimha]]. During the [[Siege of Chittorgarh (1303)|first siege of Chittorgarh]] in 1303 A.D., Kumbhakaran Singh's descendants left [[Mewar]] to north towards Himalayan foothills according to the book \" Rana's Of Nepal\" where the preface is written by [[Arvind Singh Mewar]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://books.google.com/?id=GE1uAAAAMAAJ&q=ranas+of+nepal&dq=ranas+of+nepal |title=THE RANAS OF NEPAL |last1=Rana |first1=Prabhakar S. J. B. |last2=Rana |first2=Pashupati Shumshere Jung Bahadur |last3=Rana |first3=Gautam S. J. B. |year=2003}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.np/books?redir_esc=y&id=GE1uAAAAMAAJ&dq=ranas+of+nepal&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Arvind+Singh+mewar|title=Ranas Of Nepal|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n== Historical background ==\n{{See|Kunwar family}}\n[[File:Ram Krishna Kunwar.jpg|thumb|left|''[[Sardar]]'' [[Ram Krishna Kunwar]], prominent male ancestor of Ranas of Nepal]]\nThe founder of this dynasty was [[Jang Bahadur Rana]], who belonged to [[Kunwar family]] which was then considered a minor noble family of [[Kshatriya]] status.{{sfn|Joshi|Rose|1966|p=30}} Jang Bahadur was a son of Gorkhali governor [[Bal Narsingh Kunwar]] and nephew of [[Mathabarsingh Thapa]]{{sfn|Acharya|2012|p=11-12}}, the reigning [[Prime Minister of Nepal]] (1843\u20131845) from the [[Thapa dynasty]].{{sfn|Acharya|2012|p=177-178}} Bal Narsingh Kunwar was the son of Kaji [[Ranajit Kunwar]] and grandson of ''[[Sardar]]'' [[Ram Krishna Kunwar]]{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=193}}, who was prominent military general of King [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]].{{sfn|Adhikari|1984|p=27}}{{sfn|Hamal|1995|pp=180-181}} Ram Krishna Kunwar was born to Ahiram Kunwar.{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=193}} There were ample of rewards and recognitions received by ''Sardar'' Ram Krishna Kunwar from the Gorkhali monarch Prithvi Narayan.{{sfn|Hamal|1995|p=181}} His grandson Bal Narsingh was initially a follower of the renounced King [[Rana Bahadur Shah]] and Kaji [[Bhimsen Thapa]], and followed the King in his exile to [[Banaras]] on 1 May 1800.{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=13}} On the night of 25 April 1806, King Rana Bahadur was killed by step-brother Sher Bahadur in desperation after which Bal Narsingh immediately killed the King's assassin.{{sfn|Acharya|2012|p=67}}{{sfn|Nepal|2007|pp=62\u201363}}{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|pp=27-28}} He was a close ally of the influential minister Bhimsen Thapa{{sfn|Acharya|2012|p=67}}, who initiated a great massacre at Bhandarkhal garden following the chaos from the King's murder.{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=28}}{{sfn|Acharya|2012|pp=68\u201371}}{{sfn|Nepal|2007|pp=63\u201364}} Following closeness to Mukhtiyar Bhimsen, he became the son-in-law of Bhimsen's brother ''Kaji '' [[Nain Singh Thapa]] of [[Thapa dynasty]].<ref name=\"PurushottamShamsher1990\">{{cite book |last=JBR |first=PurushottamShamsher |date=1990 |title=Shree Teen Haruko Tathya Britanta |trans-title= |url= |language=Nepali |location=Bhotahity, Kathmandu |publisher=Vidarthi Pustak Bhandar |isbn=978-99933-39-91-5 |accessdate=}}</ref> The close relatives and supporters of Thapa faction replaced the old courtiers and administrators.{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=28}} The Kunwar family came to power being relatives of powerful Mukhtiyar Bhimsen Thapa. Similarly, Kunwars were related to [[Pande dynasty]] by their maternal grandmother Rana Kumari Pande who was daughter of ''[[Mulkaji]]'' [[Ranajit Pande]].<ref name=\"PurushottamShamsher1990\" />\n\n=== Rise of Jang Bahadur ===\n[[File:Jang Bahadur Ranaji.jpg|thumb|[[Jang Bahadur Rana|Jang Bahadur Kunwar Ranaji]], founder of Rana dynasty]]\nBal Narsingh's son ''Kaji'' [[Jang Bahadur Rana|Jang Bahadur Kunwar]] became a significant person in the central politics of Nepal during the prime ministership of his uncle [[Mathabar Singh Thapa]].{{sfn|Adhikari|1984|p=27}} On 17 May 1845 around 11&nbsp;pm, Mathabar Singh was summoned to the royal palace and was assassinated in a cold blood by Jang Bahadur on the royal orders.{{sfn|Adhikari|1984|p=27}} He was considered to have been merciless, ruthless and fatal due to his association with Mathabar Singh.{{sfn|Adhikari|1984|p=27}} Jang Bahadur was made a [[Kaji (Nepal)|Kaji]] (equivalent to minister) after following the order of assassination of Mathabar.{{sfn|Joshi|Rose|1966|p=30}} On the night of 14 September 1846, Queen [[Rajya Lakshmi Devi]] summoned the courtiers on the mysterious murderer of her aide ''General Kaji'' [[Gagan Singh Bhandari]], to which courtiers hurried to the Kot quickly.{{sfn|Acharya|2013|pp=137}} Many of the courtiers were unarmed except for a sword, as they had responded immediately to the royal summons. The armies allocated by [[Jung Bahadur Rana]] also had taken most of the arms of courtiers who had managed to bring them. Queen Rajya Lakshmi Devi and King [[Rajendra Bikram Shah]] were also present in the Kot.{{sfn|Acharya|2013|pp=137\u2013145}} Queen Rajya Lakshmi demanded the execution of Kaji Bir Keshar (Kishor) Pande on alleged suspicion to which General [[Abhiman Singh Rana Magar]] looked towards King for confirmation. Jang misinformed Queen that Abhiman Singh's troops were arriving for overpowering the Queen's faction and demanded an immediate arrest.{{sfn|Joshi|Rose|1966|p=30}} Abhiman tried to force his way out and was killed by Jang's soldier. In the chaos followed, Jang and his brothers began bloodshed and many rival nobles and courtiers were eliminated by them.{{sfn|Joshi|Rose|1966|pp=30-31}} The letter to British Resident [[Henry Montgomery Lawrence]] stated that there were 32 Bharadars (courtiers) killed in the massacre.{{sfn|Stiller|1981|pp=304-306}}\n\n===Bhandarkhal massacre episode===\nWhen Jang Bahadur refused the Junior Queen's request to place Prince Ranendra in the place of Crown Prince [[Surendra of Nepal]], the Queen secretly contacted the victims of Kot and conspired to assassinate Jung Bahadur in the royal Bhandarkhal garden. After receiving a command from the Queen to come to Bhandarkhal, Jang Bahadur took his fully armed troops and headed towards the garden. The troops killed the chief conspirator, Birdhwaj Basnyat on the way, and marched towards Bhandarkhal where seeing Jang Bahadur approach fully armed with his troops, the other conspirators started to flee. 23 people were killed in the massacre while 15 escaped.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Life of Maharaja Sir Jung Bahadur Rana|last=Jung|first=Padma|publisher=|year=1909|isbn=|location=Allahabad|pages=88}}</ref> In the 23rd of September 1846, all officers of military and bureaucracy were called upon to their respective offices within 10 days. Then, Jung Bahadur appointed his brothers and nephews to the highest ranks of the government.<ref name=\"Britanta\">{{Cite book|title=Ranashasanko Britanta|last=Rana|first=Pramod Shumsher|publisher=Pairavi Book House|year=2009|isbn=9789994630721|location=Kathmandu|pages=31,32,44}}</ref> He consolidated the position of premiership after conducting [[Kot massacre]] (Kot Parva) and Bhandarkhal Parva<ref>{{cite book |last=Rana |first=Purushottam S.J.B. |title=Jung Bahadur Rana: the story of his rise and glory |location= |year=1998 |edition= |pages=150 |publisher=Book Faith India |url= |isbn=978-81-7303-087-1}}</ref> on the basic templates provided by his maternal [[grand-uncle]] ''Mukhtiyar'' [[Bhimsen Thapa]].{{sfn|Acharya|2012|p=11-12}}\n\n==Rana Regime; Rule of Jang==\nAfter the massacres of Kot and Bhandarkhal, the [[Thapa dynasty|Thapas]], [[Pande dynasty|Pandes]], [[Basnyat family|Basnyats]] and other citizens had settled in [[Banaras]]. Similarly, some citizens had gone to settle in [[Nautanwa]] and [[Bettiah]]. ''Chautariya'' Guru Prasad Shah too had gone to live with the King of Bettiah. After knowing about the presence of the King and the Queen in Benaras, Guru Prasad went there and started to congregate an army and a plan to execute Jung Bahadur started to be formed.<ref name=\"Britanta\"/>\n===Battle of Alau===\nIn May 12, 1847, Jung Bahadur gave a speech in [[Tundikhel]]. There he accused the King of the attempted assassination of the Prince and the Prime Minister. The Council then decided to dethrone King Rajendra deeming him mentally ill, and on the same day [[Surendra of Nepal|Surendra]] was crowned as the new king of Nepal. Hearing the news of the coronation of Surendra, Rajendra decided to take the responsibility of removing Jung Bahadur upon himself and declaring himself as the leader of the army, he left Benaras. Rajendra then appointed Guru Prasad Shah as the Chief of the Army for the operation of removal of Jung Bahadur Rana from Nepal and started to accumulate weapons and training the troops. Antagonism from the [[Company rule in India|British-India Company]] forced Rajendra and his troops to enter Nepal. On the 23rd of July, the troops reached a village called [[Alau, Nepal|Alau]] in Bara and set a camp there. One spy group of the Government of Nepal was keeping close eyes on the event of the rebel groups at [[Bettiah]]. They sent the news to Jung Bahadur, immediately after which he sent a troop in the leadership of Sanak Singh Tandon to Alau. They were told to suppress the rebellions, arrest Rajendra and bring him to Kathmandu. On the 27th of July, the ''Gorakhnath Paltan'' (Gorakhnath Battalion) reached and rested in a village called [[Simraungadh]], not too far from Alau. The battle of Alau was a decisive one between the forces of King Rajendra and Jang Bahadur. The King lost significantly in the battle. If the massacre of Kot had established Jung Bahadur as a dictator, the battle of Alau had helped him strengthen his dictatorship. Rajendra was imprisoned in an old palace in Bhaktapur.<ref name=\"Britanta\"/>\n=== Rise to royalty ===\nOn 15 May 1848, a Lal Mohar (Red sealed document) was issued claiming descent from [[Sisodia|Ranas of Mewar]] and authorizing the Kunwar family of Jang Bahadur to style themselves as '''Kunwar Ranaji'''.{{sfn|Whelpton|1991|p=253}} On 6 August 1856, Jang Bahadur Kunwar (now Ranaji) was conferred the title of [[Maharaja]] ('''Great King''') of Kaski and Lamjung, two former hill principalities, by King of Nepal, [[Surendra Bikram Shah]].{{sfn|Whelpton|1991|p=192}}\n\n==Rana Regime; Rule of the Shamshers==\n[[File:Bir_Shamsher JBR.jpg|thumb|[[Bir Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]], the first Shamsher Rana ruler]]\nIn 1885, the Shumsher family, the nephews of [[Jang Bahadur]], murdered many of the sons of [[Jung Bahadur]] and took over Nepal in a military [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] thus bringing in the rule of the Shamsher Rana family also known as the Satra Bhai (17 brothers) Rana family. They murdered [[Renaudip Singh Bahadur|Sri Teen Maharaja Ranodip Singh]] and occupied the hereditary throne of Prime Minister. After this they added [[Jang Bahadur]] to their name, although they were descended from Jang's younger brother Dhir Shamsher<ref name=\"PurushottamShamsher1990\" />\n\n== Kunwar family tree ==\n{{tree chart/start |summary= Ram Krishna Kunwar was born to Ahiram Kunwar.{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=193}}{{sfn|Wright|1877|p=286}} He had only a son named [[Ranjit Kunwar]] and three grandsons; [[Bal Narsingh Kunwar]], Balram Kunwar and Rewant Kunwar.{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=193}} Bal Narsingh had nine sons in the birth order; Bhakta Bir Kunwar, [[Jang Bahadur Kunwar]], [[Bam Bahadur Kunwar]], Badri Narsingh Kunwar, Jaya Bahadur Kunwar, Krishna Bahadur Kunwar, [[Ranodip Singh Kunwar|Ranauddip Singh Kunwar]], Jagat Shamsher Kunwar and Dhir Shamsher Kunwar.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royalark.net/Nepal/lamb2.htm |title=Lamb2 |accessdate=2 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180203210425/http://www.royalark.net/Nepal/lamb2.htm |archive-date=3 February 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n{{tree chart| | | | | | | | | | | | | RKK | | RKK='''[[Ram Krishna Kunwar]]'''}}\n{{tree chart| | | | | | | | | | | | | |!| |}}\n{{tree chart| | | | | | | | | | | | |RJK| | RJK=[[Ranajit Kunwar]]|}}\n{{tree chart| |,|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|v|-|^|-|-|-|-|-|.|}}\n{{tree chart| BNK| | | | | | | | BRK | | | | | | RwK|BNK='''[[Bal Narsingh Kunwar]]'''|BRK=Balaram Kunwar|RwK=Rewant Kunwar}}\n{{tree chart| |)|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|.|}}\n{{tree chart| BBK| | JBK| | BBaK| | BNK | | JBaK | | KBK | |RSK | | JSK | | DSK | BBK= Bhakta Bir Kunwar|JBK='''[[Jang Bahadur Kunwar]]'''|BBaK= [[Bam Bahadur Kunwar]] | BNK= Badri Narsingh Kunwar |JBaK=Jaya Bahadur Kunwar|KBK= Krishna Bahadur Kunwar |RSK='''[[Ranodip Singh Kunwar|Ranauddip Singh Kunwar]]'''|JSK=Jagat Shamsher Kunwar|DSK=[[Dhir Shamsher Rana|Dhir Shamsher Kunwar]]}}\n{{tree chart/end}}\n\n== Rana Prime Ministers ==\nNine Rana rulers took the hereditary office(s) of Prime Minister, Supreme Commander-in-Chief and Grand Master of the Royal Orders. All were crowned as the Maharaja of [[Lamjung District|Lamjung]] and [[Kaski District|Kaski]].\n\n{{Tree list}}\n* [[Ranajit Kunwar]] Rana (1723\u20131815)\n** {{Tree list/final branch}} [[Bal Narsingh Kunwar]] Rana (1783\u20131841)\n*** [[File:Simple silver crown.svg|15px]] '''I. Shr\u012b T\u012bn [[Jung Bahadur Rana]]''' [[Order of the Bath|GCB]], [[Order of the Star of India|GCSI]] (18 June 1816 \u2013 25 February 1877). Prime Minister and C-in-C 15 September 1846 to 1 August 1856 and from 28 June 1857 until his death. Granted the hereditary title of ''Rana'' on 5 May 1848, as a suffix to the male members of his family. Granted the hereditary title of ''Maharaja of Lamjung and Kaski'' (to be enjoyed \u2018offspring to offspring\u2019, and the hereditary offices of Prime Minister and C-in-C (to be enjoyed in succession by his surviving brothers, his sons, then his nephews), 6 August 1856. Received a [[salute]] of 19 guns from the [[United Kingdom|British]].\n*** [[Bam Bahadur Kunwar]] Rana (1818 \u2013 25 May 1857; Prime Minister: 1 August 1856 \u2013 25 May 1857)\n*** [[File:Simple silver crown.svg|15px]] '''II. Shr\u012b T\u012bn [[Ranodip Singh Kunwar]] (aka Ranodip Singh Rana)''' [[Order of the Star of India|KCSI]] (3 April 1825 \u2013 assassinated 22 November 1885). Ruled 25 February 1877 to 22 November 1885.\n*** {{Tree list/final branch}} General Sri [[Dhir Shumsher Kunwar Rana]] (1828\u20131884)\n**** [[File:Simple silver crown.svg|15px]] '''III. Shr\u012b T\u012bn [[Bir Shumsher Jung Bahadur Rana]]''' [[Order of the Star of India|GCSI]] (10 December 1852 \u2013 5 March 1901). Ruled 22 November 1885 to 5 March 1901.\n**** [[File:Simple silver crown.svg|15px]] '''IV. Shr\u012b T\u012bn [[Dev Shumsher Jung Bahadur Rana]]''' (17 July 1862 \u2013 20 February 1914). Ruled 5 March to 27 June 1901, when as a result of his progressive nature, he was deposed by his relatives and [[exile]]d to India.\n**** [[File:Simple silver crown.svg|15px]] '''V. Shr\u012b T\u012bn [[Chandra Shumsher Jung Bahadur Rana]]''' [[Order of the Bath|GCB]], [[Order of the Star of India|GCSI]], [[Order of St Michael and St George|GCMG]], [[Royal Victorian Order|GCVO]] (8 July 1863 \u2013 26 November 1929). Ruled 27 June 1901 to 26 November 1929.\n***** {{Tree list/final branch}} [[File:Simple silver crown.svg|15px]] '''IX. Shr\u012b T\u012bn [[Mohan Shumsher JBR|Mohan Shumsher Jung Bahadur Rana]]''' [[Order of the Bath|GCB]], [[Order of the Star of India|GCIE]], [[Order of the British Empire|GBE]] (23 December 1885 \u2013 6 January 1967). Ruled 30 April 1948 to 18 February 1951, at which date he was divested of his titles and later went to [[India]].\n**** [[File:Simple silver crown.svg|15px]] '''VI. Shr\u012b T\u012bn [[Bhim Shumsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]''' [[Order of the Star of India|GCSI]], [[Order of St Michael and St George|GCMG]], [[Royal Victorian Order|KCVO]] (16 April 1865 \u2013 1 September 1932). Ruled 26 November 1929 to 1 September 1932.\n***** {{Tree list/final branch}} [[File:Simple silver crown.svg|15px]] '''VIII. Shr\u012b T\u012bn [[Padma Shumsher Jung Bahadur Rana]]''' [[Order of the Star of India|GCSI]], [[Order of the Indian Empire|GCIE]], [[Order of the British Empire|GBE]], (5 December 1882 \u2013 11 April 1961). Ruled 29 November 1945 to 30 April 1948, whereupon he [[abdicated]] in favor of his cousin.\n**** {{Tree list/final branch}} [[File:Simple silver crown.svg|15px]] '''VII. Shr\u012b T\u012bn [[Juddha Shumsher Jung Bahadur Rana]]''' [[Order of the Bath|GCB]], [[Order of the Star of India|GCSI]], [[Order of the Indian Empire|GCIE]] (19 April 1875 \u2013 20 November 1952). Ruled 1 September 1932 to 29 November 1945, whereupon he [[Abdication|abdicated]] in favor of his nephew.\n{{Tree list/end}}\n\n=== Succession ===\nSuccession to the role of the Prime Ministers and the title of ''Maharaja of Lamjung and Kaski'' was by [[agnatic seniority]], by which the oldest male heir among the sons of equal (a-class) marriages in a generation would succeed. The order of succession was determined by seniority, with each eligible male heir holding a military command, as follows:\n\n# Prime Minister and Commander-in-Chief (Mukhtiyar the Heir Apparent, with the rank of Field Marshal).\n# Western Commanding-General.\n# Eastern Commanding-General.\n# Southern Commanding-General.\n# Northern Commanding-General.\n\n==Notable Rana members==\n*[[Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Bam Bahadur Kunwar]]\n*[[Ranodip Singh Kunwar]]\n*[[Bir Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Dev Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Chandra Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Bhim Shumsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Juddha Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Rudra Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Padma Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Mohan Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Baber Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Kaiser Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Kiran Shamsher Rana]]\n*[[Nir Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Toran Shumsher J.B.R.]]\n*[[Nara Shumsher J.B.R.]]\n*[[Ratna Shumsher J.B.R.]]\n*[[Pradip Shumsher J.B.R.]]\n*[[Satchit Rana|Satchit Shamsher Jung Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Pashupati Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Madhukar Shamsher Rana]]\n*[[Om Bikram Rana]]\n*[[Gaurav Shumsher JB Rana]]\n*[[Udaya Shumsher Rana]], great-grandson of Baber\n\n===Other notable connected members===\n*[[Ranajit Pande]], maternal grandfather of Ganesh Kumari, mother of [[Jung Bahadur Rana]]\n*[[Nain Singh Thapa]] was father-in-law of [[Bal Narsingh Kunwar]].\n*[[George Jivaji Rao Scindia]], father-in-law of [[Pashupati Shamsher Jang Bahadur Rana]].\n*[[Surya Bahadur Thapa]], brother-in-law of Himalaya Shamsher JBR\n*[[Prithvi Bahadur Pande]], son-in-law of Himalaya Shamsher JBR\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Rana couple.jpg|Major-General Vishnu Shamsher Rana and wife\nFile:Rana family 1915.jpg|Commanding General Babar Shumsher Rana and family\nFile:Dhir Shamsher Rana and sons bw.jpg|Dhir Shamsher Rana and sons make up Shamsher Rana dynasty\nFile:Chandra Shamsher and sons.jpg|Chandra Shamsher and sons\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Daudaha system]]\n* [[Pajani System]]\n* [[Rolls of Succession in Rana (Nepal)]]\n* [[History of Nepal]]\n* [[Rana palaces of Nepal]]\n* [[Thapa dynasty]]\n\n== References ==\n=== Footnotes ===\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{Cite book |title=The Bloodstained Throne: Struggles for Power in Nepal (1775\u20131914) |last=Acharya |first=Baburam |publisher=Penguin Books Ltd |year=2013 |isbn=978-0-14-341637-1 |location=New Delhi |url=https://books.google.com/?id=UWQtAAAAQBAJ&dq=bloodstained+acharya}}\n* {{citation |last=Acharya |first=Baburam |editor-last=Acharya |editor-first=Shri Krishna |title=Janaral Bhimsen Thapa : Yinko Utthan Tatha Pattan |location=Kathmandu |year=2012 |pages=228 |language=Nepali |publisher=Education Book House |isbn=9789937241748}}\n* {{citation |last=Adhikari |first=Krishna Kant |title=Nepal Under Jang Bahadur, 1846\u20131877 |volume=1 |publisher