1       = \n|nationalgoals1      = \n|club-update         = 14:44, 6 February 2019 (UTC)\n|nationalteam-update = \n}}\n\n'''Charles Teiko Folley''' (born 1 November 1991) is a [[Ghana]]ian [[association football|footballer]] who currently plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]]\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n{{updated|6 February 2019.}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ktff.org/BilgiBankasi/FutbolcuDetayi/16321?sid_SelectedText=2018-2019&sid_SelectedIndex=0&sid=12 |title=Charles Teiko Folley |accessdate=6 February 2019 |publisher=Cyprus Turkish Football Association}}</ref><ref>{{Soccerway|charles-teiko-folley/591684|accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n|-\n|Cihangir\n|2016\u201317\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[KTFF S\u00fcper Lig]]\n|28||1||4<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"KK\">Appearances in the [[Cypriot Cup (Northern Cyprus)|K\u0131br\u0131s Kupas\u0131]]</ref>||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||0||0||32||1\n|-\n|[[G\u00f6nyeli S.K.|G\u00f6nyeli]]\n|2018\u201319\n|14||8||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||0||0||14||8\n|-\n|[[Gokulam Kerala FC|Gokulam Kerala]]\n|[[2018\u201319 I-League|2018\u201319]]\n|[[I-League]]\n|3||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||0||0||3||0\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" |'''Career total'''\n!45!!8!!4!!0!!0!!0!!0!!0!!49!!8\n|}\n;Notes\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Folley, Charles Teiko}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian footballers]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:I-League players]]\n[[Category:Ittihad Al-Zarqa players]]\n[[Category:G\u00f6nyeli S.K. players]]\n[[Category:Aswan SC players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Tajikistan]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Jordan]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Northern Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in Northern Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in India]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in India]]\n\n\n{{Ghana-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Coyets", "label": "safe", "comment": "Full stop added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Teiko_Folley"}
{"title_page": "O'Higgins family", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Royal house|\n|surname = O'Higgins<br>''{{lang|ga|\u00d3 hUiginn}}''\n|coat of arms = [[File:O'Higgins of Ballynary Coat of Arms. Spain 1788 and 2011. Cronista de Armas de Castille y Leon..jpg|frameless|upright=0.5]]<br>Arms of The O'Higgins, Lords of Ballynary\n|country =[[Kingdom of Connacht]]\n| parent house = [[Southern U\u00ed N\u00e9ill]]\n|titles =\n\n'''Kingdom of Connacht'''\n* Lord of [[Monteige]]\n* Lord of [[Ballynary]]\n'''Kingdom of Spain'''\n* [[Ambrose O'Higgins|Marquis of Osorno]]\n* [[Ambrose O'Higgins|Bar\u00f3n de Vallenar]]\n* [[John Higgins of Montoge|Councillor of Castille]]\n'''Jacobite Peerage'''\n* [[John Higgins of Montoge|Baronet of Montoge]]\n'''Royal House of Georgia'''\n* Baron O'Higgins\n\n|current head = Karl Aiden O'Higgins\n\n|nationality = [[Irish people|Irish]]}}\n\n'''O'Higgins''' (Irish: ''[[\u00d3 hUiginn]]'') is an Irish noble family. Its Ballynary line is descended from Shean Duff O'Higgins ([[floruit|fl.]] 1600 C.E.), Gaelic Baron of Ballynary, who was married to a daughter of the [[O'Conor Don|royal family of O'Conor]] at Ballintuber Castle in Connacht. Shean Duff O'Higgins himself claimed descent from King Niall of [[Hill of Tara|Tara]] (d. 450 C.E.).<ref>The National Genealogical Office (Dublin), MS 165. p. 396-399.</ref><ref>''Annals of the Four Masters'' M378-405</ref><ref>Geoffrey Keating, Foras Feasa ar \u00c9irinn 1.48, 1.49, 1.50, 51, 52</ref> Historically, many of their ancestors were poets and scholars who enjoyed the patronage of several chiefly families including [[O'Conor Don]], [[MacDermott (disambiguation)|MacDermott]], [[O'Doherty]], [[O'Gara]], and [[MacDonagh]].\n\nO'Higgins are counted among the Gaelic nobility as a [[sept]] of the [[O'Neill dynasty|royal house of O'Neill]].<ref>See [[List of Irish clans]].The National Genealogical Office (Dublin), MS 165. p. 396-399.</ref><ref>Genealogy of \u00d3 hUiginn from O Clery Book of Genealogies (based on edition by S\u00e9amus Pender, Analecta Hibernica 15, 1951)</ref> Members of this family were further ennobled in 1724 by [[James Francis Edward Stuart|James III]] ([[pretender]] to the throne of England and Ireland) during his exile in France, and again in 1795 and 1796 by [[Charles IV of Spain]].\n\n==Family name==\nEarlier scholars traced the origin of the name from the word \"knowledge\" in Irish, possible linked to the family's early prominence as bards to the Gaelic Kings.<ref>letter from Prof. E\u00f3in Mac Neill to Prof. Knott written in December 1919.</ref> However, more recent scholars have identified that \"uigin\" refers to a Norse seafarer or Viking.<ref>The bardic poems of Tadhg Dall \u00d3 hUiginn (1550\u20131591), [[Eleanor Knott]] (ed.), London, 1920 and 1926</ref> In Gaelic times the prefix U\u00ed before a name was used to signify descent from a grandson, this family are said to have descended from the grandson of Uiginn who lived in the 11th century or possibly from a previous Uiginn who was a grandson of King Niall of Tara. In modern times the surname has often been translated from Irish into \"Higgins\" in English although members the more senior branches of the family continue to use \"O'Higgins\".\n\n===Background===\nThe O'Higgins family originated in the [[Kingdom of Meath]] and [[Kings of Brega|Brega]] which equate to the modern Irish counties of [[County Meath|Meath]] and [[Westmeath]]. As a [[sept]] of the [[Southern U\u00ed N\u00e9ill]] their roots in these areas can be traced at least to the 5th century and possibly even earlier. By the 12th century the senior branch of the family had migrated into the [[Kingdom of Connacht]] where they settled and were granted large estates by the [[O'Conor Don|O'Conors]] in [[Sligo]] at Dooghorne and Monteige in the Barony of [[Luighne Connacht|Luighne]] under the protection of the O'Hara Chiefs and at [[Ballynary]] in the Barony of Tir-Errill under the protection of the MacDonagh Chiefs.\n\nFrom the Council of Drom Ceat in 574 AD up to the end of the Gaelic era in the 17th century various members of the O'Higgins clan were hereditary poets (''fil\u00e9s'' in Irish) in the courts of [[Chiefs of the Name|Irish Princes and Chiefs]].<ref>The Book of Glendalough Rawlinson MS B 502 Oxford, Bodleian Library c. AD 1130</ref><ref>Keating, G. The History of Ireland. Section 10.</ref> As hereditary poets they were accorded a status of nobility second in rank only to the King and were entitled to wear the same number of colours in their robes. Members of this family came under the patronage of other Irish noble houses particularly [[O'Conor Don|\u00d3 Conor]], [[O'Neill dynasty|\u00d3 Neill]], MacDonagh, [[O'Rourke|\u00d3 Rourke]], [[Maguire (surname)|Maguire]], [[O'Doherty family|\u00d3 Doherty]], [[Mac Diarmata|Mac Dermot]] and [[\u00d3 Gadhra|\u00d3 Gara]]. From the 14th to the 17th centuries the O'Higgins were among the most prolific poets in the courts of the Irish Princes.:<ref>Eleanor Knott, Bardic Poems of Tadhg Dall \u00d3 hUiginn (1922), I, xx\u2013xxii:</ref>\n\n===Loss of status and migration===\nDue to their loyalty to Gaelic culture and religion, the O'Higgins family of Ballynary suffered under the English Crown in [[Ireland]] and by 1654 had lost their lands in Sligo.<ref>O'Rorke, T. (1889) \"The History of Sligo Town and County Vol. II \u2013 Conclusion\" (Dublin: Duffy & Company).</ref> While some members of the family remained in Sligo as tenants on their own lands, some members of the family migrated to [[Spain]] where they achieved high office in the service of the King. The O'Higgins of Ballynary migrated to Summerhill in Co. Meath where they lived at Clondoogan and Agher.\n\nIn 1751 [[Ambrose O'Higgins]] (ca. 1720\u20131801) left [[Summerhill, County Meath|Summerhill]] in Co. [[County Meath|Meath]] for [[Cadiz]] in Spain from where he went to [[Peru]] and [[Chile]]. In 1788 he became [[Royal Governor of Chile|Governor General]] of [[Chile]]. He was ennobled by [[King Carlos IV|King Carlos IV of Spain]] initially in 1795 as 1st Bar\u00f3n de Ballinar and again in 1796 when he was raised to Marqu\u00e9s de Osorno.<ref>Letters patent from King Carlos IV 27 January 1796 in Archives of the Indies.</ref> His son [[Bernardo O'Higgins]] became the first Head of State of [[Chile]] in 1818. His son Pedro Demetrio O'Higgins Puga (1818\u20131868) was a Chilean politician and entrepreneur. Ambrose O'Higgins' brother William (Guillermo) O`Higgins (1722\u20131772) was Captain of the Spanish troops and Colonial Administrator in Paraguay.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Portrait of Ambrosio O'Higgins.jpg|Ambrosio O'Higgins, 1st Marquis of Osorno.\nFile:Bernardo O\u00b4Higgins por Ceballos.JPG|Bernardo O'Higgins (1778-1842), 1st Head of State of Chile.\nFile:Demetrio O\u00b4Higgins.jpg|Pedro Demetrio O'Higgins Puga (1818-1868), Chilean Politician and Entrepreneur.\n</gallery>\n\nThe [[Ballynary]] line of the O'Higgins family continued at [[Summerhill, County Meath|Summerhill]] in [[County Meath]] until 1947. Karl Aiden O'Higgins of [[Cheshire]] in England now represents the family title.\n\n[[John Higgins of Montoge|Sir John Higgins]] Bt of Monteige, kinsman to the O'Higgins of Ballynary, was knighted and ennobled by (soi-disant) King [[James Francis Edward Stuart|James III]] in 1724 in return for his services to France. He was senior physician to the King of Spain. His cousin Don Esteban de Igui\u00f1o (Stephen Higgins) was a General in the Spanish Colonial Army in the Philippines.<ref>Archivo General de Indias (Sevilla), Filipinas, 194, N.38: Petici\u00f3n de Juan de Egui\u00f1o para que se d\u00e9 licencia a Esteban de Egui\u00f1o para venir a Espa\u00f1a a defenderse. 1719\u20131723</ref>\n\n==Notable members of the family==\n\n*[[Tadhg M\u00f3r \u00d3 hUiginn]] (died 1315)\n*Giolla na Naomh \u00d3 hUiginn (died 1349)\n*Raghnall \u00d3 hUiginn (died 1325)\n*Niall \u00d3 hUiginn (died 1340)\n*Tadhg \u00d3g mac Giolla Choluim \u00d3 hUiginn (died 1391)\n*Uilliam \u00d3 hUiginn (died 1378)\n*[[Fercert \u00d3 hUiginn]], Irish poet (died 1419).\n*Ruaidhri Ruadh \u00d3 hUiginn (died 1425)\n*Fearghal Ruadh mac Taidhg mheic Giolla Choluim \u00d3 hUiginn\n*[[Tadg \u00d3g \u00d3 hUiginn|Tadhg \u00d3g mac Taidhg mheic Giolla Choluim \u00d3 hUiginn]] (died 1448)\n*Tuathal \u00d3 hUiginn (died 1450), Brian \u00d3 hUiginn (died 1476)\n*Domhnall mac Briain U\u00ed Uiginn (died 1502)\n*Pilip Bocht \u00d3 hUiginn (died 1487)\n*Se\u00e1n mac Ruaidhri U\u00ed Uiginn\n*[[Bernard O'Higgins]], Bishop of Elphin, (died 1564)\n*[[Tadhg Dall \u00d3 hUiginn]] (1550\u20131591)\n*[[Ballynary|Shean Duff O'Higgins]] (fl. 1600), Baron of Ballynary.<ref>National Genealogical Office (Dublin), MS 165. p. 396-399.</ref>\n*[[John Higgins of Montoge|Sir John Higgins]] of Montoge (died 1729), Knight, Baronet and Counsillor of Castille<ref>The pedigrees and papers of James Terry, Athlone Herald at the court of James II in France(1690\u20131725)\" edited by Charles Lart</ref>\n*Don [[Ambrose O'Higgins]] (died 1801), Knight, 1st Marquess de Osorno, 1st Bar\u00f3n de Valenar.<ref>(Ricardo Donoso, El Marqu\u00e9s de Osorno: Don Ambrosio Higgins, Santiago, Publicaciones de la Universidad de Chile, 1942 p.53.</ref><ref>National Genealogical Office (Dublin), MS 165. p. 396-399.</ref>\n*Don William (Guillermo) O'Higgins (born 1725), Spanish Colonial Administrator in Paraguay<ref>Velilla, Benjam\u00edn, Parentesco de Bernardo O'Higgins Con Los Yegro del Paraguay en el \"Anuario del Instituto Paraguayo de Investigaciones Hist\u00f3ricas\" Vols. 6, 7 (1962). La versi\u00f3n en l\u00ednea incluye una entrevista con la se\u00f1ora Candida O'Higgins en \u00daltima Hora peri\u00f3dico (Asunci\u00f3n), 6 de febrero de 1985, p\u00e1gina web(http://usuarios.lycos.es/fulgencioyegros/parentesco.html), citado 06 de febrero 2007.</ref>\n*Don [[Bernardo O'Higgins]] (died 1842), first head of state of Chile\n*Pedro Demetrio O'Higgins Puga (died 1868), industrialist and Chilean politician<ref>Demetrio O'Higgins by Jorge Iba\u00f1ez Vergara.</ref>\n*Joyce Ginatta O'Higgins, South American business woman and public figure<ref>[http://www.hacer.org/pdf/Montaner08.pdf Montaner, C.A. Twisted Roots, A Look at the Historical and Cultural Influences that Shaped Latin America].</ref>\n*Dr. [[James O'Higgins Norman]] (born 1968), Irish academic and author at Dublin City University\n*Pearse Higgins, former president of [[North America Caribbean Rugby Association]]\n\n==Arms==\nThe O'Higgins family are [[armigerous]] in the [[Kingdom of Ireland]], the Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland (Jacobite) and in the [[Kingdom of Spain]].<ref>The National Genealogical Office (Dublin), MS 165. p. 396-399.</ref><ref>Archivo del cronista de armas de Castilla y Le\u00f3n, Registrada al N\u00famero 31 del a\u00f1o 2011.</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Arms of Sir John Higgins of Monteige.jpg|Arms of [[John Higgins of Montoge|Sir John Higgins of Montoge Bt]],(Athlone Pursuivant of Arms, 1724).\nFile:O'Higgins of Ballynary Coat of Arms. Spain 1788 and 2011. Cronista de Armas de Castille y Leon..jpg|Arms of the O'Higgins of Ballynary (by Ulster King of Arms, 1788; Cronista Rey de Armas, 1795; Cronista de Armas de Castilla y Le\u00f3n, 2011)\nFile:Escudo de Osorno.svg|Arms of [[Ambrose O'Higgins]], 1st Marquis of Osorno (Cronista Rey de Armas de Castilla y Le\u00f3n. 1796\nFile:Arms of James O\u2019Higgins Norman.png|Coat of Arms [[James O'Higgins Norman|Dr. James O'Higgins Norman]] (Cronista Rey de Armas de Castilla y Le\u00f3n 2011).\n</gallery>\n\nThe earliest known coat of arms was recorded in 1724 by [[John Higgins of Montoge|Sir John Higgins Bt]] of Montoge with Sir James Terry, Athlone Herald in the Court of James II at St. Germaine. Sir John Higgins's branch of the family moved to Limerick after they lost their lands at Monteige in Sligo and eventually relocated in France and later in Spain where John Higgins was knighted and became personal physician to the King of Spain.\n\nThe descent of the Arms of Shean Duff O'Higgins, Baron of Ballynary were recorded in the Office of Ulster King of Arms in 1788 having existed for at least the previous 200 years.<ref>Genealogical Office, Dublin MS 165. p. 396-399.</ref> and were later recorded in the same year with the Cronista Rey de Armas in Madrid eventually descending to Thomas O'Higgins of Cheshire.<ref>The National Genealogical Office (Dublin), MS 165. p. 396-399.</ref><ref>Archivo del cronista de armas de Castilla y Le\u00f3n, Registrada al N\u00famero 31 del a\u00f1o 2011.</ref>\n\nIn 1788, Don Ambrose O'Higgins obtained a certificate of descent and the right to use the Ballynary Arms with due difference from Ulster King of Arms (Kingdom of Ireland) and subsequently received a grant from the Cronista Rey de Armas (Kingdom of Spain).<ref>Genealogical Office, Dublin MS 165. p. 396-399.</ref> His Coat of Arms was then adopted in 1796 as the official emblem of the city of Osorno in Chile after which he had been ennobled as Marquis of Osorno.\n\n[[James O'Higgins Norman|Dr. James O'Higgins Norman]] recorded Arms in 2011 with the Cronista Rey de Armas de Castilla y Le\u00f3n before being admitted as a Caballero in La Casa Troncal de los Doce Linajes de Soria.<ref>Qued\u00f3 Inscrito en el Libro General de Linajes, Libro I, Asiento N\u00b0 82.</ref>\n\n==Fictional References==\nIn the TV episode of ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'' \"The Case of the Guilty Clients\" the Suspect is a South American from the Argentine named \"O'Higgins\" implying that she is a descendant of Don Bernardo O'Higgins\u2014although in fact Bernardo O'Higgins was a resident of Chile\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ohigginsclan.com/ The O'Higgins Clan, A Sept of the Royal House of O'Neill]\n* [http://www.theclansofireland.ie/ Finte na h\u00c9ireann ~ Clans of Ireland]\n\n{{Connachta}}\n{{Gaels}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ohiggins}}\n[[Category:Spanish noble families]]\n[[Category:Chilean nobility]]\n[[Category:U\u00ed N\u00e9ill]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Royal house|\n|surname = O'Higgins<br>''{{lang|ga|\u00d3 hUiginn}}''\n|coat of arms = [[File:O'Higgins of Ballynary Coat of Arms. Spain 1788 and 2011. Cronista de Armas de Castille y Leon..jpg|frameless|upright=0.5]]<br>Arms of The O'Higgins, Lords of Ballynary\n|country =[[Kingdom of Connacht]]\n| parent house = [[Southern U\u00ed N\u00e9ill]]\n|titles =\n\n'''Kingdom of Connacht'''\n* Lord of [[Monteige]]\n* Lord of [[Ballynary]]\n'''Kingdom of Spain'''\n* [[Ambrose O'Higgins|Marquis of Osorno]]\n* [[Ambrose O'Higgins|Bar\u00f3n de Vallenar]]\n* [[John Higgins of Montoge|Councillor of Castille]]\n'''Jacobite Peerage'''\n* [[John Higgins of Montoge|Baronet of Montoge]]\n'''Royal House of Georgia'''\n* Baron O'Higgins\n\n|current head = Karl Aiden O'Higgins\n\n|nationality = [[Irish people|Irish]]}}\n\n'''O'Higgins''' (Irish: ''[[\u00d3 hUiginn]]'') is an Irish noble family. Its Ballynary line is descended from Shean Duff O'Higgins ([[floruit|fl.]] 1600 C.E.), Gaelic Baron of Ballynary, who was married to a daughter of the [[O'Conor Don|royal family of O'Conor]] at Ballintuber Castle in Connacht. Shean Duff O'Higgins himself claimed descent from King Niall of [[Hill of Tara|Tara]] (d. 450 C.E.).<ref>The National Genealogical Office (Dublin), MS 165. p. 396-399.</ref><ref>''Annals of the Four Masters'' M378-405</ref><ref>Geoffrey Keating, Foras Feasa ar \u00c9irinn 1.48, 1.49, 1.50, 51, 52</ref> Historically, many of their ancestors were poets and scholars who enjoyed the patronage of several chiefly families including [[O'Conor Don]], [[MacDermott (disambiguation)|MacDermott]], [[O'Doherty]], [[O'Gara]], and [[MacDonagh]].\n\nO'Higgins are counted among the Gaelic nobility as a sept of the [[O'Neill dynasty|royal house of O'Neill]].<ref>See [[List of Irish clans]].The National Genealogical Office (Dublin), MS 165. p. 396-399.</ref><ref>Genealogy of \u00d3 hUiginn from O Clery Book of Genealogies (based on edition by S\u00e9amus Pender, Analecta Hibernica 15, 1951)</ref> Members of this family were further ennobled in 1724 by [[James Francis Edward Stuart|James III]] ([[pretender]] to the throne of England and Ireland) during his in exile in France, and again in 1795 and 1796 by [[Charles IV of Spain]].\n\n==Family name==\nEarlier scholars traced the origin of the name from the word \"knowledge\" in Irish, possible linked to the family's early prominence as bards to the Gaelic Kings.<ref>letter from Prof. E\u00f3in Mac Neill to Prof. Knott written in December 1919.</ref> However, more recent scholars have identified that \"uigin\" refers to a Norse seafarer or Viking.<ref>The bardic poems of Tadhg Dall \u00d3 hUiginn (1550\u20131591), [[Eleanor Knott]] (ed.), London, 1920 and 1926</ref> In Gaelic times the prefix U\u00ed before a name was used to signify descent from a grandson, this family are said to have descended from the grandson of Uiginn who lived in the 11th century or possibly from a previous Uiginn who was a grandson of King Niall of Tara. In modern times the surname has often been translated from Irish into \"Higgins\" in English although members the more senior branches of the family continue to use \"O'Higgins\".\n\n===Background===\nThe O'Higgins family originated in the [[Kingdom of Meath]] and [[Kings of Brega|Brega]] which equate to the modern Irish counties of [[County Meath|Meath]] and [[Westmeath]]. As a [[sept]] of the [[Southern U\u00ed N\u00e9ill]] their roots in these areas can be traced at least to the 5th century and possibly even earlier. By the 12th century the senior branch of the family had migrated into the [[Kingdom of Connacht]] where they settled and were granted large estates by the [[O'Conor Don|O'Conors]] in [[Sligo]] at Dooghorne and Monteige in the Barony of [[Luighne Connacht|Luighne]] under the protection of the O'Hara Chiefs and at [[Ballynary]] in the Barony of Tir-Errill under the protection of the MacDonagh Chiefs.\n\nFrom the Council of Drom Ceat in 574 AD up to the end of the Gaelic era in the 17th century various members of the O'Higgins clan were hereditary poets (''fil\u00e9s'' in Irish) in the courts of [[Chiefs of the Name|Irish Princes and Chiefs]].<ref>The Book of Glendalough Rawlinson MS B 502 Oxford, Bodleian Library c. AD 1130</ref><ref>Keating, G. The History of Ireland. Section 10.</ref> As hereditary poets they were accorded a status of nobility second in rank only to the King and were entitled to wear the same number of colours in their robes. Members of this family came under the patronage of other Irish noble houses particularly [[O'Conor Don|\u00d3 Conor]], [[O'Neill dynasty|\u00d3 Neill]], MacDonagh, [[O'Rourke|\u00d3 Rourke]], [[Maguire (surname)|Maguire]], [[O'Doherty family|\u00d3 Doherty]], [[Mac Diarmata|Mac Dermot]] and [[\u00d3 Gadhra|\u00d3 Gara]]. From the 14th to the 17th centuries the O'Higgins were among the most prolific poets in the courts of the Irish Princes.:<ref>Eleanor Knott, Bardic Poems of Tadhg Dall \u00d3 hUiginn (1922), I, xx\u2013xxii:</ref>\n\n===Loss of status and migration===\nDue to their loyalty to Gaelic culture and religion, the O'Higgins family of Ballynary suffered under the English Crown in [[Ireland]] and by 1654 had lost their lands in Sligo.<ref>O'Rorke, T. (1889) \"The History of Sligo Town and County Vol. II \u2013 Conclusion\" (Dublin: Duffy & Company).</ref> While some members of the family remained in Sligo as tenants on their own lands, some members of the family migrated to [[Spain]] where they achieved high office in the service of the King. The O'Higgins of Ballynary migrated to Summerhill in Co. Meath where they lived at Clondoogan and Agher.\n\nIn 1751 [[Ambrose O'Higgins]] (ca. 1720\u20131801) left [[Summerhill, County Meath|Summerhill]] in Co. [[County Meath|Meath]] for [[Cadiz]] in Spain from where he went to [[Peru]] and [[Chile]]. In 1788 he became [[Royal Governor of Chile|Governor General]] of [[Chile]]. He was ennobled by [[King Carlos IV|King Carlos IV of Spain]] initially in 1795 as 1st Bar\u00f3n de Ballinar and again in 1796 when he was raised to Marqu\u00e9s de Osorno.<ref>Letters patent from King Carlos IV 27 January 1796 in Archives of the Indies.</ref> His son [[Bernardo O'Higgins]] became the first Head of State of [[Chile]] in 1818. His son Pedro Demetrio O'Higgins Puga (1818\u20131868) was a Chilean politician and entrepreneur. Ambrose O'Higgins' brother William (Guillermo) O`Higgins (1722\u20131772) was Captain of the Spanish troops and Colonial Administrator in Paraguay.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Portrait of Ambrosio O'Higgins.jpg|Ambrosio O'Higgins, 1st Marquis of Osorno.\nFile:Bernardo O\u00b4Higgins por Ceballos.JPG|Bernardo O'Higgins (1778-1842), 1st Head of State of Chile.\nFile:Demetrio O\u00b4Higgins.jpg|Pedro Demetrio O'Higgins Puga (1818-1868), Chilean Politician and Entrepreneur.\n</gallery>\n\nThe [[Ballynary]] line of the O'Higgins family continued at [[Summerhill, County Meath|Summerhill]] in [[County Meath]] until 1947. Karl Aiden O'Higgins of [[Cheshire]] in England now represents the family title.\n\n[[John Higgins of Montoge|Sir John Higgins]] Bt of Monteige, kinsman to the O'Higgins of Ballynary, was knighted and ennobled by (soi-disant) King [[James Francis Edward Stuart|James III]] in 1724 in return for his services to France. He was senior physician to the King of Spain. His cousin Don Esteban de Igui\u00f1o (Stephen Higgins) was a General in the Spanish Colonial Army in the Philippines.<ref>Archivo General de Indias (Sevilla), Filipinas, 194, N.38: Petici\u00f3n de Juan de Egui\u00f1o para que se d\u00e9 licencia a Esteban de Egui\u00f1o para venir a Espa\u00f1a a defenderse. 1719\u20131723</ref>\n\n==Notable members of the family==\n\n*[[Tadhg M\u00f3r \u00d3 hUiginn]] (died 1315)\n*Giolla na Naomh \u00d3 hUiginn (died 1349)\n*Raghnall \u00d3 hUiginn (died 1325)\n*Niall \u00d3 hUiginn (died 1340)\n*Tadhg \u00d3g mac Giolla Choluim \u00d3 hUiginn (died 1391)\n*Uilliam \u00d3 hUiginn (died 1378)\n*[[Fercert \u00d3 hUiginn]], Irish poet (died 1419).\n*Ruaidhri Ruadh \u00d3 hUiginn (died 1425)\n*Fearghal Ruadh mac Taidhg mheic Giolla Choluim \u00d3 hUiginn\n*[[Tadg \u00d3g \u00d3 hUiginn|Tadhg \u00d3g mac Taidhg mheic Giolla Choluim \u00d3 hUiginn]] (died 1448)\n*Tuathal \u00d3 hUiginn (died 1450), Brian \u00d3 hUiginn (died 1476)\n*Domhnall mac Briain U\u00ed Uiginn (died 1502)\n*Pilip Bocht \u00d3 hUiginn (died 1487)\n*Se\u00e1n mac Ruaidhri U\u00ed Uiginn\n*[[Bernard O'Higgins]], Bishop of Elphin, (died 1564)\n*[[Tadhg Dall \u00d3 hUiginn]] (1550\u20131591)\n*[[Ballynary|Shean Duff O'Higgins]] (fl. 1600), Baron of Ballynary.<ref>National Genealogical Office (Dublin), MS 165. p. 396-399.</ref>\n*[[John Higgins of Montoge|Sir John Higgins]] of Montoge (died 1729), Knight, Baronet and Counsillor of Castille<ref>The pedigrees and papers of James Terry, Athlone Herald at the court of James II in France(1690\u20131725)\" edited by Charles Lart</ref>\n*Don [[Ambrose O'Higgins]] (died 1801), Knight, 1st Marquess de Osorno, 1st Bar\u00f3n de Valenar.<ref>(Ricardo Donoso, El Marqu\u00e9s de Osorno: Don Ambrosio Higgins, Santiago, Publicaciones de la Universidad de Chile, 1942 p.53.</ref><ref>National Genealogical Office (Dublin), MS 165. p. 396-399.</ref>\n*Don William (Guillermo) O'Higgins (born 1725), Spanish Colonial Administrator in Paraguay<ref>Velilla, Benjam\u00edn, Parentesco de Bernardo O'Higgins Con Los Yegro del Paraguay en el \"Anuario del Instituto Paraguayo de Investigaciones Hist\u00f3ricas\" Vols. 6, 7 (1962). La versi\u00f3n en l\u00ednea incluye una entrevista con la se\u00f1ora Candida O'Higgins en \u00daltima Hora peri\u00f3dico (Asunci\u00f3n), 6 de febrero de 1985, p\u00e1gina web(http://usuarios.lycos.es/fulgencioyegros/parentesco.html), citado 06 de febrero 2007.</ref>\n*Don [[Bernardo O'Higgins]] (died 1842), first head of state of Chile\n*Pedro Demetrio O'Higgins Puga (died 1868), industrialist and Chilean politician<ref>Demetrio O'Higgins by Jorge Iba\u00f1ez Vergara.</ref>\n*Joyce Ginatta O'Higgins, South American business woman and public figure<ref>[http://www.hacer.org/pdf/Montaner08.pdf Montaner, C.A. Twisted Roots, A Look at the Historical and Cultural Influences that Shaped Latin America].</ref>\n*Dr. [[James O'Higgins Norman]] (born 1968), Irish academic and author at Dublin City University\n*Pearse Higgins, former president of [[North America Caribbean Rugby Association]]\n\n==Arms==\nThe O'Higgins family are [[armigerous]] in the [[Kingdom of Ireland]], the Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland (Jacobite) and in the [[Kingdom of Spain]].<ref>The National Genealogical Office (Dublin), MS 165. p. 396-399.</ref><ref>Archivo del cronista de armas de Castilla y Le\u00f3n, Registrada al N\u00famero 31 del a\u00f1o 2011.</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Arms of Sir John Higgins of Monteige.jpg|Arms of [[John Higgins of Montoge|Sir John Higgins of Montoge Bt]],(Athlone Pursuivant of Arms, 1724).\nFile:O'Higgins of Ballynary Coat of Arms. Spain 1788 and 2011. Cronista de Armas de Castille y Leon..jpg|Arms of the O'Higgins of Ballynary (by Ulster King of Arms, 1788; Cronista Rey de Armas, 1795; Cronista de Armas de Castilla y Le\u00f3n, 2011)\nFile:Escudo de Osorno.svg|Arms of [[Ambrose O'Higgins]], 1st Marquis of Osorno (Cronista Rey de Armas de Castilla y Le\u00f3n. 1796\nFile:Arms of James O\u2019Higgins Norman.png|Coat of Arms [[James O'Higgins Norman|Dr. James O'Higgins Norman]] (Cronista Rey de Armas de Castilla y Le\u00f3n 2011).\n</gallery>\n\nThe earliest known coat of arms was recorded in 1724 by [[John Higgins of Montoge|Sir John Higgins Bt]] of Montoge with Sir James Terry, Athlone Herald in the Court of James II at St. Germaine. Sir John Higgins's branch of the family moved to Limerick after they lost their lands at Monteige in Sligo and eventually relocated in France and later in Spain where John Higgins was knighted and became personal physician to the King of Spain.\n\nThe descent of the Arms of Shean Duff O'Higgins, Baron of Ballynary were recorded in the Office of Ulster King of Arms in 1788 having existed for at least the previous 200 years.<ref>Genealogical Office, Dublin MS 165. p. 396-399.</ref> and were later recorded in the same year with the Cronista Rey de Armas in Madrid eventually descending to Thomas O'Higgins of Cheshire.<ref>The National Genealogical Office (Dublin), MS 165. p. 396-399.</ref><ref>Archivo del cronista de armas de Castilla y Le\u00f3n, Registrada al N\u00famero 31 del a\u00f1o 2011.</ref>\n\nIn 1788, Don Ambrose O'Higgins obtained a certificate of descent and the right to use the Ballynary Arms with due difference from Ulster King of Arms (Kingdom of Ireland) and subsequently received a grant from the Cronista Rey de Armas (Kingdom of Spain).<ref>Genealogical Office, Dublin MS 165. p. 396-399.</ref> His Coat of Arms was then adopted in 1796 as the official emblem of the city of Osorno in Chile after which he had been ennobled as Marquis of Osorno.\n\n[[James O'Higgins Norman|Dr. James O'Higgins Norman]] recorded Arms in 2011 with the Cronista Rey de Armas de Castilla y Le\u00f3n before being admitted as a Caballero in La Casa Troncal de los Doce Linajes de Soria.<ref>Qued\u00f3 Inscrito en el Libro General de Linajes, Libro I, Asiento N\u00b0 82.</ref>\n\n==Fictional References==\nIn the TV episode of ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'' \"The Case of the Guilty Clients\" the Suspect is a South American from the Argentine named \"O'Higgins\" implying that she is a descendant of Don Bernardo O'Higgins\u2014although in fact Bernardo O'Higgins was a resident of Chile\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ohigginsclan.com/ The O'Higgins Clan, A Sept of the Royal House of O'Neill]\n* [http://www.theclansofireland.ie/ Finte na h\u00c9ireann ~ Clans of Ireland]\n\n{{Connachta}}\n{{Gaels}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ohiggins}}\n[[Category:Spanish noble families]]\n[[Category:Chilean nobility]]\n[[Category:U\u00ed N\u00e9ill]]\n", "name_user": "Helmardine", "label": "safe", "comment": "\"Sept\" linked to its article and superfluous preposition \"in\" removed.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/O%27Higgins_family"}
{"title_page": "Abe Carver", "text_new": "{{Infobox soap character\n| name           = Abe Carver\n| series         = Days of our Lives\n| portrayer      = [[James Reynolds (actor)|James Reynolds]]\n| first          = December 1981\n| last           = \n| years          = 1981\u2013present\n| cause          = \n| creator        = [[Pat Falken Smith]]\n| introducer     = [[Betty Corday]] and [[Al Rabin]]\n| classification = [[List of Days of Our Lives cast members#Main cast|Present; regular]]\n| image1         = James Reynolds as Abe Carver.png\n| alias          = Abe\n| occupation     = Former Mayor of Salem <br> Former Salem police commissioner <br> Former Chief of Police <br> Former Police officer \n| residence      = Salem, [[Illinois]]\n| parents        = {{unbulleted list|Benjamin Carver|Rita Carver}}\n| brothers       = {{unbulleted list|Theo Carver|Jonah Carver}}\n| sisters        = {{unbulleted list|Karen Carver}}\n| spouse         = [[Lexie Carver|Lexie Brooks]] (1989\u20132012)\n| sons           = {{unbulleted list|[[Brandon Walker]]|[[Theo Carver]]}}\n| daughters      = [[Lani Price]] \n| grandchildren  = David Abraham Grant\n| grandparents   =\n| aunts/uncles   =\n| cousins        =\n| nephews        = Jett Carver\n}}\n\n'''Abraham Washington Carver''' is a [[fictional character]] on the long-running American [[soap opera]] ''[[Days of Our Lives]]''. Actor [[James Reynolds (actor)|James Reynolds]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soapoperadigest.com/actors/jamesreynolds/index.html |title=James Reynolds - Days Of Our Lives - Soap Opera Digest and Weekly |publisher=Soapoperadigest.com |date= |accessdate=2010-05-29 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> has played the character since he originated it on the series in December 1981, and is currently the fifth longest serving actor on the show. The role is one of the [[list of longest-serving soap opera actors#United States|longest-running]] [[African American]] characters in American soap operas. The character was created by head writer [[Pat Falken Smith]]. Abe is the widowed husband of [[Lexie Carver]], daughter of international crime lord, [[Stefano DiMera]]. He is the father of [[Brandon Walker]], [[Theo Carver]] and [[Lani Price]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbc.com/days-of-our-lives/bios/james-reynolds/ |title=Days of our Lives - Bios - James Reynolds as Abe Carver |publisher=Nbc.com |accessdate=2010-05-29 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618063306/http://www.nbc.com/days-of-our-lives/bios/james-reynolds/ |archivedate=2010-06-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Character history==\nAbe grows up in Salem with his brothers, Theo and Jonah and his sister, Karen. His passion for justice starts young, but amplifies after Theo is killed by a crooked police officer. Abe joins the Salem Police Department determined to rid the city of filth, including international crime lord, [[Stefano DiMera]].\n\nAbe is the police officer who investigates [[Anna Brady]]'s claim that she was sold into white slavery. She reports the existence of her secret Swiss bank account to her husband, [[Roman Brady]].\n\nHe has a relationship with a woman named Nikki Wade, but this is cut short after he stands her up at a d\u00e9butante ball in favor of heading up a drug bust. He was also in two short-lived relationships with Dr. [[Valerie Grant]] and singer Tamara Price, with whom he fathered a daughter [[Lani Price]]. Before Abe's promotion to police chief, he meets and marries [[Lexie Carver|Alexandra (Lexie) Brooks]]. Just after their marriage, Lexie searches through Aremid's files for her adoption records. She finds out that her aunt Frankie Brooks ([[Celeste Perrault]]) is actually her mother and that her father is [[Stefano DiMera]]. Conflict has risen many times in Abe and Lexie's marriage due to the presence of Stefano in their life.\n\nHis next major storyline involves the Aremid wedding of [[Peter Blake (Days of Our Lives)|Peter Blake]] and [[Jennifer Deveraux]]. Abe is caught up in the investigation of [[Tony DiMera]]'s murder. Abe and Lexi go to Paris to find [[Marlena Evans]] when Stefano kidnapped her. They end up finding and saving Marlena and catching Stefano but are unable to prosecute him, because only Stefano has a drug that can save Roman's life. Abe, Lexi, and [[John Black (Days of our Lives)|John Black]] help break Stefano out of jail and later he is pardoned for his crimes after returning to Salem with the drug Roman needed.\n\nLater, Abe and Lexie adopt baby Isaac, thinking he is the child of DiMera henchman [[Wilhelm Rolf]]. Isaac is actually the son of [[Bo Brady]] and [[Hope Brady]] who was switched at birth by Stefano. Abe is later appalled to learn that Lexie knew of the switch, but hides the truth from him. Abe files for divorce but after Lexie helps Hope, Brady and her son Zack, Lexie and Abe reconcile.\n\nShortly after, [[Brandon Walker]] comes to Salem with a deep hatred of Abe. Lexie sleeps with Brandon in a weak moment and becomes pregnant, unsure if Abe or Brandon is the father. It is revealed Abe is the father and Lexie and Abe reconcile for good. Brandon's presence causes issues for Abe until it is revealed that Brandon is Abe's illegitimate son with [[Fay Walker]]. After some time, Abe and Brandon embrace each other as family, and have since had a good relationship.\n\nAbe is shot dead on the day of Theo's christening. He is the first victim of the 2003 Salem serial killer. Months later he turns up on a remote tropical island, (melaswen/newsalem) which is a complete replica of Salem. Although his \"ghost\" started appearing to Celeste and Lexie while he was supposedly dead, (this was not explained). He works together with Roman and the others and got off the island. Abe is reunited with Lexie and Theo but goes blind and learns he is impotent. His anger shines through and he becomes paranoid that Lexie is cheating. Eventually, Abe's eyesight is restored but an anonymous note leads him to a motel where he finds Lexie having sex with his protege Salem Police officer [[Tek Kramer]]. Their marriage is in turmoil for a while until Abe uses Lexie in the investigation of her half-brother [[EJ DiMera]], then Abe falls back in love with her. They stay together until Lexie disappeared on December 29, 2006.\n\nHis eyesight starts deteriorate again and he undergoes a second retina transplant. At the same time, Lexie is found in the tunnels under Doug's Place and the DiMera mansion, where [[Andre DiMera]] has kept her all these months against her will. The transplant successful, Abe has returned to work as the Commissioner of the Salem Police Department. In the fall of 2010 Abe returned full-time to the screen. He began investigating the murders of the people of Salem, because he did not want anyone going through what he already had. However, the tables may turn on him when Stefano decided that he was going to frame Abe for the murders. In June 2012, Lexie, who had cancer, died peacefully in Abe's arms.\n\n== Cultural impact ==\n[[James Reynolds (actor)|James Reynolds]]' portrayal of Abe Carver since 1981 has made Abe the longest-running African American character in American [[soap opera]] history.<ref name=\"TV Guide\">{{cite news |title= The Killer Strikes (''TV Guide'', October 4\u201310, 2003)|publisher=[[TV Guide]]}}</ref>  Having logged more hours on television than most actors, Reynolds is also a humanitarian<ref>Detroit news interview with James Reynolds [http://www.detnews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20071206/LIFESTYLE05/712060391/1042/LIFESTYLE05] December 6, 2007.</ref> and his work on ''Days of our Lives'' helps continue his work. For his role as Abe Carver, James Reynolds earned a [[Daytime Emmy Award]] nomination for Outstanding Supporting Actor in 2004, and won the award for [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actor]] in 2018.\n\n{{quote|''Abe was a minority character of tremendous integrity who was not working for somebody else. He was in charge\u2014and that meant a lot to the African American audience. It had real impact.''|James Reynolds<ref name=\"TV Guide\"/> }}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links ==\n*[http://soapcentral.com/days/whoswho/abraham.php Abe Carver profile - SoapCentral.com]\n\n{{Days of Our Lives}}\n{{Days of our Lives characters|present}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carver, Abe}}\n[[Category:Days of Our Lives characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional African-American people]]\n[[Category:Fictional mayors]]\n[[Category:Fictional American police officers]]\n[[Category:Fictional police commissioners]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 1981]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox soap character\n| name           = Abe Carver\n| series         = Days of our Lives\n| portrayer      = [[James Reynolds (actor)|James Reynolds]]\n| first          = October 29, 1981\n| last           = \n| years          = 1981\u2013\n| cause          = \n| creator        = [[Pat Falken Smith]]\n| introducer     = [[Betty Corday]] and [[Al Rabin]]\n| classification = [[List of Days of Our Lives cast members#Main cast|Present; regular]]\n| image1         = James Reynolds as Abe Carver.png\n| alias          = Abe\n| occupation     = Former Mayor of Salem <br> Former Salem police commissioner <br> Former Chief of Police <br> Former Police officer \n| residence      = Salem, [[Illinois]]\n| parents        = {{unbulleted list|Benjamin Carver|Rita Carver}}\n| brothers       = {{unbulleted list|Theo Carver|Jonah Carver}}\n| sisters        = {{unbulleted list|Karen Carver}}\n| spouse         = [[Lexie Carver|Lexie Brooks]] (1989\u20132012)\n| sons           = {{unbulleted list|[[Brandon Walker]]|[[Theo Carver]]}}\n| daughters      = [[Lani Price]] \n| grandchildren  = David Abraham Grant\n| grandparents   =\n| aunts/uncles   =\n| cousins        =\n| nephews        = Jett Carver\n}}\n\n'''Abraham Washington Carver''' is a [[fictional character]] on the long-running American [[soap opera]] ''[[Days of Our Lives]]''. Actor [[James Reynolds (actor)|James Reynolds]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soapoperadigest.com/actors/jamesreynolds/index.html |title=James Reynolds - Days Of Our Lives - Soap Opera Digest and Weekly |publisher=Soapoperadigest.com |date= |accessdate=2010-05-29 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> has played the character since he originated it on the series in 1981, and is currently the fifth longest serving actor on the show. The role is one of the [[list of longest-serving soap opera actors#United States|longest-running]] [[African American]] characters in American soap operas. The character was created by head writer [[Pat Falken Smith]]. Abe is the widowed husband of [[Lexie Carver]], daughter of international crime lord, [[Stefano DiMera]]. He is the father of [[Brandon Walker]], [[Theo Carver]] and [[Lani Price]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbc.com/days-of-our-lives/bios/james-reynolds/ |title=Days of our Lives - Bios - James Reynolds as Abe Carver |publisher=Nbc.com |accessdate=2010-05-29 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618063306/http://www.nbc.com/days-of-our-lives/bios/james-reynolds/ |archivedate=2010-06-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Character history==\nAbe grows up in Salem with his brothers, Theo and Jonah and his sister, Karen. His passion for justice starts young, but amplifies after Theo is killed by a crooked police officer. Abe joins the Salem Police Department determined to rid the city of filth, including international crime lord, [[Stefano DiMera]].\n\nAbe is the police officer who investigates [[Anna Brady]]'s claim that she was sold into white slavery. She reports the existence of her secret Swiss bank account to her husband, [[Roman Brady]].\n\nHe has a relationship with a woman named Nikki Wade, but this is cut short after he stands her up at a d\u00e9butante ball in favor of heading up a drug bust. He was also in two short-lived relationships with Dr. [[Valerie Grant]] and singer Tamara Price, with whom he fathered a daughter [[Lani Price]]. Before Abe's promotion to police chief, he meets and marries [[Lexie Carver|Alexandra (Lexie) Brooks]]. Just after their marriage, Lexie searches through Aremid's files for her adoption records. She finds out that her aunt Frankie Brooks ([[Celeste Perrault]]) is actually her mother and that her father is [[Stefano DiMera]]. Conflict has risen many times in Abe and Lexie's marriage due to the presence of Stefano in their life.\n\nHis next major storyline involves the Aremid wedding of [[Peter Blake (Days of Our Lives)|Peter Blake]] and [[Jennifer Deveraux]]. Abe is caught up in the investigation of [[Tony DiMera]]'s murder. Abe and Lexi go to Paris to find [[Marlena Evans]] when Stefano kidnapped her. They end up finding and saving Marlena and catching Stefano but are unable to prosecute him, because only Stefano has a drug that can save Roman's life. Abe, Lexi, and [[John Black (Days of our Lives)|John Black]] help break Stefano out of jail and later he is pardoned for his crimes after returning to Salem with the drug Roman needed.\n\nLater, Abe and Lexie adopt baby Isaac, thinking he is the child of DiMera henchman [[Wilhelm Rolf]]. Isaac is actually the son of [[Bo Brady]] and [[Hope Brady]] who was switched at birth by Stefano. Abe is later appalled to learn that Lexie knew of the switch, but hides the truth from him. Abe files for divorce but after Lexie helps Hope, Brady and her son Zack, Lexie and Abe reconcile.\n\nShortly after, [[Brandon Walker]] comes to Salem with a deep hatred of Abe. Lexie sleeps with Brandon in a weak moment and becomes pregnant, unsure if Abe or Brandon is the father. It is revealed Abe is the father and Lexie and Abe reconcile for good. Brandon's presence causes issues for Abe until it is revealed that Brandon is Abe's illegitimate son with [[Fay Walker]]. After some time, Abe and Brandon embrace each other as family, and have since had a good relationship.\n\nAbe is shot dead on the day of Theo's christening. He is the first victim of the 2003 Salem serial killer. Months later he turns up on a remote tropical island, (melaswen/newsalem) which is a complete replica of Salem. Although his \"ghost\" started appearing to Celeste and Lexie while he was supposedly dead, (this was not explained). He works together with Roman and the others and got off the island. Abe is reunited with Lexie and Theo but goes blind and learns he is impotent. His anger shines through and he becomes paranoid that Lexie is cheating. Eventually, Abe's eyesight is restored but an anonymous note leads him to a motel where he finds Lexie having sex with his protege Salem Police officer [[Tek Kramer]]. Their marriage is in turmoil for a while until Abe uses Lexie in the investigation of her half-brother [[EJ DiMera]], then Abe falls back in love with her. They stay together until Lexie disappeared on December 29, 2006.\n\nHis eyesight starts deteriorate again and he undergoes a second retina transplant. At the same time, Lexie is found in the tunnels under Doug's Place and the DiMera mansion, where [[Andre DiMera]] has kept her all these months against her will. The transplant successful, Abe has returned to work as the Commissioner of the Salem Police Department. In the fall of 2010 Abe returned full-time to the screen. He began investigating the murders of the people of Salem, because he did not want anyone going through what he already had. However, the tables may turn on him when Stefano decided that he was going to frame Abe for the murders. In June 2012, Lexie, who had cancer, died peacefully in Abe's arms.\n\n== Cultural impact ==\n[[James Reynolds (actor)|James Reynolds]]' portrayal of Abe Carver since 1981 has made Abe the longest-running African American character in American [[soap opera]] history.<ref name=\"TV Guide\">{{cite news |title= The Killer Strikes (''TV Guide'', October 4\u201310, 2003)|publisher=[[TV Guide]]}}</ref>  Having logged more hours on television than most actors, Reynolds is also a humanitarian<ref>Detroit news interview with James Reynolds [http://www.detnews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20071206/LIFESTYLE05/712060391/1042/LIFESTYLE05] December 6, 2007.</ref> and his work on ''Days of our Lives'' helps continue his work. For his role as Abe Carver, James Reynolds earned a [[Daytime Emmy Award]] nomination for Outstanding Supporting Actor in 2004, and won the award for [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actor]] in 2018.\n\n{{quote|''Abe was a minority character of tremendous integrity who was not working for somebody else. He was in charge\u2014and that meant a lot to the African American audience. It had real impact.''|James Reynolds<ref name=\"TV Guide\"/> }}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links ==\n*[http://soapcentral.com/days/whoswho/abraham.php Abe Carver profile - SoapCentral.com]\n\n{{Days of Our Lives}}\n{{Days of our Lives characters|present}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carver, Abe}}\n[[Category:Days of Our Lives characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional African-American people]]\n[[Category:Fictional mayors]]\n[[Category:Fictional American police officers]]\n[[Category:Fictional police commissioners]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 1981]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n", "name_user": "2a01:e34:ef60:a6b0:6c39:6708:7e92:8002", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Abe Carver)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abe_Carver"}
